<HEAD>U.S. Bishops Back Mediation Effort by Panamanian Colleague</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with McGrath suspending mediation
effort.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops have lent moral support for Archbishop <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON>'s now-suspended offer to mediate talks between the Panamanian government and the opposition which has been trying to oust Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. A letter of support from the American bishops to <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON>, the archbishop of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, was released on Thursday, just hours before <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON> announced he was suspending the mediation effort. <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON> said he was withdrawing his offer because: opposition groups refused to talk to the government until it showed a willingness to discuss <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s departure; <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> had n't offered explicit backing of the initiative in writing; and there were no assurances that the four international leaders who proposed the talks could be present. Archbishop <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> May </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION>, in the letter to <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON>, said: `` The voice of the church in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> has been clear and consistent, denouncing the instances of civic corruption and state violence that have tragically become so much a part of recent news reports.'' The letter was made public Thursday. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON>, the acting president of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, said his government agreed to talks mediated by the church. But the opposition insists on assurances that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is willing to step down and leave the country. `` I write to express our full support and ecclesial solidarity with you, your fellow bishops and all the suffering people of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' May said in his letter to <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON>. He added that `` we continue to urge our own national leaders to exercise the greatest care in balancing pursuit of legitimate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interests in the region with the essential quest for a peaceful and just settlement of this crisis.'''
