<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 61-year-old college professor, infatuated with the lilting Scottish voice recording of his bank's automated teller, finally got to meet the woman of his cash machine dreams. `` I guess the first thing I should say is, ` Your transaction is processing,''' said <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Masterson </PERSON>, a 29-year-old British radio talk-show host, on meeting <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferry </PERSON> after a trans-Atlantic flight Wednesday. The encounter was arranged by the <ORGANIZATION> Decatur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Review's editors, who tracked down Ms. <PERSON> Masterson </PERSON> after Ferry, an education professor, wrote a Feb. 4 newspaper column about his `` infatuation with the talking teller. `` She is very sweet, she is very charming,'' Ferry said later. `` She is a person I'd very much like to have for a friend.'' `` I think he's smashing,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Masterson </PERSON>. `` He's what I call wacky, because he's got that wacky sense of humor.'' Ferry's wife, <PERSON> Carol </PERSON>, said she first heard Ms. <PERSON> Masterson </PERSON>'s voice last weekend. Before Wednesday's meeting, Mrs. Ferry asked, `` How would anyone feel if a young sexy person wants to meet your husband?'' Ms. <PERSON> Masterson </PERSON>, who is single, made the teller-machine recording three years ago in <LOCATION> Dundee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, for <ORGANIZATION> NCR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. `` I thought she was charming,'' Mrs. Ferry said. `` I've thoroughly enjoyed this. Ms. <PERSON> Masterson </PERSON> returns to <LOCATION> Britian </LOCATION> on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After a short-lived stint as a party animal, Bullwinkle the moose has come home to roost atop the pizza palace from which he was moosenapped seven months ago. As you'll recall, in our our last episode, the 40-foot inflatable effigy of Rocket J. Squirrel's best buddy vanished from the roof of Bullwinkle's <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION>' n Fun Restaurant in August. The restaurant, eager to get its $ 17,000 mascot back, offered the culprits free pizza for a year for the 300-pound moose on the loose. Suspicion soon focused on the notorious spy <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Badenov </PERSON> and his companion, <PERSON> Natasha </PERSON>. Finally, on April Fool's Day a deflated Bullwinkle was unceremoniously deposited in the parking lot of the eatery along with a 2-by-3-foot note. `` Hey guys! The moose is no longer loose. He wanted to party with us so we brought him along. It turns out he was too wild for us! Please keep an eye on him, he's dangerous! April Fools, Class of'88. `` P.S. Sorry.'' Police, who say the case is closed, believe the moose's abductors may have been students from <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clara </LOCATION> High who decided to give back Bullwinkle after they realized what it was worth The restaurant manager, however, ca n't just laugh it off, having ordered a replacement moose for the roof. Stay tuned for the next episode: `` Wedding Bells For Bullwinkle?'' or `` Hey, Bub, This Roof Ai n't Big Enough For Both of Us!''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ULITHI ATOLL, Yap (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While many people are griping about having to pay a quarter to mail a letter, the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has given the 700 residents of this <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> island chain something to smile about. <LOCATION> Ulithi </LOCATION> Atoll finally has its own Zip Code. The atoll, best known as the site from where the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> launched its World War II invasions of <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> and Iwo Jima, is part of Yap State in the <LOCATION> Federated </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Micronesia </LOCATION>, a former trust territory that holds a compact of free association with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. It is about 1,200 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Ulithi </LOCATION> Atoll includes dozens of islands, but people live on just four of them. Only about 700 people live here now, but in September 1944 hundreds of warships gathered in the atoll's sheltered lagoon to prepare for the 1945 invasions of <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> and Iwo Jima. The <LOCATION> Ulithi </LOCATION> rendezvous was the largest <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> task force assembled during the war. A post office opened here in March to distribute mail flown in from <LOCATION> Colonia </LOCATION>, the island's governmental seat about 100 miles east of <LOCATION> Ulithi </LOCATION>. The postal address is <LOCATION> Ulithi </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Yap </PERSON>, FM 96943.
