<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Drugs,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three of Four Reputed Drug Barons Sought in Camerena Case now
Jailed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With the spiriting away of <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Matta </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> to an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> prison, three of four reputed drug barons sought in the killing of an American drug agent are behind bars. The Feb. 7, 1985 kidnapping of <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON>, a special agent of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, put the spotlight on the immense power and wealth accumulated by drug traffickers in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The bodies of <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavala </PERSON> <PERSON> Avelar </PERSON> were found March 5, 1985. <PERSON> Zavala </PERSON> <PERSON> Avelar </PERSON> was a Mexican pilot who worked with <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> in anti-narcotics programs from their base in <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s second-largest city. During the hunt for <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> and then for his killers, an outline of a powerful drug organization became clear. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials called the organization <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Familia </ORGANIZATION> _ the Family. Talk of Mexican cooperation in anti-drug programs was replaced in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> by charges of widespread corruption. The narcotics issue has remained a major sticking point in U.S.-Mexican relations. The four top men in the illicit drug trade were said to be Ernesto `` <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Neto </PERSON>'' <PERSON> Fonseca </PERSON>, reportedly the organization's leader; <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>, <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Matta </PERSON>. <PERSON> Matta </PERSON> is a Honduran citizen and the others are Mexican. Although they were not all accused of direct participation, their organization that was believed responsible for ordering <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON>'s murder. `` These people were all involved in a drug trafficking organization,'' <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Graves </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fonseca </PERSON> were taken into custody in spring 1985 and remain imprisoned, charged in <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON>'s murder. <PERSON> Matta </PERSON> was picked up Tuesday in a pre-dawn helicopter police raid at his home in <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>, the Honduran capital, and put on a flight out of the country without a passport. Honduran legislators angrily called the incident a `` kidnapping'' and the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> started an investigation of the procedures used. The exploits of <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON> in particular, his rise from poverty to vast wealth, have given him almost a folk hero status in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Two escape tunnels were discovered last fall near his prison, one almost complete. <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON> remains at large. No warrant has been issued for him in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Reports surface from time to time that he dined with a governor or made some other public appearace. `` There are more than 50 people imprisoned,'' <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Flores </PERSON>, spokesman for the federal attorney general's office, said Wednesday when asked for a status report on the <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> case. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> count is 63 people in custody in the case, a small number of them sentenced. `` We expect the Mexican judicial system to find these people guilty. We expect convictions, given the overwhelming evidence against them,'' <PERSON> Graves </PERSON> said. In January, a federal grand jury in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> indicted nine people, including <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>, on charges stemming from the <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> kidnap and murder. The attorney general's office said: `` The respective trials will continue to develop before the Mexican jurisdictional bodies, independent of whatever procedure is opened in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or in third countries.'' Attorney General <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> said in a February interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that recriminations between <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> over which one is lagging in the drug trade war are not in the interest of either country. `` We find it difficult to accept the opinion held in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of what really goes on in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` The border is not a border between black and white, good and evil. It is a border between countries.''
