<HEAD>TV Station Urging Viewers To Take 15-Minute Break</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A television station is urging its viewers to take a 15-minute break from watching. As part of its `` For Kids' Sake'' campaign, <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>'s KDKA-TV will present a special half-hour edition of `` Story Break'' at 1 p.m. on Saturday, April 16. The program's hosts will read children's stories for the first 15 minutes, then a title slide will appear reading, `` Right now, share a story with the child in your life. For kids' sake.'' `` We've never done anything like this,'' said General Manager <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Berwanger </PERSON>. `` It's our job to air the best and most appropriate programming for our viewers, and we believe this 15-minute break from TV will be a very special time for anyone watching with kids.'' The station also plans to broadcast public service spots in place of local advertisements during the day.
