<HEAD>Teacher With AIDS Continues Work While Fighting Illness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A teacher who won a landmark court decision allowing him to continue teaching despite suffering from AIDS says his life has almost returned to normal even though his body is weakening. `` There are some days that I think nothing is wrong, and there are other times when I know very well something is, uh, lurking in my body,'' <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Chalk </PERSON> said in an interview published Wednesday in the <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilot </ORGANIZATION>. Chalk, a vocational counselor for hearing-impaired students at <ORGANIZATION> Venado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>, filed a lawsuit against the <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> last year when officials reassigned him to a desk job after learning he had AIDS. In November, the 9th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled in what is believed to have been the nation's first such AIDS discrimination case, saying he could not be barred from the classroom. Chalk, 43, said he never anticipated the publicity the case generated, which forced his parents to tell their friends that their only son was homosexual, something they had known for years. Chalk said he felt sorry for himself at first. `` I'm not nor ever have been a very sexually active kind of person,'' said Chalk, who lives in <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> with a companion of six years. `` I thought, ` Other people are out there doing a lot more than I am. They would make better subjects.' But you ca n't go through life dealing with ` Why me's?''' But now, he's motivated to remain in the classroom, although he weighs 130 pounds, down from 160, and is plagued by a chronic sinus infection, he said. Chalk has trimmed his work week to three days so he wo n't weaken. `` There are people who want to say, ` See? Knew you could n't do it,''' he said. Chalk said he listens to motivational tapes and uses visual imagery in fighting AIDS, and has given up casual cocaine use and alcohol. `` I'm trying to create as much health in my life and my body as possible,'' he said.
</TEXT>
