<HEAD>Dissident Teacher Sues Catholic University</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A civil court will hear the Rev. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>'s complaints that <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> illegally ousted him from his teaching post as a result of <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> displeasure with his theology. <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>, a prominent professor of theology, is suing the university for breach of contract. Superior Court Judge <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beaudin </PERSON> on Tuesday rejected the university's claim that <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>'s suspension was under church law and therefore is immune to civil court review. `` This court finds the university's position without merit,'' <PERSON> Beaudin </PERSON> said in a written order denying a motion by the university for dismissal of the suit. `` Professor <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>'s claim is based on an employment contract governed by the civil law and contract principles of the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Beaudin </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the university, said `` we do n't comment on ongoing litigation. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>, in 1986, declared <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> unfit to teach as a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> theologian because of his dissenting views on sexual issues. He had expressed the view that contraception and sterilization `` are not intrinsically evil,'' and that `` in certain circumstances,'' the church should allow divorce. He has also said that for a `` genuine homosexual, homosexual acts in the context of a loving relationship striving for permanency can in a certain sense be objectively and morally acceptable.'' Archbishop <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hickey </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, the ex-officio chancellor of <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, suspended <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> from all teaching at the university last January. <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>, who now teaches at <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, challenged the suspension in court as a breach of university bylaws and his contract. The school asked dismissal of the suit, principally on the ground that court interference in canon law is barred by the freedom of religion clause in the Constitution. <PERSON> Beaudine </PERSON> said he did not dispute the school's contention that the court lacks authority `` to review and examine the university's interpretation and application of canon law'' and that his ruling applied only to <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>'s academic tenure and employment contract In a statement released by his lawyers, <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> said he is not asking the church `` to do or change anything in its decision concerning me. I am asking the court to ensure that a civilly incorporated university follow its own bylaws and its contract with me.''
