<FIRST>r w PM-HousingSurvey     04-07 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing Survey,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Says Majority Of Americans Would Support More Housing
Programs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: R L Associates in 7th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A non-profit housing group says its new poll shows that people are willing to pay higher taxes to ensure that poor and middle-class Americans get decent, affordable housing. `` There's no doubt the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people support programs to expand home ownership, help low-income renters and aid the homeless,'' <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Atlas </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` And contrary to the conventional wisdom, they're willing to pay. The poll found that most Americans believe there is a lack of affordable housing for the poor and middle class. Most of those surveyed said they would pay an extra $ 10 to $ 15 a month in taxes for programs to aid the homeless, the elderly and middle-class families unable to make down payments to buy houses. The survey also found that nearly 75 percent of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> public believes a presidential candidate who advocates housing programs for middle-and working-class families `` understands the real needs in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' The vast majority _ 86 percent _ said they feel homelessness is `` a national disgrace'' and an even higher percentage _ 93 percent _ said homelessness is an important problem that should be eliminated. `` Politically, a presidential candidate who guarantees every American a decent affordable home might have a new home himself _ on <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Atlas </PERSON> said. The report, `` A Status Report On The American Dream: How the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> View </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Problems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Programs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION>,'' was based on polling by <ORGANIZATION> R </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> L </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>. The firm interviewed 1,001 adults by telephone during February and March. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Rappaport </PERSON>, spokesman for the polling firm, said the margin of error is plus or minus 4 percentage points. In general, the survey found that at least two-thirds of those questioned support programs to finance renovations in housing for the elderly, to rehabilitate old and vacant buildings, to establish a homeless prevention program to help those close to eviction for financial reasons, and to begin a mortgage assistance program to help with downpayments. On the issue of higher taxes to support housing programs, 66 percent said they would be willing to spend $ 10 a month more, while 55 percent said they would agree to pay $ 15 a month more. The poll also found that half of those surveyed said they would be more likely to vote for a candidate who supports `` a package of housing programs,'' while only 6 percent said they would be less likely to support such a candidate. Seventy-four percent said they believe a presidential candidate who advocates housing programs for middle - and working-class families `` understands the real needs in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` The <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people are increasingly aware that this nation faces a housing problem,'' <PERSON> Atlas </PERSON> said. `` Our poll shows that <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> understand that it's hard to find affordable housing and that Americans are shocked at homelessness.'' He said the housing institute, which describes itself as a representative of housing interests for moderate - and low-income families, can not lobby <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for housing programs because of its non-profit status It does plan to provide its poll data to other groups that can promote the programs. <PERSON> Atlas </PERSON> said spending authority for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> dropped 57 percent from 1980 to 1987, from $ 35.7 billion a year to $ 15.2 billion. And he said that the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> budget last year represented 1 percent of the federal budget.
