<FIRST>r a PM-HensonBurial     04-07 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Henson Burial,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Explorer Given Full Recognition 79 Years Later</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They were together at the discovery of the North Pole in 1909. But in death, <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> was in a shared grave in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> while Adm. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peary </PERSON> was honored at <ORGANIZATION> Arlington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cemetery </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> was black, and for that reason, said supporter Dr. <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Counter </PERSON>, `` he was denied proper recognition because of the racial attitudes of his time.'' On Wednesday, 79 years to the day after <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> planted the American flag on the North Pole, the two explorers were reunited as <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>'s remains and those of his wife were reinterred with full military honors at <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>. `` Now, finally, <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Peary </PERSON> can talk about old days out there,'' a part-Eskimo grandson, <PERSON> Qitdlaq </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Qaanaaq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION>, said through a translator _ his cousin <PERSON> Navarana </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> _ at a news conference following the ceremony. `` I have waited for this day for over 30 years,'' <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>'s great niece, <PERSON> Olive </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> <PERSON> Fulton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Roxbury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, told the gathering of about 100 relatives and admirers at the windswept hilltop burial site. Recalling that she was expelled from school because she had written a paper about <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> when her assignment had been to write about a hero, Ms. <PERSON> Fulton </PERSON> said: `` Finally, my uncle is given his place in history.'' Counter said the reinterment of <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>, was `` long overdue recognition for our hero ... -LRB- that would -RRB- right a tragic wrong.'' `` Welcome home, <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>,'' he said. `` Welcome home to a new day in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. ... May your presence here inspire generations of explorers.'' Last October, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> approved Counter's petition to allow <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>'s remains to be reinterred at <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>. He had been buried in 1955 in <LOCATION> Woodlawn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cemetery </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Among those honoring <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> at the ceremony were Gen. <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckton </PERSON> of the White House military office, who conveyed greetings from <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, the chairman and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which publishes Ebony and Jet magazines; Col. <PERSON> Guion </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bluford </PERSON>, the first black astronaut; and <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Height </PERSON>, the president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Negro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION>. Counter, an associate professor of neurophysiology at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> who previously had brought together <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>'s and <PERSON> Peary </PERSON>'s part-Eskimo offspring, said <PERSON> Peary </PERSON> had insisted before his own death in 1920 that <PERSON> Henson <