<HEAD>Bush Bumps Up Against Fund-Raising Limit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign treasury is filled to the brim and campaign officials say the biggest worry now is guarding against spending more than the $ 27 million pre-convention limit set by federal election law. The vice president's campaign has already spent all but $ 4 million of that cap, with more than four months yet to go to the Republican convention this August, said campaign treasurer <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign hit the contribution limit on Wednesday, reporting that it had raised a total of $ 30 million, including $ 22.5 million in direct contributions and commitments for another $ 7.5 million in federal matching funds. This total includes about $ 3 million earmarked for legal and accounting expenses which are exempt from the $ 27 million-limit. `` The challenge is to take that $ 4 million we have left and maximize it so that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> gets the best benefit out of that he can,'' said the campaign official, who is not related to candidate <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` I'm thrilled,'' <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in an interview. `` As far as this process is concerned, we're finished.'' The cap applies to both raising funds and spending them. <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> contender <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> was the first candidate to actually bump up against the spending ceiling. The former televison evangelist said after the costly Super Tuesday contests on March 8 that he was within $ 2 million of the spending cap. Since then he has laid off staff and dropped an extensive television marketing operation. Though he has only 17 delegates to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s 888, he remains in the race and is spending the rest of his money primarily on personal travel. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said staying within the limits is far easier because <PERSON> Bush </P