<HEAD>Judge Says Prosecution Plan For Release Of Documents Too
Cumbersome</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The judge in the Iran-Contra case says he wants to streamline procedures for pre-trial disclosure of 150,000 pages of classified documents to the four defendants. Signaling his intention to move the case to trial as quickly as possible, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> on Wednesday rejected independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s proposal to prevent unauthorized disclosure of the classified material as too cumbersome. The proposed procedure for three months of pre-trial discovery `` appears to be far too complex, lacks definite time restrictions and creates undue obstacles to the fair and expeditious disposition of this case,'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said in a brief opinion. At a hearing scheduled for next Tuesday, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said he `` intends to determine the timing of discovery disclosures in relation to a realistic trial date.'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said he will ask <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> to say which documents `` will be made available immediately'' to the defense. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> had said in pleadings filed Monday that he planned to turn over the material to the defendants in the next three months. The judge also said he wants to set a deadline this month for completion of an interagency review of the documents, which <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> says `` describe in detail some of the nation's most carefully held secrets about its foreign policy, its intelligence activities and its covert activities.'' An objection to <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s plan was filed by defense lawyers for former national security adviser <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>, Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and arms dealers <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>. The four are accused of conspiring to illegally divert proceeds from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to the Nicaraguan rebels. Among elements of the security plan the defense found objectionable was a requirement that the defendants and their lawyers answer detailed government questionnaires in order to obtain security clearances to review the documents. Requiring the defendants to answer detailed questions about their travel, aliases, corporate affiliations `` and other matters potentially at issue in the case'' could violate their Fifth Amendment protection against self-incrimination, the defense said. The joint opposition also noted that North and <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> had previously had access to many of the documents when they worked at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said `` it will be necessary to frame a more limited protective order fashioned to the nature of this case, which in essence alleges a course of conduct carried out using classified materials in classified channels from a highly classified site.''
