<HEAD>New Laws Urged For Those Who Act To Spread AIDS Infection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The need to protect against people with the AIDS virus who knowingly try to spread the disease must be balanced against the need to protect individual rights, a public health expert told the White House AIDS commission. `` An isolation statute could require a due process determination that a viral carrier is unwilling or unable to refrain from engaging in conduct likely to spread the disease,'' <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gostin </PERSON> testified Wednesday before the panel. `` Constitutionally allowable isolation would not focus on a person's status as having an infection or a disease, but upon his or her behavior leading to transmission,'' said <PERSON> Gostin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gostin </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Medicine and associate professor at the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, was among 28 witnesses appearing before the panel in two days of hearings this week. The commission, working toward a June 24 final report, has scheduled three more days of hearings later this month. A <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> prosecutor told the commission that existing laws are inadequate to deal with people who know they are infected with the virus and behave in a manner that could spread it to others. `` The citizens of this country deserve protection from being recklessly or intentionally targeted for exposure to this dreadful disease,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Flint </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, the elected prosecuting attorney in <LOCATION> Genesee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, explained his rationale for filing assault with intent to murder charges against a man infected with the virus who tried to spit on police after being arrested for drunken driving `` He fought with the arresting officers and, once lodged, kept spitting through the bars of his cell, taunting the officers and daring them to come closer so he ` could give them AIDS,''' said <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>. `` We filed ... under the theory that his expressed intention to communicate an incurable, terminal disease amounted to an intent to cause death,'' he explained. The court reduced the attempted murder charge to assault on an officer, partially on grounds there is insufficient evidence that the virus can be spread by spitting, said <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>. He said that although the `` percentage of AIDS carriers who will maliciously or irresponsibly place others at risk is largely speculative, this fact should not deter us from developing a legislative framework to control such conduct.''
