<SECOND>PM-Crash Tests,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peugeot Shows High Head-Injury Potential, NHTSA Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> says crash tests of nine 1988 vehicles show drivers of the Peugeot 505 GLS have the greatest chance of sustaining a head injury. A 35 mph crash of the four-door compact into a fixed barrier produced a head-injury criterion of 1701 on the driver, the highest recorded among this year's tests. The head-injury criterion is an index of the force experienced by occupants of the car, as measured by a test dummy. The passenger-side dummy recorded a head-injury criterion of 1457. The Peugeot results were among six released Wednesday by <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION>. The agency had tested three vehicles earlier in the year. The Toyota Corolla FX two-door hatchback, a subcompact, produced a head-injury criterion of 593 for the driver, and 397 for the passenger. The driver head-injury criterion was the least among the nine models tested this year. A second subcompact, the Toyota Tercel two-door hatchback, produced a head-injury criterion of 1005 for the driver and 398 for the passenger. In compact car crash tests, the <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> Maxima SE four-door produced a head-injury criteria of 907 for the driver and 861 for the passenger, and the <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> Le Mans two-door <PERSON> Aerocoupe </PERSON> produced head-injury criteria of 819 for the driver and 897 for the passenger. Wednesday's test results included one van, the <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vanagon </ORGANIZATION>, with head-injury criteria of 1320 for the driver and 899 for the passenger. Earlier, <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> had released test results on the 1988 <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> Taurus and Mercury Sable. The crash-test results are intended to help consumers compare vehicles when deciding which to buy, <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said. Only one vehicle of each model is tested, and further crash tests could produce different results, <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said. The 35 mph crash speed was 5 mph faster, or one-third more severe, than that specified by federal motor vehicle safety standards. The 30 mph standards permit a maximum head-injury criterion of 1000, and higher figures can be expected at the higher speed, <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said.
