<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two local Republicans riding with <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the vice presidential limousine were serving as a welcoming committee _ but <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wanted to talk business. `` If <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> wins this thing on the other side, you guys are going to have to help me in setting the record straight,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told them as his motorcade wound through narrow city streets from the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> station in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> End </LOCATION> to a political rally at <LOCATION> Faneuil </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hall </LOCATION>. The vice president was talking about <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who has a strong shot at facing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the general election next fall. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wanted to make sure he knows the full details of the governor's record, said state Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cellucci </PERSON>, who sat next to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Riding in the jump seat was state Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Locke </PERSON>, who along with <PERSON> Cellucci </PERSON> is co-chairman of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. `` If we can help you understand the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> philosophy, we will do that,'' <PERSON> Locke </PERSON> told <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. That conversation, as recalled by the two senators, occurred Feb. 24, two weeks before <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s Super Tuesday landslide. Since then, his principal rival, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, has bowed out. With the nomination virtually locked up, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is plotting strategy against the Democrats. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, whose treasury and organization far outstrip those of the other Democrats, has drawn by far the most attention. With three wins in a row under his belt _ in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> _ he is well positioned for the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> primary later this month. In addition, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is the only Democrat who competes well against <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in hypothetical matchups in recent public opinion polls. `` There's a perception within the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is in a strong position to win it,'' <PERSON> Cellucci </PERSON> said. `` We're compiling data that will indicate that the governor did not have much to do with the strong economy in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>.'' He maintained that military spending, tax cuts, a property tax limitation law and Reaganomics are responsible. `` We also want to be in a position where the vice president can demonstrate that <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is a liberal and he believes in big government,'' <PERSON> Cellucci </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think that's anything that's going to be too difficult to demonstrate. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Cellucci </PERSON> said, has been `` trying to move to the middle'' by touting his own tax reductions, his record of balancing budgets and his opposition to communist expansion in Central America. But <PERSON> Cellucci </PERSON> said, `` the change is so startling and dramatic that you have to question its sincerity.'' The intelligence-gathering effort on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is not limited to the material <PERSON> Locke </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cellucci </PERSON> can provide. The <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which looks into the background of all the Democratic candidates, has had a researcher assigned to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for nearly a year, according to <ORGANI