<TEXT>
 The Chateau of <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION>, the former royal palace where <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> XIV </PERSON> spent his honeymoon, will be renovated, the government said. `` The chateau, as it stands, is a discouraging site,'' said former culture minister <PERSON> Jean-Philippe </PERSON> <PERSON> Lecat </PERSON>, head of the renovation committee. The government announced Wednesday that the fortress will be renovated. Lecat proposed a five-year, $ 30 million plan to turn the picturesque complex into a cultural facility to accomodate about 400,000 visitors yearly. The castle currently receives about 30,000 visitors each year. Completed in 1370 by King <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> V </PERSON>, the castle originally was conceived as the cornerstone of a vast royal city he planned to control. Centuries later the young <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> XIV </PERSON> spent his honeymoon there but he preferred to live in <LOCATION> Fontainebleau </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Versailles </LOCATION>.
