<FIRST>r w PM-Pulitzer-Complaint     04-07 0823</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pulitzer-Complaint,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Wants Board To Reconsider Philadelphia Inquirer Pulitzer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> magazine is asking the <ORGANIZATION> Pulitzer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prize </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> to reconsider an award to The <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> Inquirer, saying the newspaper's prize-winning entry replicated earlier work by others including one of the magazine's reporters. Inquirer editors Wednesday denied the accusation by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> that reporter <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON> used an earlier article by <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> reporter <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> as a `` blueprint'' for his series on a secret Pentagon budget. <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON>'s series won a Pulitzer for national writing. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Naughton </PERSON>, Inquirer deputy managing editor, said, `` I think it's a cheap publicity stunt to call attention to the magazine.'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> editor, wrote Wednesday to the Pulitzer board, saying: `` We make no accusation of plagiarism, but by no account does the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> Inquirer series deserve a Pulitzer because <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON>'s reporting on the size and composition of the black budget plows no new journalistic ground.'' The weekly Journal, owned by Times-Mirror, does in-depth reporting on government and has a circulation of 5,000, mostly among government officials and journalists. An annual subscription costs $ 584. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, in an interview, said he did not complain about the <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON> articles when they first appeared because his publication is used to having its work lead to reporting by others, but usually with some credit given. The Inquirer articles, published in February 1987, do not mention the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>'s report nearly a year earlier. `` They could have avoided this if they had given some credit,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, `` but then they would not have won the Pulitzer.'' <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON>, who shared a 1982 Pulitzer for reporting for the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, said he wrote a sidebar to his articles citing <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> and describing how he analyzed the secret budget, `` but it was spiked because it was deemed too boring.'' <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON> said he does not write to win prizes and feared journalism would be hurt by what he said are false allegations. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pulitzer </PERSON> board secretary, said he had been informed of the complaint but had not yet read the letter requesting board action. `` Clearly any allegation of this kind, any complaint of this kind would be considered,'' said <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON>. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> wrote that <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON>'s story `` can only be read as a blatant and egregious case of building a news story according to someone else's blueprint: in this case, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>'s March 1, 1986, cover story, ` The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s Black Budget.''' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> told the board that several other news organizations also had earlier written about the money used to underwrite secret defense research and unpublicized aspects of the arms buildup. He enclosed copies of the Journal and Inquirer stories, along with a <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> article on preparations for World War IV, which he said <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON> `` substantially replicates'' in one of his reports. The letter cites quotations from <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>'s story that are nearly identical to those in <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON>'s article and says in several places <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON>'s phrasing and detail echo those in <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>'s article However, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said he was not accusing <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON> of lifting quotes _ he said at least one official acknowledged saying exactly the same thing to both reporters. `` Most of <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON>'s sources are pretty much the ones that <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> had used a year earlier,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> wrote. `` We are confident that the board, armed with these facts, will reconsider its awarding of the prize to the Weiner series,'' the letter said. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> in 1985 became the first to use Pentagon documents to determine the size of the `` black budget.'' At the time <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> was a senior research analyst at the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION>, an independent think tank. He later joined the Journal. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, interviewed at the Journal office, said he thought <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON> did `` an amazingly poor job in developing the story, considering the amount of time he had.'' He said the Pulitzer board should make awards for ground-breaking stories, adding, `` I'm sorry they failed to do this.'' Inquirer Managing Editor <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON> called the Journal protest an `` unfair attack on <PERSON> Tim </PERSON>'s reporting.'' He said both stories quote some of the same sources because there are few sources available on the matter. `` The Journal did not inspire our story. We did not replicate but went well beyond what it reported,'' <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON> said he interviewed more than 100 people around the country and was `` knee-deep in this before I saw <PERSON> David </PERSON>'s work.'' `` I think <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> is a terrific reporter, and he did fine work on this subject. But he's making a false accusations, and it's a false controversy that's going to ultimately hurt journalism,'' he said `` I do n't write stories to win prizes, and I wrote these to bring an important public policy issue to people's attention,'' he said. <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Neumann </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION> editor for investigative projects, said the Inquirer laid the groundwork for the `` black budget'' story even before <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON> became involved and long before the <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> article was written.
