<HEAD>Students Protest Racial Remark, Call For Happy Chandler's
Resignation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf pvs, `Chandler, a...', to
insert further comment from Chandler that he is sorry `if it is
offensive.' Picks up 4th graf pvs, `But in...'. Note language in
5th and 10th grafs. A version moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> students marched Wednesday to protest a racial slur made the previous day by former Gov. A.B. `` Happy'' <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, who helped the first black players get into major league baseball. About 40 students marched across campus to meet with university President <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Roselle </PERSON> to call for an apology by <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> or his resignation from the school's board of trustees. Some marchers expressed anger with placards such as `` Hopefully Happy is Sad,'' while others demanded an explanation, shouting `` We want to know!'' <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, a two-time governor of <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senator, reacted by saying, `` They're trying to make a mountain out of a molehill.'' He said he had no plans to apologize unless asked to do so by <PERSON> Roselle </PERSON> or Gov. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON>. But in an interview with the <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> Herald-Leader, he said: `` If it is offensive, I'm ready to say I'm just really sad and sorry. In other words, my head is bloody but unbowed.'' During a committee's discussion Tuesday of the university's 1985 decision to sell off its investments in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said, `` You know <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>'s all nigger now. There are n't any whites.'' `` I do n't think I should be censured for this,'' he said in a telephone interview from his home in <LOCATION> Versailles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION> `` I do n't think I deserve any harsh treatment. <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, 89, was commissioner of baseball from 1945-51 and takes credit for opening the door for <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> to become the first black to play major-league baseball when <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> signed with the <ORGANIZATION> Brooklyn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dodgers </ORGANIZATION> in 1947. <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON>, who appointed <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> to a voting position on the university governing board earlier this year, said Wednesday that he believed <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> meant nothing derogatory but should apologize anyway. `` It was a bad statement and it was a statement that should never be made,'' <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> said, `` and I'm going to recommend to him that he apologize and explain it.'' In the telephone interview, <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said that while growing up in <LOCATION> Corydon </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Henderson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> `` there were 400 whites and 400 blacks. We called them niggers and they did n't mind. We loved each other. We never had any trouble. `` I integrated schools when other governors were sending troops in to keep blacks out. I was sending troops in to keep them in.'' He was governor in 1935-39, and again in 1955-59. <PERSON> Roselle </PERSON> told the students that the `` university completely and totally repudiates what it is Governor <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> says.'' But he said he did n't known yet whether there would be any action against <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>. <PERSON> Roselle </PERSON> said he hopes some good comes from the incident such as the need for `` a continuing, aggressive program of action to put aside all semblances of racial prejudice at this <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION>.''
