<HEAD>Woman Marries Man Just Before He's Sentenced To Long Prison Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An 18-year-old man married a woman he had never seen outside of jail or the courtroom five minutes before he was sentenced to 27-years-to-life in prison for murder. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Mastropietro </PERSON> and his 30-year-old bride, <PERSON> Antoinette </PERSON> <PERSON> Natale </PERSON> exchanged vows in a state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge's chambers shortly after his sentencing judge refused to perform the ceremony, said defense attorney <PERSON> Gaspar </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mastropietro </PERSON>, of Troy, was convicted for his role in the 1987 stabbing death of 81-year-old <PERSON> Irene </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> suburb of Watervliet A companion, <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Cummings </PERSON>, received an 18-years-to-life sentence. <PERSON> Mastropietro </PERSON> was introduced to <PERSON> Natale </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> hairdresser, during a jailhouse visit shortly after he was arrested in March 1987, <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> said. The pair corresponded frequently and <PERSON> Natale </PERSON> visited <PERSON> Mastropietro </PERSON> in jail, the attorney said. She faithfully attended her future husband's murder trial. A few days before the sentencing, <PERSON> Mastropietro </PERSON> told his lawyer he wanted to get married. `` I attempted to discourage them because they really did n't have an opportunity to formulate a relationship,'' <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> said. `` They insisted that they wanted to get married.'' <PERSON> Natale </PERSON>, dressed in a plain white dress for her wedding, said she did n't want people thinking she's foolish for marrying <PERSON> Mastropietro </PERSON>. `` I love him and I believe he's innocent,'' she said before ducking away from reporters. <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Court Judge <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> refused to marry the couple, but delayed sentencing to give the lawyer a chance to find a judge who would perform the ceremony. Supreme Court Judge <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Conway </PERSON> agreed. <PERSON> Mastoprietro </PERSON> could n't have been married after the sentencing because under state law, prisoners serving life sentences can not get a marriage license, <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> said. During the ceremony, <PERSON> Natale </PERSON> gave a ring to <PERSON> Mastropietro </PERSON>, who could n't reciprocate. The lawyer said he was n't sure when the couple will have the chance to be alone together. Only some <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> prisons allow conjugal visits, but there's a long waiting list for the privilege, he said. `` I spoke to this woman at length and she's committed to this young man,'' <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> said. `` I'm not sure if it's love or the kind of human concern that develops for another person that does n't have anything to do with romantic love.'' <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> said he's appealing <PERSON> Mastroprietro </PERSON>'s conviction. <PERSON> Mastroprietro </PERSON> was given the maximum sentence. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> rejected <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON>'s bid for leniency in sentencing <PERSON> Mastropietro </PERSON>, saying `` what happened here transcended the normal bounds of society.'' <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> was found stabbed in her home on March 8, 1987. <PERSON> Mastroprietro </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cummings </PERSON> had gone there with the intent of stealing her car. The woman's hands were tied and she was stabbed three times in her side. Doctors said she lingered for several hours before dying.
