<HEAD>Drug Ring and Bribes Ensnare Police, Fire Chiefs and County
Officials</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Johnie in 7th graf is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A drug ring openly run by a small-town fire chief, police chief and their families was protected by a web of bribes that has implicated two county sheriffs and commissioners, according to court documents. The latest to agree to a plea bargain in the case involving the town of <LOCATION> Kermit </LOCATION> was <LOCATION> Mingo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> `` </PERSON> <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilbert </PERSON>, who is trying to avoid trial on 13 felony counts alleging that he bought his job for $ 100,000 and then protected the ring, court documents say. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Savage </PERSON> called <PERSON> Hilbert </PERSON>'s alleged activities `` the most appalling abuse of public office since <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> gave away the monarchies in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to his relatives. The joint federal-state probe began two years ago when investigators discovered drugs being sold so freely in <LOCATION> Kermit </LOCATION>, a town of 700 in <LOCATION> Mingo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, that undercover officers were able to photograph a `` No Drugs Today'' sign posted outside a trailer. So far, the investigation of the ring, which sold cocaine, PCP and other drugs, has netted more than 50 convictions or guilty pleas, with no acquittals. Among those serving sentences of up to 16 years for operating the ring are former Kermit Fire Chief <PERSON> Wilburn </PERSON> <PERSON> Preece </PERSON>; his wife, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>; their son-in-law, former Police Chief <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramey </PERSON>; and their four sons and two of their daughters. A third daughter was placed on probation. <PERSON> Hilbert </PERSON> will be sentenced in federal court on April 18, the same day as <PERSON> Johnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, a one-time <ORGANIZATION> Mingo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> chairman and sheriff accused of selling his sheriff's job to <PERSON> Hilbert </PERSON>. <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> faces up to 14 years in prison and $ 700,000 in fines. An court order filed Tuesday provided no further information on <PERSON> Hilbert </PERSON>'s proposed plea agreement. <PERSON> Hilbert </PERSON> would face a maximum sentence of life imprisonment without parole if convicted of all 13 counts. In an interview this week, <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> denied knowing about the <PERSON> Preece </PERSON> drug operation when he sold his job, but said `` it's going to be a better Mingo'' because of the investigation. `` If nothing else, it's made people realize that it was wrong. Even if they knew it was wrong, they did n't know the extent it was wrong,'' he said. <PERSON> Hilbert </PERSON>, who is free on $ 100,000 bail and continues to serve as sheriff, could not be reached at his office Wednesday night, and his home number was unlisted. <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> said he accepted a $ 20,000 downpayment on the $ 100,000 bribe from <PERSON> Hilbert </PERSON>, then persuaded the three county commissioners to accept his resignation and appoint <PERSON> Hilbert </PERSON> in exchange for half of the bribe. Former Commissioner <PERSON> Rastie </PERSON> <PERSON> Runyon </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> has pleaded guilty to federal income tax evasion charges related to the bribe and awaits sentencing later this month. Commissioner <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON>, the only member of the 1982 panel still in office, was indicted Jan. 15 on one count of bribery. He has denied the charge but is not running for re-election. The third commissioner, state Sen. <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafin </PERSON>, has not been charged in federal or state court. He has adamantly denied any knowledge of the sale of the sheriff's office. Also caught by the investigation was county political boss <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamrick </PERSON>, who pleaded guilty to three felony charges of protecting the <PERSON> Preece </PERSON> drug ring, using public funds for political campaigns and intimidating a witness. The indictment against <PERSON> Hilbert </PERSON> accuses him of two counts of racketeering in connection with buying both his office and a spot on a powerful county political slate from <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>. He also faces two counts of aiding and abetting the <PERSON> Preece </PERSON> family drug operation `` by seeing to it the law was n't enforced'' in return for illegal campaign contributions.
