<HEAD>Jackson Pleads For Money, Respect For His Qualifications</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> gave a spirited defense of his credentials as he pleaded with supporters to provide him the funds to finish the last stage of the race for the Democratic presidential nomination. `` The only hope for the campaign's success is to believe in it enough to invest in it,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said Wednesday at a fund-raiser at an <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> nightclub, which approximately 650 people paid $ 20 apiece to attend. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is a close second to <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in the number of delegates won. <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> is a distant third. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said his campaign's ability to survive financially through delegate-selection procedures in 40 states shows his management skill. That skill plus his ability to set a moral tone for the nation and to voice the concerns of the averae American make him qualified to be president, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> contended. `` Some officeholders are not leaders, and some leaders are not officeholders,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. `` If tomorrow morning, you were about to lose your job, among those who are running, Republican or Democrat, who would you want to argue your case?'' In a 30-minute speech, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said that although he has n't held public office, he has experience negotiating in labor disputes, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and in farm crises. Holding office should n't be a criterion for running for president, he said. `` Most Cabinet members who run the government on a day-to-day basis have n't held a government office,'' said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` You want somebody to argue your case, here am I.'' At his first stop in <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> on Wednesday, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> predicted that his campaign stands against drugs and for farmers will inspire a wide range of people to vote for him in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>'s May 3 Democratic presidential primary <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> declined to say that he will win the primary and the largest share of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>'s 79 delegates, but he said his involvement should stir voter interest and increase participation. The 2 -LCB- - hour event was also beamed by satellite to seven other locations in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and sites in eight other states
