<FIRST>r a PM-GridlockBuster Bjt   04-07 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gridlock Buster, Bjt,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Electronic Device Would Help Drivers Beat Gridlock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Relief may be in sight for frustrated motorists trapped on <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s gridlocked highways _ in sight, that is, on a 4-inch dashboard video screen. As part of a pilot traffic management program unveiled Wednesday by the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>, little black boxes will alert drivers to road congestion and traffic accidents on electronic road maps displayed on the dash. The sophisticated devices, which transportation officials used last year to help monitor traffic during Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, will then help motorists snake their way around traffic problems by flashing alternate routes on the screen. `` This system will help the user avoid problems rather than driving into and becoming part of the problem itself,'' Department Director <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Best </PERSON> said at a news conference announcing the project. The $ 1.6 million test of the system will begin this summer in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. During the study, which is a joint project involving the department, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, drivers hired by the state will cruise the congested <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Freeway </LOCATION> in 25 cars equipped with the units. On-board computers will relay the location and speed of the cars to the the state agency's traffic operations office in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, improving the accuracy and timeliness of traffic reports the department relays to media outlets. To operate the device, a driver inserts a cassette containing an electronic map of an area up to 10 miles from the car and selects a destination. An arrow on the 4-inch-square screen then traces the vehicle's progress along roads. The state agency currently uses television monitoring and electronic road sensors placed every quarter-mile along 300 miles of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' most congested freeways to gather road information. <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, notorious for its rush-hour traffic, is the only area now wired to accommodate the two-way, high-tech navigational system, which will utilize the sensor monitoring system. A similar system for 215 miles of congested freeways in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> would cost $ 130 million, officials said. The units, which are commercially available for about $ 2,500 apiece, will cost between $ 300 and $ 500 when they are mass-produced, officials said. But even if the pilot program goes well, it may be 10 years before the technology is perfected and the system is available to most drivers. In a test run after the news conference, officials were embarrassed when one of four units failed to work properly. `` This one needs to be recalibrated, I guess,'' said driver <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Juje </PERSON>, of the state agency. `` I guess we pushed too many buttons.'' Nevertheless, officials heralded the beginning of the project as an important next step. `` If we want to continue to make owning and operating a car a pleasure instead of a chore, one challenge our industry must take up _ and quickly _ is improving the commuting experience,'' said Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Angew </PERSON>, director of programs and planning for <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> is providing the cars and support personnel for the project. The state is contributing $ 900,000, and the federal agency is providing $ 750,000 and technical assistance. More than half of all congestion is caused by accidents and incidents that distract drivers' attention, officials said. Urban congestion `` ca n't be solved entirely by more asphalt and concrete,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Farris </PERSON>, an official with the federal agency.
</TEXT>
