<HEAD>Parents of 28 Children Get Keys To 15-Bedroom Dream Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM COUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FIFE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> and <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Cornyn </PERSON> and 23 of their 28 children pulled up in the family bus and then received the keys to a 15-bedroom, eight-bathroom dream house remodeled for them with government help. `` This is all very exciting,'' said <PERSON> Cornyn </PERSON>, a 42-year-old chief warrant officer stationed at nearby <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> who has been in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> for 24 years. `` We're all very ecstatic.'' The Cornyns adopted 25 of their children, including some who are South Korean, Colombian, Indian, Amerasian and black and some with disabilities. Some are wheelchair-bound or move about on crutches. They all help care for each other. `` We have a rainbow family,'' said <PERSON> Cornyn </PERSON>. `` We have just about every color there is. We look at the rainbow as God's promise.'' The family, except for three children who were in school and two in a hospital, were at Wednesday's ceremonies. `` Perhaps in the future we'll need more bedrooms,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Cornyn </PERSON>. `` But this is a dream come true. Somebody believed in us enough to help us. This is something we thought would never happen.'' Excited smiles shone on the faces of the children, who range from age 8 months to 26 years, as they explored the 5,620-square-foot house. It has eight bathrooms, a downstairs family room that takes up nearly the entire floor and two washing machines, dryers and dishwashers. A yard big enough for a softball game surrounds the rambling white house at the end of a tree-lined road in this rural town 30 miles south of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. `` I have two children. Believe me, you've got to be courageous,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Dicks </PERSON>, D-Wash., who presented the keys to the Cornyns `` It's touching and rewarding to see a family like this.'' The house was remodeled at a cost of $ 60,000 by the <ORGANIZATION> Pierce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which was formed last April 24. Called Project 30 because the <PERSON> Cornyn </PERSON> family numbers 30, the home purchase and remodeling job is the first project undertaken by the association, which is leasing the house to the Cornyns. The Cornyns were high school sweethearts in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> who married as soon as <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> graduated. They adopted their first child when the family was stationed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in 1979. `` I guess we do it because it feels good and it's the right thing to do,'' <PERSON> Coryn </PERSON> said. `` It just makes us feel good to help someone else. We enjoy seeing these children grow physically and mentally.'' He noted that many of his adopted children would be in institutions if he and his wife had n't adopted them. <PERSON> Cornyn </PERSON> said some of his adopted children received supplemental Social Security benefits and the family also receives food from local food banks and clothes from `` lots of people.'' The Cornyns are the largest family housed under the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>'s housing voucher program, receiving $ 700 monthly toward rent and utilities. The Cornyns are moving from a six-bedroom home in <LOCATION> Puyallup </LOCATION> to their new home, which has been expanded during the past six months from eight bedrooms. `` It seems like we've never had enough room,'' said <PERSON> Cornyn </PERSON>.
