<FIRST>r a PM-DoctorGlut     04-07 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Doctor Glut,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says Aging Baby Boomers May Run Out of Doctors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The aging baby boom generation may run out of doctors early in the next century as a widely predicted surplus of physicians turns into a shortage, according to reports released today. The authors of two reports, both published in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, contend that a feared doctor glut wo n't happen But at least one of the experts who has forecast an overabundance of physicians says he is not ready to change his mind. Several studies during the past decade have forecast that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will have too many doctors by the year 2000, and recommend that the nation train fewer of them. But now, with that date just 12 years away, there are signs that opinion may be swinging the other way. In one of today's reports, Drs. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Tufts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sloan </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> predict that at best, there will be just enough doctors by 2000 but a mild shortage is possible. In the other, less detailed paper, Dr. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schloss </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> looks into the early decades of the next century. `` It is entirely possible that for the majority of people who are alive today, there may be another shortage just when they will need doctors the most _ after 2011, the year in which the first of the baby boom generation will turn 65 and enter their retirement years,'' he concludes. In general, the doctors argue that the earlier predictions overstated the supply of doctors and underestimated the demand for their services. However, <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> said those predictions already have had an impact. `` Many college students are looking on medicine as an unpromising career, in part because they are being told that there is going to be a huge physician surplus,'' he said in an interview. `` That is undoubtedly one of the factors that has led to a sharp reduction in the number of applications to medical school,'' which have fallen 15 per cent since 1981. <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>' report projects that 592,000 physicians will be needed by the turn of the century, and 585,000 will be available. Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Petersdorf </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colleges </ORGANIZATION>, has been warning of a coming doctor glut for years. He said <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>' study makes assumptions about physician supply and demand that may be wrong. `` I agree with the authors that the presumed projected oversupply should not act as a deterrent to choosing medicine as a career,'' <PERSON> Petersdorf </PERSON> said. `` At the same time, I am not prepared to state that an oversupply does not exist. The support for such an assertion is based on assumption and not on fact.'' One of the most widely quoted of the earlier projections was a report in 1980 of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> It predicted that in 2000, there will be 144,700 too many physicians. However, <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> said that and other predictions greatly overstated the supply of doctors. The biggest mistake was assuming that all of the nation's doctors will be treating patients. Instead, <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> said that about 93,000 of them will be administrators, teachers and researchers. Another miscalcuation, he said, was failing to take into consideration the impact of the growing proportion of female doctors, who, studies show, work about 10 percent fewer hours than their male counterparts. The researchers also did not foresee a movement to require resident physicians to work shorter hours in large teaching hospitals. <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> said the earlier predictions also made a mistake by assuming that the demand for physicians will remain constant. Instead, he said, the demand for care has been growing at an annual rate greater than 1 percent for several decades. The availability of new kinds of care, such as exotic imaging machines, transplants and genetic analysis, may speed up the demand for more doctors. Other factors that could increase demand, he said, include the increasing age of the population, wider medical insurance coverage and the AIDS epidemic.
</TEXT>
