<FIRST>r a PM-Brite--StrandedSeals     04-07 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brite--Stranded Seals,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stranded Seals Need New Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGANTINE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two young hooded seals that beached themselves earlier this year are now healthier and in need of a new permanent home, but finding one is n't as easy as calling a zoo. Wookie and Sweet Pea may be adorable seal pups now, but they eventually will become rather ferocious adults weighing more than 700 pounds each, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoelkopf </PERSON>, director of the Marine Mammal Stranding Center. In addition, a zoo or aquarium must have the proper refrigerated pool to keep the seals comfortable, he said. `` I'm afraid this is a passing-through facility only,'' he said of the non-profit center he runs. The two female seals beached themselves on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> in late January and early February, <PERSON> Schoelkopf </PERSON> said. Wookie was sickly and bald; Sweet Pea was extremely ill and emaciated. Both had bronchial infections that took weeks to clear, <PERSON> Schoelkopf </PERSON> said. The seals have regained their strength, fat and rambunctious energy, barking at each other and romping in the center's pool, he said. Now they must find a colder home `` or else I'll have to start buying a lot of ice cubes,'' he said. `` Refrigeration is not so much the problem at this point, but we start seeing stranded porpoises and sperm whales this time of year,'' <PERSON> Schoelkopf </PERSON> said. `` There's no way I can put them in with the hooded seals. ... These seals are not known for their friendliness.'' He said that releasing the seals to the wild would also be a poor solution because they have become fairly docile. Sweet Pea is estimated to be only a few months old and eats only when hand-fed. Wookie, believed to be about a year old, has bald spots and could not survive sunburn, her rocky native coast of <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION> or skirmishes with other animals, <PERSON> Schoelkopf </PERSON> said. Hooded seals, named for the fleshy snouts of the adult males, normally are never found south of <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Schoelkopf </PERSON> said. That made them 1,500 miles off course when the reached <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. `` It's like us planning to go to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and winding up in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> instead,'' he said. He said the ideal situation would be to find a benefactor sympathic to the plight of the stranded seals and other stranded marine mammals who would donate enough money to build a nearby facility for them. `` It would be a great tax writeoff, and we'd even name the place after them,'' <PERSON> Schoelkopf </PERSON> said, only half-jokingly. The marine specialist has contacted an animal placement agency in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> that spread the word about the seals. In the past two weeks, however, no one has expressed an interest. `` We're not trying to find just anyplace _ we want the animals to go somewhere where they will be cared for properly,'' <PERSON> Schoelkopf </PERSON> said. `` I want somewhere that has federal permits to handle these animals, not a roadside attraction.''
</TEXT>
