<HEAD>Former Siamese Twins Return Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Separated Siamese twins <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Binder </PERSON> returned to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> today, seven months after an operation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> separated their skulls and circulatory systems. The twins arrived at <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> airport this morning on a <ORGANIZATION> Lufthansa </ORGANIZATION> flight from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lufthansa </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gessner </PERSON> said. He said the twins were immediately taken by a private jet to an undisclosed destination in southern <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gessner </PERSON> said he did not know who had arranged for the private jet. The boys, now 14 months old, were released from <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday. Their parents, <PERSON> Theresia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Binder </PERSON>, accompanied them on the flight. The were also joined by several friends and a doctor from <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, who traveled with the boys as a precaution. <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> will be allowed to go home immediately, but <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> is to spend at least several days in a West German hospital for observation. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>'s progress has been slower since he stopped breathing briefly when he choked during a feeding on March 13. The two were separated during a lengthy operation in September. Doctors at <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> said on Tuesday the boys have the potential to lead normal lives, but emphasized that their development has been severely delayed.
