<SECOND>PM-Turner's Castle,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Glenn Turner Property To Go On Auction Block</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A three-story, 16-room castle owned by onetime motivational entrepreneur <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> is going on the auction block, with the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and other creditors splitting the proceeds. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, 53, created a $ 300 million empire in the 1970s by selling distributorships in his Dare to be Great and Koscot International companies. But his empire collapsed after state and federal investigators accused him of operating pyramid schemes that bilked thousands of investors. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, imprisoned in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> prison for fraud, has owed the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> millions of dollars in back taxes for more than a decade, and the agency has succeeded in foreclosure proceedings against the property in <LOCATION> Seminole </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. The unfinished castle, its boathouse, stables and surrounding 79 acres will be sold to the highest bidder after a federal court hearing April 26, according to court documents. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>, which had a $ 15 million claim, has been awarded a judgment of $ 9.275 million, but appraisals put the value of the Turner property at $ 1 million to $ 2 million. Before the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> gets its share, <LOCATION> Seminole </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> has the right to collect $ 16,900 in unpaid property taxes for 1987, said county Tax Collector <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON>. Private investors also have claims against the property for $ 200,000 in tax certificates, under which they paid the taxes and earn 18 percent interest until the property is sold and the tax amounts are paid back to them.. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> and his family have n't paid property taxes since 1979, but investors bought tax certificates equal to the back taxes each year <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> documents in <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION> indicate there are dozens of other Turner creditors, but it is unlikely they will be paid from any proceeds from the Castle's sale, officials said. Bids on the Castle property will be advertised over the next few weeks to notify any other bidders of the pending sale. The castle and boathouse have been vacant for several years, and the castle has been used only for tours by the public for charitable events. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, the son of a <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> sharecropper and a self-styled country boy, rose to fame in the early 1970s through inspirational speeches that promised great wealth if people bought distributorships in his operations. The companies collapsed in 1973 under lawsuits filed by investors and investigations by state and federal agencies. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> and a partner, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Rector </PERSON>, 57, were sentenced to seven years in prison in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> in August on charges of operating a pyramid scheme there and defrauding investors through a self-motivational company called <ORGANIZATION> Challenge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>.
