<HEAD>Cease-Fire Talks Make Some Headway, Ortega Warns of Major
Offensive</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To CORRECT that Ortega was referring to Contra freedom of
movement, SUBS graf 2, `Ortega also ... cease-fire zones' and graf
13, `In his ... in the country.' Picks up 14th graf, ```They can
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> put pressure on Contra negotiators participating in cease-fire talks in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> by threatening to launch a major military offensive against the rebels if the talks break down. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> also said Contra leaders in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> for peace talks will not be allowed freedom of movement to talk with internal opposition leaders until rebel fighters have moved into designated cease-fire zones. The president of the leftist government spoke Wednesday as <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> and Contra military leaders reported making progress in technical cease-fire talks they planned to resume today in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>, an outpost on the Costa Rican border. Key issues on bringing about a lasting peace have yet to be negotiated. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> launched an offensive against the U.S.-supported Contras in northern <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> last month. On President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s orders, 3,200 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops flew to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> on March 17-18 after Honduran President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> said 2,000 Nicaraguan soldiers had invaded his country in pursuit of Contras The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops never saw action and returned home at the end of March. Finishing their fourth technical meeting, the military negotiators in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> agreed on seven zones in which Contra fighters are to gather by April 15 _ two each in the north, central and <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, and one in the south. Still to be worked out are details for the combatants' security, the key issue of what needs to occur before the Contras lay down their arms. The two sides also agreed to postpone until April 15 a high-level meeting in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> between <LOCATION> Contra </LOCATION> and Sandinista political leaders. Those talks had originally been scheduled for Wednesday. `` If the Contras do n't accept the agreements, the people must be ready for combat and ... launch an offensive with all available force to be rid of -LRB- the Contras -RRB- once and for all and not prolong the war,'' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> told farmworkers at an agricultural cooperative in the eastern province of <LOCATION> Granada </LOCATION> on Wednesday. `` We have to fight so the -LRB- peace -RRB- agreements work, but for the agreements to work we can not let down the defense of the country,'' he said in the remarks carried by state-run Voice of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. Both the political and technical cease-fire discussions are part of a preliminary peace agreement the two sides signed on March 23 in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>. The accords put into effect a 60-day truce last Friday that aims to give negotiators time to arrange an end to their six-year war. In his speech, <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said <PERSON> Contra </PERSON> leaders who come to <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> for the high-level talks will be restricted in their travel in the country until the rebels have moved into the cease-fire zones. `` They can come to <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>,'' he said, `` but to the meeting _ nothing more.'' The Contras have been pressing for permission to move about freely during their stay, saying they want to meet with opposition groups. They also have accused the Sandinistas of violating a provision of the <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> accords calling for `` unrestricted freedom of expression'' by not supplying newsprint to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s only opposition newspaper, <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Prensa </PERSON> did not publish Wednesday and its publisher, <PERSON> Violeta </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrios </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>, told a news conference that the newsprint restriction was `` a deliberate blow to freedom of expression in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.'' The Sandinistas, who control the importation and distribution of Soviet newsprint, say a shipment has been delayed. The Sapoa accords do not directly deal with the issue of a Contra surrender of arms, of what will happen to rebel fighters after they move to the designated zones and the cease-fire expires. The Contras maintain they will not lay down their arms until they are assured of full democracy in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The government says the putting down of weapons is `` indispensable'' to the truce's success. The peace pact says the government pledges that `` individuals who have been reintegrated into normal civilian life'' will be able to take part in future elections. But `` normal civilian life'' is open to interpretation in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, where the government claims to have 300,000 people under arms. In complying with the accords, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> on March 27 freed 100 political prisoners. The Contras say only 10 of the prisoners they requested were released. The pact does not give the rebels a say in who is freed. Both sides declared a truce March 21 at the start of the talks that led to the peace plan.
