<HEAD>Settlers Call for Revenge at Funeral for Teen-age Settler</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY8</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with funeral, quotes from Shamir, Arabs
wounded. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARNEI SHOMRON, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of Jewish settlers, some shouting `` Revenge! Revenge!'' attended the funeral today for an Israeli girl stoned to death by <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> villagers. Earlier, settlers attacked <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> cars and homes. Under heavy army guard, settlers carrying <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> flags strung with black ribbons buried 15-year-old <PERSON> Tirza </PERSON> <PERSON> Porat </PERSON>, who was killed Wednesday during a clash between settlers and <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> villagers in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Beita </LOCATION>. `` Near the fresh grave of <PERSON> Tirza </PERSON> <PERSON> Porat </PERSON>, God will avenge her blood. The heart of all the people boils over,'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> told about 9,000 mourners. `` Every killing strengthens and unites the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> people, links it more to this land, deepens its roots here. The rioters and instigators will not achieve a thing. They are leading their people to tragedy,'' he said. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> was interrupted by cries of `` Revenge!'' and `` Expel the Arabs!'' Many in the crowd carried M-16 rifles or pistols. The body, wrapped in a black tarpaulin bearing a white Star of <PERSON> David </PERSON>, was carried in a 25-minute procession from the Elon Moreh settlement, where the girl had lived, through the heart of the Arab city of <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION> and past several <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> villages, to the Jewish cemetery in <PERSON> Karnei </PERSON> <PERSON> Shomron </PERSON>. <PERSON> Tirza </PERSON> was the first <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> civilian to die in four months of unrest in the territories occupied by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> since the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. According to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> figures, 140 Arabs have died, and one <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldier has been killed. Israeli troops shot and wounded two Arabs today during clashes in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Hospital officials said <PERSON> Fathi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahmoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON>, 20, of the Beach refugee camp in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> was wounded in the chest and another 18-year-old Arab from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>'s Qabatieh was shot in the abdomen The army announced it had destroyed four <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> homes in <LOCATION> Beita </LOCATION> belonging to villagers suspected of attacking the settlers. Thirteen Israelis were injured in the incident Wednesday. According to army accounts, it began after <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON> stoned a group of teen-agers on a hike. Israeli guards accompanying the hikers fired on the stone-throwers, killing two Palestinians and wounding two, the army said. Arab witnesses said the clash was provoked by Israelis. They said the guards fired without provocation on Arab villagers and that the villagers then charged the Israelis. Justice Minister <PERSON> Avraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharir </PERSON> proposed demolishing houses in <LOCATION> Beita </LOCATION> and expelling hundreds of villagers allegedly involved in the violence. Rabbi <PERSON> Eliezer </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldman </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> member from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kiryat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arba </ORGANIZATION> settlement, echoed the call `` With an Arab village in which a pogrom on Israeli children takes place, there's nothing else to propose but to destroy all of the village, to wipe it out from the land of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' he told <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s armed forces radio. Throughout the night and into this morning, settlers attacked <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> homes and cars, despite appeals by Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> and Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Shomron </PERSON>, armed forces chief of staff, not to retaliate for the slaying. Some called for <PERSON> Beita </PERSON> residents to be expelled to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and for authorization allowing soldiers to shoot anyone throwing stones. <PERSON> Raja </PERSON> <PERSON> Salem </PERSON>, who had a swollen lip and a cut on his face, told a reporter he was beaten up by settlers in the Arab village of <LOCATION> Hawwara </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Beita </LOCATION>. `` Every house on the main road is in danger of attack now. They want to retaliate. They want to kill us,'' he said. <PERSON> Aly </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON>, 57, another resident, said `` everyone has clubs and stones but that is not enough to face guns. Settlers using guns come to humiliate us, but if we fight them, they will kill us.'' The Maariv daily reported that dozens of villagers identified as attackers by the Israeli teen-agers were detained Wednesday night. It said they included a woman and her daughter suspected of killing the girl to avenge the death of their cousin, who was killed during the clash. Army spokesmen declined comment on the report. The army announced it was extending the closure of Arab schools until May 8. The 850 Arab schools and five universities attended by 300,000 students have been closed since Feb. 4. <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON>, speaking on armed forces radio, said that Arabs responsible for the attack had been arrested and would be punished. He did n't say how many were arrested, and he noted that some Arabs had tried to protect the Jewish teen-agers. Dozens of settlers held a vigil Wednesday near <LOCATION> Beita </LOCATION> and announced they would build a settlement at the site of the clash. Leading right-wing politicians such as former Defense Minister <PERSON> Ariel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> went today to <PERSON> Elon </PERSON> <PERSON> Moreh </PERSON>. About 100 men and women gathered at the <PERSON> Porat </PERSON> home. Many of the men held M-16 rifles in their laps as they waited for the funeral to begin. Some wept.
