<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, in an interview published today, was sharply critical of Democratic presidential contender <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> for his attacks on rivals <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` It does not work, and it's terribly dangerous,'' <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said of the negative campaigning. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> governor told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview that he is unlikely to make an endorsement before his state's primary on April 19. `` The closer you get to primary day, the less reason'' there is to announce support for one of the candidates, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said, adding that he would prefer to remain neutral until after the final primaries. `` That's the time for leadership in this process,'' he said. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, already important by virtue of the 255 delegates at stake in its primary, takes on an added significance because of the seesaw race being run by <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. The two have remained close in the national delegate count. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> finished a strong second in the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> primary and had a major win in the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> caucuses; <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> came back with victories in the <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> primary, the <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> caucuses and the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> primary. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said he expects the contest between <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> `` will be very close here.'' Noting that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had garnered 26 percent of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> vote in 1984, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> told the Post: `` You've got to give him 10 points more than that this year. I'd say, 35 to 40 percent is his base.'' The governor said his call to hold down negative campaigning was `` intended for all Democrats and specifically for <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> has said both <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> lack experience in international issues, and has been particularly critical of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` It does not work, and it's terribly dangerous and counterproductive in a primary where one of you will be the nominee,'' <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. `` You should not spend a lot of time criticizing your opponents, especially if you have not established your own identity in this state.'' Another politician who has been vocal in his criticism of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has been <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said there was little he could do to get <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> to heed his call to tone it down. `` The mayor has already ignored it and will continue to. I have no hopes of conversion, short of his being struck in the tush by a bolt of lightning ... and I have no command over the lightning,'' he said. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said he expected about 10 percent of the Jewish vote to go to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, despite the furor in 1984 over <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s reference to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> as `` Hymietown.'' `` Most of them -LRB- Jewish leaders <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> addressed last week -RRB- agreed with him that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> should be defeated, but then the question comes: Are you, Mr. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, the way to do it? The sophisticated ones, who read the polls, may decide the best way to do it is with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said he expected black voters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, as they have elsewhere, to `` go overwhelmingly for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>.''
