<HEAD>Conspiracy Charge Dropped Against Three As Trial Begins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prosecutors and defense attorneys say the trial of a polygamist leader and three others charged in the bombing of a Mormon chapel and a 13-day standoff with police will proceed much more quickly because of the dismissal of a conspiracy count. `` It relieves the government of proving a real complex count and makes the issues in the case much clearer,'' <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Metos </PERSON>, attorney for defendant <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, said Wednesday. A pool of 170 potential jurors reported Wednesday to the courtroom of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, where they received a 20-page questionnaire and heard the charges. The federal charges now include bombing, destruction of the <ORGANIZATION> Kamas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> with an explosive, use of a bomb, attempting to kill federal agents, assault on federal officers, possession of a bomb, possession of a sawed-off shotgun and two counts of use of a firearm. <PERSON> Vickie </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON> is charged with all eight counts; polygamist leader <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> faces all but the shotgun-possession charge; <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, who had not been charged with conspiracy, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON> face the firearms, assault and attempted murder counts. <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> is <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>'s brother, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON> is <PERSON> Vickie </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>'s son. Associate Utah Attorney General <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON> said Wednesday that state prosecutors would wait until after the federal trial to file homicide charges in the death of corrections Lt. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON>, killed during the shootout that ended the siege at the defendants' farm. <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, 27, appeared in court Wednesday in a buckskin coat emblazoned with a Mormon pioneer flag. His mother-in-law, Mrs. Singer, 44, was dressed all in white, including a white bow in her hip-length hair. `` It is turning into a nightmare,'' <PERSON> Metos </PERSON> said. `` I've done nothing but criminal law for 10 years, and I never saw defendants do anything like that to draw attention to themselves,'' he added. Although <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> granted the prosecution motion to strike the conspiracy count, he denied requests from all four defendants to separate their trials, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. The judge did not rule on a motion by <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> that his trial should be moved out of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> because of the predominance of the <ORGANIZATION> Mormon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, which abandoned polygamy in 1890. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> has said he would rule on the issue during jury selection. <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> has said he was chosen by God to gather the American Indians for the second coming of Christ.
