<HEAD>David Holt on Road for Musical Celebrations of Americana</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA3 of April 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<HEAD>AP Television Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Holt </PERSON> is on the road looking for traditional music and other celebrations of American life, from banjo makers to washtub players to cowboy poets. <PERSON> Holt </PERSON> will begin reporting on his discoveries next Wednesday in `` Celebration Express,'' a new segment of `` Nashville Now'' on the <ORGANIZATION> Nashville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>. The on-location reports, with upbeat and musical themes, will run every Wednesday until Sept. 28. `` <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> Now'' is a live, 90-minute variety series that features the best of the country music stars. Next week, the show will come live from <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cayman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> with such guests as <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Travis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabbitt </PERSON>, <PERSON> Conway </PERSON> <PERSON> Twitty </PERSON>, <PERSON> Loretta </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hoyt </PERSON> <PERSON> Axton </PERSON>. The host is <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Emery </PERSON>, along with his puppet, <PERSON> Shotgun </PERSON> <PERSON> Red </PERSON>. `` I travel all the time,'' said <PERSON> Holt </PERSON>. `` That's what I do for a living, playing concerts. I've been collecting music and songs from the old-time mountaineers for 20 years, so this is like an extension of that.'' <PERSON> Holt </PERSON>'s first `` Celebration Express'' segment on the show will come from <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, a look at cowboy poet <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>. Another Denver segment will feature <PERSON> Daddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON>, who owns a barbecue restaurant and gives away an estimated 4,000 meals a year. `` He's a real inspiration,'' said <PERSON> Holt </PERSON>. `` He's doing this out of the goodness of his heart. He's been doing it since he was a child and he's 88 now. `` Since this is a celebration of the <ORGANIZATION> Nashville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>'s fifth anniversary,'' <PERSON> Holt </PERSON> said, `` we're looking for people who are having a celebration. Or whose very lives are a celebration. We're going to travel 100,000 miles around the country. `` I'd love to see this become a series. It's been a wonderful experience for me just in the short time I've done it. It's wonderful to search out these people and spend time with them. <PERSON> Holt </PERSON>, who previously served as host of <ORGANIZATION> TNN </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Fire on the Mountain'' series, is a musician, storyteller and historian who is helping to preserve the Appalachian musical heritage. In <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Holt </PERSON> found the <ORGANIZATION> Deering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banjo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which is one of four places in the world that still make fine banjos. `` Most of the craftsmen also play, and we got a little session going that I joined in,'' he said. `` <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> is celebrating its 100th anniversary as a city and I did an interesting musical piece. I played a 64-string dulcimer, which is made of spruce, in the cockpit of the Spruce Goose. It makes an interesting sound to play an instrument of the same wood as the room you're in.'' The Spruce Goose is the flying boat built by <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> in World War II, now on display in a <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> museum. <PERSON> Holt </PERSON> then went to <LOCATION> Claremont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, to see <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindley </PERSON>, a musician noted for unusual folk instruments. `` He plays the Hawaiian slide guitar and the saz, which is a Turkish instrument with a long neck and six strings,'' said <PERSON> Holt </PERSON>. `` It