<HEAD>Rival Shiite Factions Battle for Third Day, 18 Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDMOND SHEDID</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABATIYEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shiite Moslem militias fighting for control of south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> battled today with rocket-propelled grenades and automatic weapons. Police said 18 people were killed and 27 were wounded. It was the third straight day of violence between the Syrian-backed Amal militia and the pro-Iranian <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, believed to be the umbrella organization for groups holding foreign hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Thirty people have been killed and 61 wounded since Tuesday. A police spokesman said Justice Minister <PERSON> Nabih </PERSON> <PERSON> Berri </PERSON>'s Amal fighters, backed by armored personnel carriers, were advancing slowly on <LOCATION> Ghaziyeh </LOCATION>, a key <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> stronghold six miles south of <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION> is the provincial capital of south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. `` If <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> controls <LOCATION> Ghaziyeh </LOCATION>, then <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>'s remaining strongholds will also fall eventually,'' the spokesman said. He spoke on condition of anonymity in keeping with police regulations. The official said Amal had seized 10 major towns and villages and that <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> still held four hamlets in addition to <LOCATION> Ghaziyeh </LOCATION>. He said Amal seized <LOCATION> Nabatiyeh </LOCATION>, a market town 18 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION>, in a `` sweeping attack'' before dawn. `` Rescue teams are searching the rubble of devastated houses for bodies,'' the spokesman said. Six Hezbollah fighters, their hands raised, walked out of a gutted house to surrender to Amal after the fall of <PERSON> Nabtiyeh </PERSON>. It has a population of 50,000 people, most of them Shiites. The battle for the town lasted several hours as <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> fighters, holed up in a school belonging to the town's tiny Christian community, traded rocket-propelled grenades and mortar fire with the Amal militiamen. Tensions between <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> have increased since Feb. 17 when <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> blamed <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> for the abduction in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marine officer Col. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON> Amal rounded up dozens of <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> members it accused of involvement in the kidnapping. <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> has denied the Amal allegations and accused the rival militia of `` harrassing the believers by searching for an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> spy.'' The Organization of the Oppressed on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, an underground group believed linked to <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, claimed responsibility for <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>' abduction He is one of nine Americans missing after being kidnapped in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. American journalist <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, chief <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asssociated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, is the longest-held foreign hostage. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
