passenger. Pick up 5th pvs, `Twelve British...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Hijack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A British passenger freed from a hijacked Kuwaiti jet in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was quoted today as saying that two of the hijackers offered her pillows and drinks and chatted with her daughters. An Austrian businessman also released said the seven gunmen were brutal when they seized the plane but later treated the hostages well. `` We did n't have time to be frightened, things happened so fast,'' British passenger <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Sefton </PERSON> was quoted as saying in an interview with <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION>. She spoke by telephone from the Hyatt Hotel in <LOCATION> Mashhad </LOCATION>, northeast <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> confirmed today that all 22 Britons on the plane, which has hijacked Tuesday on a flight from <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, had been freed. The hijackers were still holding about 50 hostages, including three members of <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s royal family. They are demanding <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> release 17 convicted pro-Iranian extremists. Austrian <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Degeorgi </PERSON>, 53, who manages <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s office in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, was freed early today with 31 other passengers and crew members. In a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Mashhad </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Degeorgi </PERSON> said the hijackers were armed with handguns and grenades. All wore masks. At the start of the hijack the crew members were forced to lie on the floor with their hands behind their heads, and some passengers were handcuffed, <PERSON> Degeorgi </PERSON> said. `` At this stage things were quite brutal,'' he said. `` But they told passengers repeatedly to be calm, not to worry. They were really very friendly to us. Some passengers got excited and needed oxygen. But they -LRB- the hijackers -RRB- kept reassuring us.'' Twelve British men were among 32 people released earlier today and had been taken to the <LOCATION> Hyatt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hotel </LOCATION>, where they were reported `` fit and well,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Irishman </PERSON> <PERSON> Kieran </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Kelly </PERSON> and his wife, Nisran, also were freed. Mrs. <PERSON> Sefton </PERSON> and her daughters <PERSON> Jane </PERSON>, 14, and <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON>, 12, were among 10 British women freed by the hijackers on Wednesday and later contacted by the Daily Mail in repeatedly interrupted telephone calls. `` One minute I was asleep, the next I was being nudged in the ribs by my husband and I saw one of the hijackers in the aisle,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Sefton </PERSON> was quoted as saying. `` The hijackers were n't always within my view but I saw them and one said, ` Do n't worry. Keep quiet.' ... A couple of the hijackers spoke English and asked if we wanted pillows and drinks and things. They talked a bit to the children.'' Relatives of the Britons hijacked on the Bangkok-to-Kuwait flight were jubilant at the release of their loved ones. `` We are obviously very relieved,'' said <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Stillwell </PERSON>, businessman father of 23-year-old <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Stillwell </PERSON>, who was among those freed today. Speaking from his home at <PERSON> Ryde </PERSON> on the Isle of Wight off the southern English coast, the elder <PERSON> Stillwell </PERSON> added: `` It was an ugly situation. `` These hijackings often end peacefully but who can be sure? It has been a bad time. We are very pleased at the news. Now we are waiting for official confirmation, but that could take a long time.'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Stillwell </PERSON>, a commercial photographer, had been returning from a six-month holiday in the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> with his 19-year-old girlfriend <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> McIntosh </PERSON>, who also comes from the Isle of <PERSON> Wight </PERSON>. She was among the British women freed Wednesday. `` We felt so helpless,'' said <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, mother of British hostages <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Appleby </PERSON>, 23, and <PERSON> Nicola </PERSON> <PERSON> Appleby </PERSON>, 25. `` We have just been waiting from one news bulletin to the next, hoping and praying they would be released,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said from her home in the western English port city of <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Appleby </PERSON>, a graphics salesman, and <PERSON> Nicola </PERSON> <PERSON> Appleby </PERSON>, a travel courier, had been vacationing in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>.
