<HEAD>Former Miss Minnesota-USA Pleads Guilty In Shoplifting Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDINA, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former Miss Minnesota-USA who gave up her title after being arrested for shoplifting has pleaded guilty but will not be convicted if she stays out of trouble and completes a counseling program, her attorney says. <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolich </PERSON>, 24, of <LOCATION> Mound </LOCATION>, entered the plea to a charge of gross misdemeanor theft Wednesday in <LOCATION> Hennepin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Court </LOCATION>. Her attorney, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Timmons </PERSON>, said she must take part in a county pretrial diversion program for first offenders that includes counseling and job assistance. If she successfully completes that program, all charges will be dismissed in a year, he said. <PERSON> Bolich </PERSON> was arrested on Jan. 22 at the <ORGANIZATION> Southdale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shopping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in this <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> suburb and charged with shoplifting a bathing suit, scarves and hairpieces valued at around $ 370, authorities said. She resigned as Miss Minnesota-USA on Feb. 8 and passed the title on to <PERSON> Jolene </PERSON> <PERSON> Stavrakis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Apple </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, first runner-up in the contest, who also withdrew before the Miss <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> pageant after it was reported that she had pleaded guilty to shoplifting in 1986. Second runner-up <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> eventually represented <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> at the pageant in March.
