urors' deliberations would be affected by what they know. Although both the state and the defense have said they were fearful of the effect of the pre-trial publicity, many of the potential jurors said they discounted what they had read, because of a distrust of the press. `` They have a tendency to present people as guilty just because they have been charged,'' said <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Cioffi </PERSON> on Wednesday. <PERSON> Ferraro </PERSON> and her husband, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaccaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, have attended the questioning, which is taking place in the cramped chambers of the presiding judge to put the potential jurors at ease. The process has shed some light on the strategies lawyers may take in the trial. <ORGANIZATION> Addison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>'s Attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON> has asked potential jurors if they have any objections to police acting on rumors and to the use of undercover police officers. Police said they began their investigation of <PERSON> Zaccaro </PERSON> after hearing he was dealing drugs. Defense lawyer <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Tetzlaff </PERSON> has asked jurors if they would be willing to acquit someone based on a technical defect in the state's case. The defense is expected to try to prove that <PERSON> Zaccaro </PERSON> was entrapped by the police, and that the police singled him out because of his famous mother.
