<HEAD>NYSE Limit on Program Trading Triggered For First Time</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with late-morning Dow average
today and to include Japanese, British stock activity. Picks up 3rd
graf pvs, `Although the ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jump in the Dow Jones industrial average tested the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> voluntary limit on computerized program trading for the first time, but Wall Street experts differ on whether the restriction matters. Traders said a cheer erupted on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s vast floor when the widely-followed average careened past 50 points at about 3:20 p.m Wednesday, automatically placing the `` collar'' on so-called index arbitrage trading for the rest of the day. The Dow average closed at 2,061.67, up 64.16 points. The momentum of that rally helped inspire strong buying in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> today that pushed prices past their pre-crash levels. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, which gained 195.82 points Wednesday, gained another 258.05 today, reaching 26,769.22. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index was up about 22 points to the 1767 level by late afternoon. But as of late morning in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, however, the momentum stalled and the Dow Jones average was off about two points to the 2,059 level. Although the average had flirted with a 50-point daily up or down limit at least four times since the restriction was announced Feb. 4, Wednesday marked the first time the threshold was breached. The collar is part of an effort to suppress wild price swings in the aftermath of the Oct. 19 market crash and restore investor confidence. Some traders said that without the limit, the Dow average might have risen as much as 100 points Wednesday, but others said it was impossible to know. `` There was a lot of program trading when the Dow was up between 35 and 49 points,'' said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Puccio </PERSON>, manager of institutional trading at <ORGANIZATION> Dillon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Read </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` It went from 40 to 49 within five minutes.'' Several other influences boosted stocks, notably a stronger dollar and lessening fears of higher interest rates. But many brokers said program trading played at least a partial role in the Dow's sudden surge. Program trading refers to a sophisticated form of arbitrage, the simultaneous purchase and sale of similar goods in different markets in order to profit from price disparities. Using computers that instantly place massive orders, program traders buy stocks in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and sell corresponding stock-index futures in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, or vice versa. Many brokers have blamed the technique for injecting enormous volatility _ as well as crushing trading volume _ into the stock market without regard for underlying stock values. Some studies have suggested program trading was an important element in the October crash. <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Torrenzano </PERSON> said Wednesday after the 50-point collar was triggered that `` it's not the solution but it's clearly a first step in controlling what we call intra-day volatility. Asked how far the Dow average would have moved without the limit, <PERSON> Torrenzano </PERSON> said, `` If you talked to 10 people you'd get 10 different answers. I have no idea.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Twenty-First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which utilizies program trading, said he believed the technique was n't an element in the Dow's rise Wednesday, largely because the price disparities between stocks and stock-index futures were n't profitable enough for widespread arbitrage `` It's sort of a non-event,'' he said. `` Program trading was n't fueling the up move I do n't think there was any particular rhyme or reason to it.'' Others said the reaching of the limit caused the Dow to retreat several points before it began moving up again, but at a slower pace that reflected the absence of program trading's influence. `` Without the restriction, I think you would have seen it up 100 points today,'' <PERSON> Puccio </PERSON> said. `` I think the limit is good because it gives people a little pause to reflect rather than buying with abandon.''
</TEXT>
