<HEAD>Special Mudpack to Clean the Taj Mahal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Workers are using a new method involving clay mixed with solvents to clean the stained marble of the Taj Mahal, the world's greatest monument to love. The `` clay pack technique'' is used to remove stains and yellowing caused by pollution and fumes from an oil refinery 28 miles northwest of the landmark. The 17th century all-marble monument at <LOCATION> Agra </LOCATION>, 111 miles south of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, was built by the Moghal emperor <PERSON> Shahjahan </PERSON> in memory of his wife, <PERSON> Mumtaz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahal </PERSON>. <PERSON> L.P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sahi </PERSON>, minister of state for culture and education, told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> that the clay packs had been used on a few areas of the Taj on an experimental basis. He said the treatment had proved to be satisfactory and would be extended to clean large surfaces. In the method, inert clay and non-toxic detergents are spread on the marble. The yellowing film on the marble is absorbed by the clay after being washed away by the detergents, <PERSON> Sahi </PERSON> said.
