<TEXT>
 A Danish group plans to set up <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s first alligator farm in southern <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> to produce skins and meat for export, the project organizer said Thursday. `` The baby alligators would come from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and be bred at the farm in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, but it would take three to four years before production and export of the reptiles' skin and meat could begin,'' said <PERSON> Leif </PERSON> <PERSON> Skovgaard </PERSON> in a telephone interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Skovgaard </PERSON>, a chartered accountant who is organizing the project for a group of seven Danish investors, said 10,000-12 ,000 alligators would be bred yearly at a farm near the town of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Roque </LOCATION> European Alligator Institue, as the project is called, seeks financial support from the local and state governments in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> as well as the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. The farm, which the group hopes to open by the beginning of 1989, would employ about 100 people, <PERSON> Skovgaard </PERSON> said. `` As alligators are dangerous at any age, our personnel will be specially trained to cope with them so they do n't lose fingers,'' he added. The project envisions a nature park where visitors can observe the 9 - to 15-foot-long animals in an outdoor environment <PERSON> Skovgaard </PERSON> said he did not anticipate protests from animal protection or environmentalist groups. The group contemplates inviting a representative of the World Wildlife Fund to sit on the new company's board of directors, he said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> banned hunting alligators because the species was disappearing, but it was lifted recently after the animals made a comeback.
