<HEAD>Rescuers Find Stranded Spelunkers Alive &amp; Well</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARREDONDO, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nine spelunkers were found safe and sound Thursday after being stranded for four days inside a huge cave that was threatened by rain-swollen underground rivers, a rescue official said. Rescuers emerged from the cave with seven of the cave explorers just before 7 a.m., said <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Isla </PERSON>, a government <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. Two other men decided to continue their trek through the 18-mile-long cave known as Cueto-Coventosa, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s second-largest and a favorite of national and international spelunkers, he said. `` Everything went fine until we ran into the swollen waters of a lake on our way towards the Coventosa exit,'' one of the men rescued told <ORGANIZATION> Spanish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> shortly after emerging from the cave. <PERSON> Isla </PERSON> said doctors declared the seven men who emerged from the cave in good condition, but advised them to eat and get some sleep. He said the men had been near to using up their food supplies. More than 100 cave explorers took part in the search that began Monday when explorers, who were aged between 18 and 30, failed to emerge as planned after entering the cave Friday. The cave is on the outskirts of <PERSON> Arredondo </PERSON>, 23 miles east of the northern port of <LOCATION> Santander </LOCATION>.
