<HEAD>Guerrillas Forming Afghan Counter-Regime</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCHEHEREZADE FARAMARZI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaders of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s fractious Moslem guerrillas are forming their own regime to challenge the communist government from `` liberated'' areas when Soviet military forces are gone. The alliance of seven parties, three moderate and four fundamentalist, has been meeting almost daily to preserve unity while they lay the groundwork for their own government. `` There is hope that it will work,'' a moderate leader said. `` No doubt, when the Russians leave <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s regime will collapse,'' said <PERSON> Gulbaddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON>, head of the alliance. `` To avoid anarchy and possible armed clashes to seize power, it's necessary that all parties agree to a temporary government. Soviet forces entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979 and an estimated 115,000 soldiers now are helping fight the insurgency, which began after a Communist coup in April 1978. <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and Afghan leader <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> issued a joint statement Thursday saying all obstacles had been cleared in negotiations to end the war and the Soviets hope to start pulling their troops out next month. In <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mediator indicated major differences remain but <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, where 3.5 million Afghan refugees have taken refuge, said an agreement was ready for signing. The guerrilla alliance has agreed to hold elections among fighters in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and refugees in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> for a council that would vote on establishing of an interim Moslem government. Leaders of the seven groups have named <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> as president and <PERSON> Zabihullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mojaddedi </PERSON> as his deputy to lead a 21-member Cabinet, in which each party is to have at least two members. A leadership council of the seven guerrilla leaders would function as the head of state and supervise <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON>'s government, which would operate from a `` defended'' area beyond the reach of the Communist government's forces <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammadi </PERSON>, leader of the moderate <ORGANIZATION> Harkat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, named five guerrilla-controlled areas: <LOCATION> Kunar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Noorestan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakitia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Panjshir </LOCATION> and Hazarejat. <PERSON> Sebghatullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mojaddedi </PERSON>, leader of the moderate <ORGANIZATION> Afghan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` If we come under pressure in one place, we will move to another.'' Agreement also has been reached on having a judiciary committee to settle disputes among the parties. `` We will work hard for the liberation of Afghanistank, but the devil ... may influence some people and encourage disputes,'' <PERSON> Mojaddedi </PERSON> said. `` We hope our brothers will understand that, except for unity, solidarity and compromise, there is no other way to reach our pure goals. For the freedom of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and in order to create true Islam in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, we must put aside all these disputes. There is hope that it will work.'' Not all rebel leaders are equally keen on forming an interim government inside <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Gailani </PERSON> of the moderate <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> fears it could cut the nation in half. `` If there are two governments in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, there is the danger of partition into north and south or east and west, as with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, or East and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Gailani </PERSON> prefers a transitional government in exile until the Communist regime can be overthrown. <PERSON> Yunis </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalis </PERSON> of the hardline <ORGANIZATION> Hezb-i-Islami </ORGANIZATION> faction expects outside interference. `` Colonialist countries, the superpowers _ East or <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> _ have joined hands to prevent the creation of a total Islamic government in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>,'' he said. <LOCATION> Khalis </LOCATION> said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, where Shiite Moslems dominate, is urging <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas to reject a Sunni Moslem government in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, where Sunnis are in the majority. `` Therefore, we can not for certain bring about an Islamic government in the present circumstances,'' he said. `` This is why we declare we will not abandon our jihad -LRB- holy war -RRB-.'' Deep-seated frictions persist. One source <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON>, who is unpopular even in the hardline camp but recently replaced <LOCATION> Khalis </LOCATION> as head of the alliance. `` He is not the leader but only head of the alliance. Every party is independent,'' <PERSON> Mojaddedi </PERSON> said. `` Of course we have had our complaints. The brothers have warned him that, now that he has become the head, it does not mean he has all the authority in his hand to do whatever he likes.'' <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON>'s men have been accused of harassing guerrillas of other parties, journalists and relief workers traveling to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. His party, also called Hezb-i-Islami, has been blamed for the killing of a British cameraman last year. <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON> has denied it.
