<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Global registration began Thursday for a second Sport Aid `` Race Against Time,'' the six-mile street jog by nearly 20 million people in 1986 that raised $ 35 million for starving Africans. Organizers are hoping to involve all 218 countries and inhabited territories in the Sept. 11 extravaganza, compared with 89 nations last time. Major charities and sports federations in 85 countries have already joined the Sport Aid'88 campaign. `` We're trying to build on that new constituency of compassion,'' said an organizer, <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Dring </PERSON>. `` All we can do is to create a forum for this to happen and say to the world, ` Please join us.''' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is expected to contribute more this year, Dring said. Sport Aid was a flop in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in 1986 because it coincided with a nationwide `` Hands Across America'' campaign to raise funds for the poor and homeless. `` America is <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' Dring said in an interview. `` It lives within itself so adequately, it's very difficult sometimes to involve them in events of this nature. `` We're presently in discussions with the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and with a number of major sponsors in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and we believe this year <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will run,'' he said. The first person to register for this year's run was <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalifa </PERSON>, a Sudanese athlete who dramatized the plight of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s famine victims when he carried a burning charcoal ember in an Olympic torch to 14 countries to launch the May 25, 1986, event Each runner will be given an individual number tag, starting with <PERSON> Khalifa </PERSON>'s No. 1, which he donned during a news conference at <ORGANIZATION> Sport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aid </ORGANIZATION>'s headquar