ZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>. More than 40 percent of those discharged were women, who represent only about 5 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>' strength. Department of Defense figures also show that, during the three-year period, 662 cases of homosexuality among Marines were investigated by the <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and about a third of the investigations involved women. There's no clear reason for the disparity and the matter has never been studied, said <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Schilling </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. She denied that special attention was being paid to lesbians. `` A commanding officer has the responsibility if someone in their command has indicated a reason to believe there's a violation of the <ORGANIZATION> UCMJ </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Uniform Code of Military Justice -RRB- to check it out,'' she said. The investigation at <LOCATION> Parris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> `` is not a regular occurrence but it's not an unprecedented thing,'' said Maj. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McLean </PERSON>, a spokesman for the base. Records of such cases are kept only about two years, but <PERSON> McLean </PERSON> said he understood that there was a similar hearing involving women Marines three or four years ago. He said the base does n't make unsolicited announcements of such hearings but will answer media inquiries. The current proceedings are Article 32 hearings, which are similar to civilian grand jury hearings. They are, in effect, an open investigation in which defendants have certain rights and defense and prosecution witnesses can be called. The investigating officer then makes a non-binding recommendation to the Marine's commanding officer. The recommendation may be that the charges go to a court-martial, that the Marine go before an administrative discharge board or the charges be dismissed. In an administrative discharge board, a board of <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION> determines whether the defendant has the potential for further service. A court-martial could lead to a prison sentence. In addition to the counts of indecent acts, the defendants face various charges including dereliction of duty, sodomy, conspiracy to obstruct justice and assault. `` Not all the charges are related to homosexuality,'' <PERSON> McLean </PERSON> said. `` In a larger sense, we are talking about breaches of good order and discipline.'' He said the Corps can not tolerate homosexuality because `` homosexuality is contrary to good order and discipline, not because there is a statement being made about lifestyles. `` Recruit training must be conducted with the highest standards of order and discipline,'' he added. `` The overwhelming majority of those who serve perform faultlessly.''
