<HEAD>Nine-Month-Old Recipient Of Multi-Organ Transplant To Leave
Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two months after being given a new liver, small bowel, pancreas and a portion of stomach, 9-month-old <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Steward </PERSON> is ready to go home, his doctor says. The success of the transplant operation so far is `` absolutely fantastic news'' that provides hope for other children suffering from multiorgan failure, Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> says. The boy, who is from <LOCATION> Rockford </LOCATION>, underwent a multiorgan transplant operation at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s Rush-Presbyterian-St. <PERSON> Luke </PERSON>'s Medical Center in February <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, the youngest child to receive such a transplant, is scheduled to be released from the hospital Saturday, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said Wednesday. Only three other children are known to have had such transplants. Two have died; the third still is hospitalized. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> was born with a twisted intestine that turned gangrenous and had to be removed a week later. That left him with an intestine too small to absorb food. Intravenous feeding kept him alive but destroyed his liver, necessitating the transplants. After the transplant surgery, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> battled setbacks, including holes in the donor small bowel, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. `` There have been a couple of times in this course that I did n't think he was going to survive,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said He said it was possible the boy will be able to function normally. `` I'm very encouraged by the progress that has been made so far, but it's still an experiment and we're still in the middle of it,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said the donor bowel has been maturing well and the child now gets about two-thirds of his nutrition through it. He gets the rest of his nourishment through intravenous feeding. The doctor said he expects the boy will be weaned entirely from intravenous feeding within two weeks. The donor small intestine has not yet been connected to the boy's stomach, so he will have to return to the hospital in about two months to undergo an operation to connect it, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. `` We ca n't say that we have the total solution to short gut syndrome in children, but we are strongly encouraged that this procedure can be a promising option for other children suffering from similar problems,'' he said.
