<HEAD>Ancient Religious Order Electing New Grand Master</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials of the Knights of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> cast secret ballots Friday for a new leader to carry on the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> order's 900-year-old tradition of chivalry, charity and nobility. Thirty-six electors will lock themselves in a villa on the <LOCATION> Aventine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> on Friday to vote for a successor to Fra Angelo de Mojana di Cologna. The order's grand master died Jan. 18 at the age of 82 after 25 years as the knights' supreme leader. The 78th grand master will be chosen from among 22 of the electors, including de Mojana's interim replacement, <PERSON> Fra </PERSON> <PERSON> Giancarlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Pallavicini </PERSON>, a Hungarian-born American biochemist. A grand master carries the title of prince and is addressed as `` Your Most Eminent Highness.'' Equal in rank to a cardinal, he is elected for life and is considered the highest-ranking layman in the Roman Catholic church. To be eligible for the position, he must have attained the top rank of `` Knight of Justice'' and followed vows of poverty, chastity and obedience. He also must be able to prove 200 years of nobility on the side of both parents. The result of the election will be announced only after the decision is ratified by <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, possibly several days after the vote. The Sovereign Military Order of the <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jerusalem </ORGANIZATION>, of <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> and of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> _ the group's full title _ was founded during the crusades when it opened a hospice for pilgrims in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> in the early 11th century. It has the status of an independent state and has diplomatic relations with 50 nations. The order is not related to the Knights of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, an American Roman Catholic society for men founded in 1882 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, that also is involved in charity and social works. The Knights of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> dedicate themselves to chivalry, charity and nobility. Today the order has about 10,000 members, led by <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> with 2,800 and followed closely by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with 2,500, said spokesman <PERSON> Monsignor </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Jannone </PERSON> said. Among its well-known members in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> financier <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Grace </PERSON>, attorney <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, former Secretary of State <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Haig </PERSON> and the late <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>. Italian members include Foreign Minister <PERSON> Giulio </PERSON> <PERSON> Andreotti </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Francesco </PERSON> <PERSON> Cossiga </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Giovanni </PERSON> <PERSON> Agnelli </PERSON>. Beyond the image of chivalry, pomp and noblesse oblige _ symbolized by their uniforms, cloaks, medals, plumed hats and swords _ the knights are known for their dedication to the sick and wounded. The order operates about 200 hospitals and first aid centers in 90 countries, especially in Third World nations and war zones. `` After centuries of fighting to protect our citizens and territory, the order has returned to its original function: health assistance, hospitals, fighting against hunger and misery,'' <PERSON> Jannone </PERSON> said in an interview. For centuries, membership in the order required proof of `` blue blood,'' but some ranks including `` Knights and <PERSON> Dames </PERSON> of Grace and Devotion'' are now accessible to those without noble ancestry. About 60 percent of the order's members today do not come from nobility, <PERSON> Jannone </PERSON> said. Since 1834 the order has been based in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, where it owns a 16th century palace on Via <LOCATION> Condotti </LOCATION> in the heart of the shopping district and a four-acre villa on the <LOCATION> Aventine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. The site is a favorite spot for Romans and tourists, who can peek through a gate keyhole down a cypress-lined path that frames the dome of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peter </LOCATION>'s Basilica in the distance. The order took on its military-chivalric character to defend pilgrims and the Christian kingdom against Moslem attacks. The knights were forced out of the Holy Land at the end of the 13th century, eventually settling in <LOCATION> Rhodes </LOCATION>, where they became a naval power in the eastern <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. They were driven from <LOCATION> Rhodes </LOCATION> by the Ottoman Turks in the 16th century and moved to <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>, which they turned into an island fortress and a thriving center of Christianity and trade. The knights stayed in <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> until 1798, when the island was captured by French Emperor <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON>. Before settling in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, the order temporarily came under control of Czar <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> I of <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> and shuttled among <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Catania </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ferrara </PERSON>. Among their activities in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the Knights of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> run free cl