<FIRST>r i AM-FoodConference     04-07 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Food Conference,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>US, EEC Clash On How To Balance World Food Situation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MILAN RUZICKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and European officials disagreed Thursday over how to prevent food surpluses from building up in the developed nations when much of the Third World goes hungry. The two-day World Food Conference, organized by the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, brought together 200 agriculture and development experts to discuss the problem of surplus food output in parts of the world and continuing shortages elsewhere. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said only an end to farm subsidies `` will bring about the necessary reform.'' Continuing current policies, `` will inevitably lead to greater surpluses, more wasted resources ... more disincentives for economic expansion in developing countries and more trade confrontation,'' <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> told the delegates. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is seeking an end to all state aids to farmers by 2000 in the current round of trade liberalization talks within the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. But <PERSON> Frans </PERSON> <PERSON> Andriessen </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commissioner </ORGANIZATION>, said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal was `` neither possible nor desirable.'' `` Some form of stabilization and protectionism ... will always be needed,'' given the unpredictability of food production. He said the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> agreed in February to curb its runaway growth of farm output through production ceilings and penalties for overproducers. He termed this `` a major contribution'' toward restoring a balance between supply and demand. He added, `` European farmers expect a similar action by other producing areas.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> are the world's largest food producers. Zambian President <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaunda </PERSON> appealed for an end to `` economic parochialism'' and greater liberalization of world trade. He urged the developed nations to put aside national differences. `` We have to move from blind protectionism to ... regional and finally global harmonized free movement of goods and services,'' he said. `` The social and economic world order ... can no longer permit undue overemphasis on what I wish to call economic parochalism.'' <PERSON> Kaunda </PERSON> urged food producers not to dump `` surplus stocks on us through food aid'' but to help the Third World become self-sufficient. Concessions to Third World producers, he said, `` must be seen as a major incentive for promoting self-reliance in development more appropriate than food aid.'' The delegates to the conference hope to adopt a common statement at the end. A preliminary draft obtained by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> calls on key food producing nations to switch from accross-the-board food price subsidies to income supports for needy farmers. Ending subsidies, the draft said, should be joint effort by all industrial nations. Delegates said the draft, if adopted, would echo the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s views, rather than the more radical ones of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, as a way to come to grips with the imbalance in supply and demand <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, in seeking a way out of the world's farm trade problems through <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>, prefered a `` multilateral solution. It would, however, `` continue to support <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agriculture vigorously ... if fair trade can not be achieved multilaterally,'' he added. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal for a radical end to farm subsidies was backed by <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unions </ORGANIZATION> which said `` agricultural export subsidies and measures with equivalent effect should be phased out over the next 10 years.'' It added the developed nations should rid themselves of food surpluses through lower prices for farmers, giving food to its own needy citizens and those in the world's poor regions. Western food must be given to developing nations in emergency cases only, the group said in a paper. `` Long-term Western food aid carries the disadvantage that it competes with ... locally grown food.'' It criticized as unfair to the Third World the repeated EEC efforts to tax imports of oils and fats and to pay <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> farmers a bonus to use some of their cereal output as animal feed.
