 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has agreed to sell <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> a ring laser gyroscope for use in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s development of its own light combat aircraft. The sale of the device, which is used to stabilize the steering mechanism of a jet, is the latest in a series of technology transfers from the Untied States to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> for the project. Last year, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> approved the transfer of 10 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> engines for the plane. The sale of the gyroscope was announced Wednesday by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Defense Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carclucci </PERSON>, who noted that `` since the memorandum of understanding in 1983, the transfer of technology items has gone up by 400 percent'' from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. The agreement was signed by Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s mother and predecessor, <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>. Talks on further transfer of technology for the combat aircraft are continuing. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> also confirmed that `` there has been formal notification to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>'' of the transfer of 11 F-16 fighter jets to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. He described them as `` attrition aircraft'' to replace jets <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> had lost. He said the jets were part of the recently approved $ 1.04 billion, six-year aid package to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>.
