<HEAD>Simon's Statement As He Suspends His Presidential Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a transcript of Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>'s statement Thursday as he suspended his campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination I am today suspending my campaign for the presidency. I'm grateful to all who have campaigned with me and for me. And I leave the field of active campaigning with no regrets for having made the race. No regrets, first, because it has been an exhilarating experience to get to know our nation better, both our difficulties and our potential. I understand more fully the plight of native Americans in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, the nuclear energy in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the similarities and difficulties that farmers in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> share with their <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> counterparts, the isolation of a small city in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> in winter, the disfigurement oil rigs could cause to the magnificent coastline of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, the sadness of unemployment in <LOCATION> Starr </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and the wasted humanity in too much of our nation. But I've also come to know better a nation with potential, a nation that is limited not by our talent and resources, but by our dreams and our leadership. Where I have had the opportunity to reach people I have seen them respond with a selflessness that must be tapped. Americans instinctively know that we are one nation, one family, and when anyone in that family hurts, all of us eventually hurt. There really is a yearning across this land for leadership that appeals to the noble in us rather than the greed in us. I wish I had been able to tap that yearning more effectively. But to the extent my supporters and I have been able to reach out and talk about programs and a vision of a better nation, to that extent we have helped to make possible the building of a better nation. For that, I am grateful to far too many people to be acknowledged here, but they include my wife <PERSON> Jeanne </PERSON>, a superb campaigner; my daughter <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> and her husband <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Knop </PERSON>, who were married Sept. 12, and have since been honeymooning in places like Audubon, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Sturgeon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, and my son, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, my traveling companion, photographer and consultant. No candidate could have stronger family support. To the staff of my campaign, who worked long hours for limited pay, to our chairman <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Manatt </PERSON>, and the countless volunteers, more volunteers than any other campaign, who are unbelievable in their efforts; to those who raised money against great odds, to a host of others I should be acknowledging my gratitude. And to the people of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> who have been both supportive and understanding, my full efforts will now be devoted to being your senator, and I shall be a better senator because of this rich experience. The Polish writer, <PERSON> Kazimierz </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandys </PERSON>, tells a story of two who were approached during a period of ferment in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and asked to protest the illegal arrest and imprisonment of a leading intellectual. One refused to sign and said, `` I ca n't. I have a son.'' The other immediately took out his pen and said, `` I have to sign because I have a son.'' Both acts are understandable. But the legacy of honor that one leaves is vastly different than the other. I entered this race beause I have a daughter and a son. I entered this race because I have had the good fortune to understand the vast difference in the lives of millions of people action by government can make.
</TEXT>
