<HEAD>Summit on Track, Reagan Spokesman Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with remarks by Baker and
Powell on Afghanistan; Picks up 13th graf pvs, Discussing U.S.
pressure.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is pleased with news of an agreement that could lead to the beginning next month of a Soviet Army withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, White House chief of staff <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said today. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told reporters that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> believes Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s agreement with Afghan leaders clearing the way for settlement of the 10-year-old Afghan war `` is a step forward.'' But <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> also said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` wants to see the fine print. He wants to see the details of the arrangement. He wants to know the reaction and the interpretation of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' `` So the president is cautiously optimistic,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told reporters outside a seaside resort hotel here. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> had said Wednesday that planning for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s summit in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> `` is on track'' and wo n't be derailed by any continuing Soviet military presence in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. In a briefing that also touched on <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will `` press the case'' for a pullout if Soviet occupation forces are still in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> when the summit begins May 29. But in <LOCATION> Tashkent </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> leaders announced today that they had resolved problems blocking a settlement, and the Soviets offered to start pulling troops out of the country on May 15 if agreement is reached in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on the terms for that withdrawal. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said today that `` we've got to examine that communique carefully. We've had n