 <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> out of power, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said another 800 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Marines will be sent to the Central American nation. But <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> insisted that the movement of the Marines from <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pendleton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, to a jungle training facility at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sherman </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> has nothing to do with the increasing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military show of force there. `` This unit training deployment has been scheduled since December,'' he said. `` These -LRB- troops -RRB- will be there for three weeks and they'll come out.'' On other topics, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> cautioned against concluding that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> plans to grant pardons to former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aides <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>, who have been indicted in the Iran-Contra case. A congressman who attended a March 22 meeting quoted <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as saying `` I like the sound of those words,'' when someone in the meeting broached the possibility of pardons. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> acknowledged that the remark seemed to indicate that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> favors pardons for his former top aides, but he said, `` I do n't believe you should make any assumptions or conclusions on the basis of that throwaway comment.''
