<FIRST>u w AM-GettingTheirMan     04-07 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Getting Their Man,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Authorities Often Get Their Men, No Matter Where They May Flee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American authorities, often aided by friendly foreign governments, have had some successes lately luring or forcing criminal suspects out of safe havens abroad into the long arms of the law. Some people call it kidnapping, but federal courts have generally approved the practice. The latest dramatic case occurred this week when Honduran police acting on information from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marshals arrested alleged international cocaine czar <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Matta </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballesteros </PERSON> at his home in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, and started him on a plane journey that ended in the federal penitentiary in <LOCATION> Marion </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Matta </PERSON>, who escaped from a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> jail in 1971 and has been charged with subsequent drug offenses in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, also was sought for questioning in the murder of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> narcotics agent Honduran legislators, citing a law against extradition of Honduran citizens, labeled the transfer a kidnapping, but the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Marshals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> called it `` a major milestone in our worldwide assault on illegal drug trafficking.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has extradition treaties with more than 100 countries, but each accord is different and some require long and often fruitless court proceedings that frustrate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law enforcement agents' desire to get their hands on suspects. Getting other countries to help by using what are euphemistically called `` non-diplomatic means'' _ as in the <PERSON> Matta </PERSON> case _ are common, law enforcement authorities say, though no statistics on such arrests are published. Police jokingly refer to these methods as `` Mexican Extraditions,'' a reference to the longstanding Mexican practice of shooing suspects wanted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> across the border, where <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> police are waiting. In the <PERSON> Matta </PERSON> case, two countries helped. The Hondurans put him on a plane to the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> without a passport. Officials in that country expelled him by placing him aboard a flight bound for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marshals aboard the aircraft arrested him immediately. Last year, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>, a reputed drug kingpin from <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, was extradited to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at the request of the Drug Enforcement Administration. Sometimes, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> captures people abroad without overt assistance from foreign nations. Last year, according to the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, undercover agents tracking <PERSON> Fawaz </PERSON> <PERSON> Younis </PERSON>, a suspect in the 1985 hijacking of a <LOCATION> Jordanian </LOCATION> aircraft, tricked him into going aboard a yacht in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> and arrested him under a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law giving <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> courts jurisdiction to try suspected terrorists who act against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens. <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> is awaiting trial in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. In 1982, former <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, who had fled to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> after being indicted on weapons sales charges, was duped by an acquaintance into flying to the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>. Authorities there put him on a non-stop flight to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where he was arrested. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Leary </PERSON>, the drug culture guru who escaped in 1970 from a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> jail, was turned over to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> narcotics agents in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> even though the two countries had no extradition treaty. Defense attorneys in some of the celebrated cases _ notably the <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> cases _ have sought dismissal of charges on grounds the overseas arrests violated the defendants' rights by, in effect, kidnapping them. Those requests, however, generally have been denied. The courts have said the manner of a suspect's arrest _ even an abduction _ is not relevant in assessing guilt or innocence. The only exception, based on a plea by a defendant brought back from <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> in the 1960s, would be a case in which the suspect's treatment, such as torture, was so outrageous it `` shocked the conscience'' of the court Even then, a suspect would have to prove it was <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities who committed the torture. Despite success in capturing such suspects as <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, other big fish have eluded the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> net. Since 1974, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been trying to extradite fugitive financier <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vesco </PERSON> to prosecute him on charges of looting $ 224 million from an international investor's fund. <PERSON> Vesco </PERSON> first went to <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>. He has since emerged in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, beyond the reach of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> police. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also tried for many months to arrange the arrest of <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON>, alleged mastermind of the 1985 hijacking of the Italian cruise ship <PERSON> Achille </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON>, during which New Yorker <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Klinghoffer </PERSON> was killed. <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> was aboard an Egyptian airliner forced down in <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> jets, but Italian authorities released him and he was later seen in several Islamic countries.
</TEXT>
