<HEAD>Mayor Saves Fairhaven Woman's Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bullard </PERSON> came as a guest to a luncheon honoring local heroes, but he left a hero himself after saving a choking woman. `` He saved my life,'' <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Macomber </PERSON>, 55, of <LOCATION> Fairhaven </LOCATION>, said. `` I could n't breathe. I could n't move. Then <PERSON> John </PERSON> jumped up, pushed his chair back and practically lifted me up off the floor'' while performing the Heimlich maneuver. The application of sudden upward pressure on the upper abdomen is intended to force a foreign object from the windpipe. <PERSON> Bullard </PERSON> had to apply it at least three times before dislodging a piece of chicken that had prevented Mrs. <PERSON> Macomber </PERSON> from breathing. `` Everyone in the room could have done the same thing,'' he said. `` I just happened to be the closest.'' The annual <ORGANIZATION> Wamsutta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> luncheon Wednesday, sponsored by The Standard-Times, honors residents for heroic, selfless and courageous deeds. They are first recognized in the newspaper's Hats Off column, published the last day of every month. Mrs. <PERSON> Macomber </PERSON> was being honored for thwarting a would-be robber at her liquor store last year by smashing his knuckles with a rum bottle. `` It was a truly heroic act,'' said Standard-Times Editor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ragsdale </PERSON>. `` Here we are, in a room celebrating many people who had themselves saved lives, and the mayor saved a life himself. Perhaps we should give him the Hats Off Award of the Year. He saved us from tragedy.''
