<HEAD>From Nepal to the Via Veneto, Campaign to Stop Smoking</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The health minister of <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> set fire to a pile of 35,000 cigarette butts on Thursday, Roman youths gave tourists apples for their smokes, and Chinese tried ointments and shock therapy to get through a day without tobacco. Thursday was the first worldwide `` No Tobacco Day,'' sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. It coincided with the 40th anniversary of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> agency and was designed to urge people to stop smoking or using chewing tobacco. Anti-smoking activists drove around the northern Japanese city of Hokkaido in a car equipped with a loudspeaker asking smokers to be considerate of non-smokers. <ORGANIZATION> ZDF </ORGANIZATION> television in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> showed grim footage of patients on a cancer ward. In <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, which introduced cigars and cigarettes to much of the world more than 300 years ago, officials in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Barcelona </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Valencia </LOCATION> sponsored contests for the best anti-smoking posters. The WHO campaign had no apparent effect in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, however. The streets and sidewalk cafes of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> were filled with smokers, despite radio broadcasts and posters denouncing the perils of puffing tobacco. `` Because of the civil war, the number of smokers in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> has increased dramatically,'' said <PERSON> Soha </PERSON> <PERSON> Tamim </PERSON>, a public health officer at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s civil war has raged since 1975. In <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, WHO Director General <PERSON> Halfdan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahler </PERSON> said tobacco use `` is tantamount to slow-motion suicide.'' He urged smokers and other tobacco users to stop for the day and then extend that `` into a week, a month, a year.'' The WHO awarded 40 medals to people and organizations it said promoted the idea of a tobacco-free society. They included former President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, actor <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>, the Soviet airline <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carrier <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>, the cigarette butts were collected by volunteers of the <ORGANIZATION> Nepal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. The health minister, Mrs. <PERSON> Shushila </PERSON> <PERSON> Thapa </PERSON>, lighted the pile during a ceremony in an open theater in the center of <LOCATION> Katmandu </LOCATION>. Major stores in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> stopped selling cigarettes for the day, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. In front of the Museum of Chinese History facing the central Tiananmen Square, educational stands were set up to help smokers who wanted to quit. Stalls sold `` anti-smoking ointment,'' `` restrain-and-stop-smoking drops,'' herbs and even a `` quit smoking mouth gargle'' to deter smoking. A cancerous lung, encased in plastic, also was on display. For the really desperate, merchants were offering the `` longevity brand electrotherapy device for helping give up smoking and protecting health.'' The device, which sold for about $ 4, consists of battery-powered electrodes attached to the cheeks and is activated every time the user gets the urge for a smoke. There was no indication whether <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most famous chain-smoker, senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, complied with the government's request to stop smoking for a day. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has 300 million smokers, the world's highest number. From the Pantheon to the <LOCATION> Via </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Veneto </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, volunteers handed out baskets of apples with the message `` A piece of fruit is OK, but cigarette smoke is n't. An apple goes farther than the cigarette.'' They also walked around town asking smokers to put out their cigarettes in exchange for flowers or apples. Colorfully dressed women in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, collected money for the fight against cancer. One of them who stood in <LOCATION> Calvin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> downtown said she collected the equivalent of more than $ 200 from passersby. According to WHO, 2.5 million people die each year from tobacco-related diseases, including lung cancer, chronic bronchitis, emphysema and heart disease. WHO says this represents one death every 13 seconds. The organization estimates that, in industrialized countries, one-third of all people over 15 are smokers, while in the Third World about half of all males and 10 percent of females over 15 are smokers. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, a former supporter of the tobacco industry, was given an award for his `` candid change of views'' that led him to write in 1986 that he had become `` increasingly active in attempting to spare people from the tobacco addiction,'' <ORGANIZATION> WHO </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Hagman </PERSON>, star of the TV series `` <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>,'' was commended for serving as chairman for eight years of the `` Great American Smokeout.'' WHO said that due to his influence, tobacco is never portrayed on `` <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> was honored for pledging in 1981 never to smoke in public and subsequently quitting. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, which is known worldwide for its fine cigars, participated in the no-smoking day. Despite being a major tobacco producer, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has launched a strong anti-smoking campaign. <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> was praised for being the first carrier in the world to fly regular smoke-free routes internationally, and <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> `` for introducing the smoke-free four-hour flight in 1978, and for being the first to make all internal flights smoke-free, from January 1982.'' In July, South African Airways banned smoking on all domestic flights.
