<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAARLEM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police found the body of a kidnapped Dutch tycoon buried in a forest after his abductor admitted murdering his captive seven months ago and led authorities to the grave, officials said Thursday. The discovery Wednesday night of the body of grocery baron <PERSON> Gerrit </PERSON> <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON> ended the nation's longest kidnap case. <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON>'s body was dug up near the northeastern village of <LOCATION> Renkum </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Theo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bot </PERSON>, a spokesman for the prosecutor's office An unemployed architect admitted kidnapping <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON>, 56, on Sept. 9, 1987, and shooting him to death a few hours later, <PERSON> Bot </PERSON> said. Most of the ransom of 8 million guilders -LRB- about $ 4.3 million -RRB- and 1,200 diamonds paid by <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON>'s family was found in the suspect's home, along with the gun used to kill <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bot </PERSON> said. The case became known as the `` Heijn Affair'' and, despite a news blackout, dominated headlines throughout the nation. It is the first modern Dutch kidnapping case in which a prominent victim was killed. In line with police procedure, authorities refused to identify the suspect except by his initials, P.E. They said he lived in the village of <LOCATION> Landsmeer </LOCATION>, a few miles north of <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> and about 75 miles from where <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON> was buried. The 45-year-old architect was arrested early Wednesday at home, police said. Bot said police also took into custody the man's wife and his three children, aged 17 to 25, but he said it was unclear if they had any role in the crime. <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON> was kidnapped at gunpoint Sept. 9 as he left his home for a dentist's appointment. He was vice-chairman of the family-run <ORGANIZATION> Ahold </ORGANIZATION> grocery concern, which operates the nation's largest supermarket chain, <PERSON> Albert </PERS