ashington </LOCATION> assurances it would not launch a pre-emptive strike against the missiles. The purchase angered a group of 30 senators who have threatened to try to block further arms sales to <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration apparently intends to go ahead with its plan to provide new equipment for U.S.-built AWACS radar planes. `` That's obviously got great value,'' the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said, defending the deal. In contrast to <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> efforts, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> evidently has made headway with <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> over a new constitution for <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. He said he had `` quite constructive discussions'' with President <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> on Tuesday. The Syrians evidently are prepared to help devise new constitutional guidelines that would rearrange the division of power among <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s warring factions. Describing the plight of the country, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official traveling with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> recalled that `` people said a year ago, two years ago, this is anarchy, total anarchy. Two years later, it's worse. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s kind words for <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> contrasted with his cool approach to <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>. On Wednesday, he urged <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> to regard negotiations with his neighbors as the most fundamental element in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s security. In an interview with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> television, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> lauded <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> as `` a man of peace'' and said the questions he posed about the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plan showed he was engaged in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> effort. Sizing up his five-day visit, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said `` I think it's been worthwhile and we've made a little progress here and there. But it comes very hard and slow and I do n't want to exaggerate the progress that has been made. But it is important to keep at it.''
