<HEAD>Iran Claims Baghdad Bombed; Iraq Fires Back With 11 Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said its warplanes sneaked through Iraqi radar into <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> on Thursday and bombed a military base and oil refinery in the city, killing or wounding dozens of <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> soldiers. It was the first reported bombing of the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> capital in three years. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> denied the city was hit, but the ferocity of <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> attacks later gave some credence to the Iranian claims. Both sides bombarded each other's cities and towns with missiles and reported scores of civilian casualties. A <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> team arrived in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> to investigate Iraqi allegations that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> used chemical weapons in a March 30-31 battle in northeastern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> accused <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> of using chemical weapons in the same battle. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s deputy foreign minister, <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Larijani </PERSON>, met with <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> to discuss a cease-fire in the 7 -LCB- - year-old war <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said squadrons of its fighter-bombers dodged <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s radar net and the heavy air defenses around <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> just after 6 a.m. and dropped bombs in two raids, 10 minutes apart. They were the first reported bombing raids on <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, a city of 5 million, since March 1985 and came as <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> marked the 41st anniverary of the founding of its ruling <ORGANIZATION> Baath </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, monitored in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, said the air raids `` completely caught the enemy by surprise.'' It said warplanes bombed the al-Doura refinery and the <PERSON> Khafaji </PERSON> military camp on <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>'s southern outskirts, `` killing or wounding dozens of soldiers'' and leaving their targets on fire. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said all its planes returned safely. It did not say how many were involved in the raid. The official <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, also monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, quoted military communiques as saying only one Iranian jet got through but was driven off by anti-aircraft fire before it could drop any bombs. It said the plane was later shot down by <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> interceptors over western <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. In one of their most widespread missile barrages, the Iraqis reported firing 11 long-range missiles: four at <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, three at the central city of <LOCATION> Isfahan </LOCATION>, two at the industrial town of <LOCATION> Karaj </LOCATION>, northwest of the capital, and one each at the holy city of <LOCATION> Qom </LOCATION> and the northwestern city of <LOCATION> Tabriz </LOCATION>. It was the first time <LOCATION> Karaj </LOCATION> had been hit by a missile since the war began in September 1980. In retaliation, the Iranians said they fired two long-range missiles into <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> and 13 short-range projectiles into the ports of <LOCATION> Basra </LOCATION> and Umm Qasr, an Iraqi naval base. They also reported bombing <LOCATION> Basra </LOCATION> and Umm Qasr and the northern Iraqi city of <LOCATION> Erbil </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION> said Iranian warplanes attacked <LOCATI