<HEAD>Bennett Says Government Should Pay Parochial Schools To Teach
Tough Kids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> NEW </LOCATION> <LOCATION> YORK </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Education Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> called on Catholic schools Thursday to enroll the `` worst 5 or 10 percent'' of public school students and ask state or local government to help pay for teaching them. His proposal, made in an address to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s 85th annual convention here, was greeted warmly by <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> educators but was challenged as unconstitutional by several leading public education groups. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> dubbed his proposal `` Project Voluntas,'' Latin for good will. Parochial schools already have done an exemplary job teaching minority students, who make up 22 percent of their 2.5 million total enrollment, he told the gathering. But he said <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> educators have not been effective in telling outsiders how much better they've done with difficult students compared with many public schools. `` The challenge is simple,'' said <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, a parochial school product himself. `` Show educators around this country what works.'' `` Seek out the poor, the disadvantaged, the disruptive, the dropout, and take them in, educate them, and then ask society for fair recompense for your efforts,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. He said Catholic schools should ask state or local governments for `` half the price, or two-thirds of the price, or something like that,'' of whatever it would have cost to teach such students in public school. Governments `` would, I believe, be receptive to constitutionally sound efforts to pay for the education of such students.'' But if government ca n't or wo n't, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said, `` business and others in the private sector would surely want to support such a worthwhile endeavor.'' `` I think there's a good deal of possibility for it,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON>, director of education for the Archdiocese of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> which enrolls 180,000 kindergarten through 12th-grade students. `` We do not subscribe to the absolute separation of church and state that others who oppose us do. The so-called wall of separation is not in the -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- Constitution,'' he said. But `` Project Voluntas'' was condemned by <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Marx </PERSON>, associate executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> Administrators: `` Every thoughtful American should be appalled by the secretary's remarks. He constantly hits people in the public schools below the belt and they are the ones who are working hardest to deal with the problems of at-risk youth.'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, called <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>'s proposal `` a welcome challenge to Catholic schools,'' but questioned its constitutionality. `` If the Catholic schools are going to do what they are supposed to do, that is, teach <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> beliefs in an integrated way throughout the curriculum, it would be unconstitutional on its face'' to support such schools with public funds, <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>'s proposal is the latest of several he has advanced, largely unsuccessfully, aimed at expanding educational options including the private school sector. His ideas have included tuition tax credits and tuition vouchers that would offer tax breaks or direct assistance to parents of private school children. But with prospects bleak for tax credits or vouchers, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> urged <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> schools to take the initiative and prove that they deserve community support. <PERSON> Roxanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradshaw </PERSON>, secretary-treasurer of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest teacher union, dismissed <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>'s idea as `` a back-door approach to finance private schools.'' `` On the one hand, he's saying that money is irrelevant to a quality education. On the other hand, he's saying the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> schools need more money to educate at-risk children. Which is it, Secretary <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>? Does money matter, or does n't it?'' she said. But <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said Catholic schools `` have often done more with less.'' Citing studies by <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> sociologist <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said the dropout rate among parochial high school sophomores nationwide is just 3 percent, compared with 14 percent in public schools. Median tuition at <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> elementary schools is about $ 700, and $ 1,500 for high schools, compared with an average of about $ 4,500 a year to educate a child in public school, said <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>. Still, he said, more than 4,000 parochial schools have closed in the last 20 years, and part of the blame is with <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> schools themselves for being reticent in proclaiming their excellence. `` I believe that it is in your interest to take up this challenge,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. `` It is also in society's interest. Catholic schools should n't be closing. And disadvantaged children should be getting a good education.''
