<HEAD>Budget Director, Postal Workers Clash on Privatization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal budget director <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> pushed the idea of turning over the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to private companies Thursday, as about 100 picketing postal workers accused him of trying to destroy the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mail. New Postmaster General <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, appearing at the same meeting, opposed the privatization idea and called for greater discretion for the service to manage its finances and set rates. Picketers said they had no dispute with <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> appeared at a seminar sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Cato </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a conservative policy research organization. `` There is no good reason why -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- should remain part of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, and no good reason why it should enjoy a monopoly over the delivery of letter mail,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. He accused the service of wanting to be a government-protected monopoly when it comes to letter mail and a federal agency when it comes to federal subsidies and other benefits. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> denied allegations from the postal unions and others that his <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> has tried to intrude into management of the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which is an independent government agency. He said his problem is not with the 800,000 postal workers but with the system which he said is `` not working particularly well right now.'' `` If given the opportunity to compete, I'm sure the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, including its employees, would do very well indeed,'' he said. `` <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, he's a jerk; privatization just wo n't work,'' chanted members of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, who obstructed the front door of the hotel where the seminar was held until police arrived and ordered them to the sides. <PERSON> Moe </PERSON> <PERSON> Biller </PERSON>, president of the 365,000-member union, called <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s proposal `` cockeyed'' and said it would cause chaos with the mail and increase costs to the public. `` No responsible businessman has advocated privatization,'' <PERSON> Biller </PERSON> said. Wearing a sign accusing <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> of betraying postal reform, <PERSON> Biller </PERSON> stood at the doorway of the seminar room for a few minutes before the budget director arrived. <PERSON> Biller </PERSON> later followed <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> into the hotel and shook his hand, saying he wanted to debate him. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, who took over the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> March 1, said it should not be operated for profit. `` It should be the most efficient, reliable, convenient public service in the country,'' he said. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said he senses even among advocates of privatization a desire to effect only gradual changes. `` I sense a desire to go slowly, a recognition that the mail system, like <ORGANIZATION> Humpty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dumpty </ORGANIZATION>, once broken, could n't be put back together again,'' he said. He said that if privatization means eliminating the letter-mail monopoly, skimming off the profitable segments of the postal business or busting the postal unions, he opposes it. But the postmaster general said he was willing to explore the idea of privatization that would promote efficiency through more sharing of the workload with major mailers and more contracting of non-critical postal services.
