<HEAD>Amid Missile Attacks, Iran Ready For Parliamentary Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Under the threat of <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> missiles and air raids, Iranians vote Friday for a new parliament that will be a key factor in determining the course of the Islamic revolution. The election of a new 270-seat Majlis, or parliament, will be vital in determining who will hold power in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> after the <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> dies. He is 87 and reported in poor health. The vote is seen as a test of strength between fundamentalists who support an Islamic-style capitalism and radicals who favor a socialist-style economy. Iranian leaders fear that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> will blitz <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and other major cities with a barrage of missiles to disrupt the elections, and they have urged <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s more than 20 million voters to turn out in a massive show of defiance. `` The people will attend the election with God's help, even if they are under missile attack. I will vote under any circumstances,'' <PERSON> Khomeni </PERSON> said last week. He added, `` The people must beware and choose candidates among ... those loyal to <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>. They must choose their deputies from among those who have suffered from poverty and are real Moslems, not those who obey <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Islam.'' About 1,400 candidates, approved by provincial and city governors controlled by Interior Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON>, will be running. Tha's about 400 more than ran in the last election in 1984. There will be 30 female candidates. It's the first time women have run for <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s parliament. It is the third parliamentary poll since <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s 1979 Islamic revolution toppled the late <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON>. Iranian leaders have said the election will be a crucial test for the Islamic form of democracy, and the campaigning has shown sharp differences between rival factions over the future course of domestic policy. The 7 -LCB- - year-old Iran-Iraq war, the country's most pressing problem, has not figured in the campaigning <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s undisputed patriarch, has decreed that the war will not end until his adversary, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>, has been toppled The conservatives essentially identify with the religious fundamentalists, who base their concept on a narrow interpretation of the teachings of the Koran, <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>'s holy book, which protects private property and free enterprise. Their protagonists, seeking tighter state control, are likely to garner widespread support from the increasingly discontented poor who have to cope with runaway inflation and a flourishing black market. Cigarettes cost $ 10 a pack, red meat is about $ 16 a pound, and eggs are $ 8.50 a dozen. House Speaker <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s closest aides and considered a pragmatist on most issues, is expected to be reelected along with most of the leading figures in the hierachy. But the hardliners, such as Prime Minister <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON>, are expected to make some gains, a development that could have far-reaching effects on the shape of the revolution in the post-Khomeini era. None of the candidates is running on party tickets. The last formal party, the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s clerics used to gain power in the early days of the revolution, was disbanded by <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> last June because it was torn by factionalism. The candidates will represent various shades of Islamic and revolutionary thinking. The results may not be known for 10 days, and the new parliament may not sit until June while a new cabinet is screened and nominees scrutinized by the deputies.
