<HEAD>US Soybean Producers Facing Heavy Competition From Abroad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 World demand for high-protein, oil-rich soybeans has led other producing countries into a fierce competition with American farmers, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report said Thursday. Soybeans have the potential to supplement diets of low-income people in the Third World, where it will be important to gain consumer acceptance for soybeans and soy-fortified foods, said <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Vocke </PERSON>, an agriculture and trade analyst in the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> `` A historical view shows that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dominance of world soybean trade, founded on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> research and development in the 1940s and 1950s, declined in the 1980s as <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries, spurred by high prices, developed large-scale production and processing facilities,'' he said. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> have been the main <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> competitors in the international soybean market. <PERSON> Vocke </PERSON> added: `` Their success, mainly in temperate areas, has not been duplicated in tropical areas elsewhere in the Third World.'' The major factors behind the increased demand for soybeans in the Third World are rising incomes and population growth, <PERSON> Vocke </PERSON> said. As families have more to spend, their demand increases for meat and other food products such as margarine and cooking oil. `` Fierce export competition with the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> for these markets, as well as the developed country market, will likely continue,'' <PERSON> Vocke </PERSON> said. `` The expansion of large-scale soybean production in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will continue as long as soybean prices are high enough for Brazilian farmers to profitably open new lands for soybeans.'' Further encouragement would be in the Brazilian government's willingness to develop the rural transportation system connecting the new lands to ocean ports, he said `` If the price of soybeans is high relative to other crops, farmers in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and elsewhere will find it profitable to switch even more of their existing cropland to soybeans,'' <PERSON> Vocke </PERSON> said.
