<HEAD>FCC Dismisses Five Indecency Complaints Against Broadcasters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Please note that grafs 11 and 12, ``Another complaint ...
double entendre,'' contain material that may be offensive to some
readers''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday dismissed five indecency complaints, including one against a television station that aired a sex-education program for teen-agers and another against a radio station that apparantly aired a reading of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON>'s `` Ulysses.'' In four of the cases, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said the material involved did not violate the agency's decency standards. It said thre fifth case did not contain sufficient information to determine the context of the material aired. A complaint filed against <ORGANIZATION> KING-TV </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, cited a program called `` Teen Sex, What About the Kids?'' which included what the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> described as `` frank discussions of sexual topics, the use of sex organ models and the simulated demonstration of various birth control devices.'' In a letter to the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> couple who complained, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said that while the program contained references to sexual and excretory organs and activities, the references `` in context, were not ` vulgar,' ` lewd' or ` shocking.' Nor were they made in a pandering or titillating manner.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> judges material to be indecent if it `` depicts or describes, in terms patently offensive as measured by contemporary community standards for the broadcast medium, sexual or excretory organs or activities.'' The agency also says it will examine the context of the material. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> has said indecent material may be broadcast between midnight and 6 a.m. because there is little risk children would be in the audience then. Obscene material, however, can not be aired at any time. Such material is defined as appealing to the prurient interest and lacking serious artistic, literary, political or scientific value. Broadcasters are challenging the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s year-old decency standards in court, charging the guidelines are vague. They say the commission has refused to identify specific material that would be deemed indecent under the standards. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> has said broadcasters should be guided by the decisions the agency makes in the cases that come before it. A complaint against <ORGANIZATION> WBAI-FM </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pacifica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> station in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, described portions of an unidentified program that the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said appeared to be a reading from the `` Penelope'' chapter of `` Ulysses.'' Assuming the program was a reading from the classic work, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said, `` we would not expect that the commission would find such -LRB- sexual and excretory -RRB- references, dispersed as they would have been throughout the three-hour reading of this work of literature, to be patently offensive.'' Another complaint the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> dismissed had been filed by the mayor of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourne </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, against WTMA-AM, <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, for airing a political advertisement opposing his proposal to put a clock on the City Hall. Toward the end of the ad, someone shouts `` clocksucker.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> also found the song `` I Want to Kiss Her, But ...,'' aired by <ORGANIZATION> WTRG-FM </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, was not indecent, despite its use of double entendre. `` The lyrics at issue here are not such that they are capable of only one, sexual meaning. Rather, the lyrics are capable of two meanings _ one innocent, one sexual,'' the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said. The commission ruled last April in a case involving <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> disc jockey <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON> that double entendre and innuendo could be deemed indecent when they were mingled with explicit references that made the material capable of only a sexually explicit meaning. The <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s series `` Heimat,'' about the life of three German families from the end of World War I to the 1960s, was the target of another complaint because of scenes containing sexual activity. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said the complaint, filed against WCET-TV, <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, did not contain sufficient information to determine the context of the material. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, a WCET executive, said the series that aired on about 70 PBS stations last October and November contained some nudity, but he said it was relevant to the story line and the characters. `` Without those scenes a large part of the content would not have made sense,'' he said.
