<HEAD>For Artists, Horrors of Hiroshima Live On</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The world changed for the Marukis when they left their small plot of land near <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> three days after it was destroyed by an atomic bomb. For millions born after 1945, the devastation of <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> is history. For <ORGANIZATION> Iri </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Toshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Maruki </PERSON>, it was a revelation that led to the creation of murals depcting the horrors of war. The two are subjects of the film `` Hellfire: A Journey from <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION>,'' produced by filmmaker <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Junkerman </PERSON> and nominated for a 1988 Academy Award as best documentary feature. <PERSON> Maruki </PERSON>, born in <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> 86 years ago, and his wife, 76, went to <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> on Aug. 9, 1945, the same day an atomic bomb was dropped on <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION>, to check on family members. He had lost his father, uncle, two nieces and numerous friends in the inferno, which killed an estimated 130,000 people. Both say the death and destruction left by the bomb remains a living memory. `` How can we forget?'' <PERSON> Maruki </PERSON> said. `` The horror is always in our mind. The stench of death was in our nostrils for three or four weeks.'' He and Mrs. <PERSON> Maruki </PERSON> were interviewed Thursday at the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION>, which is displaying some of their works _ powerful ink canvases including some of the `` <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> Panels,'' `` <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>,'' and `` The Battle of <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION>.'' The two are scheduled to receive honorary doctorates from the college. Titled `` Surviving Visions,'' it is the first <PERSON> Maruki </PERSON> exhibition in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since 1970. The artists, who spent a month in the devastated city, describe this work as `` a procession of ghosts, with hands held before them ... -LRB- who -RRB- pushed on, dragging their burned bodies, falling and piling into one another, groaning and dying. `` One lone child slept innocently, with unburned skin,'' they write in a an exhibit catalog. `` Perhaps it survived, sheltered by its mother's breast.'' One of the `` <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> Panels,'' `` Ghosts,'' completed in 1950, depicts some of the dead and dying, naked, their bodies charred, their faces anguished. `` Death of American Prisoners of War'' is a 1971 canvas depicting a tragedy that was taboo in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for decades, the massacre of 23 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> POWs by enraged survivors of the bombing. `` We trembled as we painted the death of the American prisoners of war,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Maruki </PERSON> wrote. The victims' manacled corpses are intertwined with erotic nude figures of their wives and lovers back home. A dark, menacing mass of enraged Japanese crowds the periphery of the drawings. `` Auschwitz'' resulted from a trip to the former death camp in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, where 3 million Jews and other inmates were gassed or starved to death by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>. Completed in 1977, the work's eight somber panels pay tribute to Holocaust victims and survivors. The <PERSON> Marukis </PERSON> said their art educates generations born too late to experience the horrors of World War II. `` The kids do n't know because they're not taught in school,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Maruki </PERSON>, suggesting that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> still was reluctant to come to grips with a painful period in its history. `` I suspect that the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> is somehow maneuvering not to teach -LRB- this -RRB- modern history to children.''
