<SECOND>AM-Alzheimer's Disease,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Confirm Early Brain Sign of Alzheimer's Disease</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to fix typo in slug.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SPEER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists have confirmed the presence of an abnormal protein in normal-looking brain cells in Alzheimer's disease patients, adding evidence that it may be an early contributor to the disease Further study may lead to a way of battling the memory-decaying condition before its effects are irreversible, they said Thursday. `` You can imagine how exciting it would be if we had a way of intervening before there has been much irreversible damage,'' <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Damasio </PERSON>, head of the neurology department at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION>, said at a news conference. There is no known treatment or cure for Alzheimer's disease, which the scientist said affects nearly 3 million Americans and is the single most common cause of mental decline in older people. The results of <PERSON> Damasio </PERSON>'s study, done in collaboration with <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoesen </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> and brain chemists at the <ORGANIZATION> Albert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Einstein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, were to be published Friday in <ORGANIZATION> Annals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Neurology </ORGANIZATION>, the journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Neurological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Alzheimer's is centered in cells which transmit signals to and from the memory center in the brain, <PERSON> Damasio </PERSON> said. He compared the disease's action to a computer with faulty input and output lines. That limits the functioning of the computer `` while not doing too much damage to the computer itself,'' <PERSON> Damasio </PERSON> said. The study, done by autopsies on the brains of Alzheimer's patients, shows that the disease is very specific in the brain cells it attacks, <PERSON> Damasio </PERSON> said The protein confirmed by the study was previously idenfified and named A68, by Dr. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> at <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>. `` It looks like the disease knows its way and is very choosey,'' he said.
