<SECOND>AM-Radon Response, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0720,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Finds Some US Agencies Weak on Radon Threat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs pvs 15th graf, ``The department,'' to update with HUD
comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal agencies involved in housing, hamstrung by a lack of congressional guidance, are doing little or nothing about the threat from cancer-causing radon, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. Although environmental officials say radon causes up to 20,000 cancer deaths a year, the housing agencies see little responsibility to respond, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, an investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said in a report. The report scrutinized the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Sen. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, who requested and released the year-long <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> study, called its results `` disturbing.'' `` While millions of Americans are at risk, federal bureaucrats ... sit on their hands,'' said <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON>, who chairs the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s environmental oversight subcommittee Radon is a naturally occurring, odorless and colorless gas. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> says radon may cause from 5,000 to 20,000 lung-cancer deaths annually. A byproduct of decaying, underground uranium, radon rises from the ground and can seep into buildings. Trapped indoors, the gas poses health threats that can far surpass heavy smoking or inordinate exposure to X-rays. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> noted that <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> was assigned by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to lead the attack on radon. So far, it said, `` much work remains'' on <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s acceptable, but slow-moving strategy <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON> asked the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> to evaluate the radon response by federal agencies who administer housing or subsidize home ownership. Investigators found an overall lack of response, `` ranging from responding to a few site-specific problems to not being involved with indoor radon at all,'' the report said. Officials of the housing agencies are largely unaware of radon problems. and are uncertain whether they have any legal responsibility, it said. Courts appear unlikely to hold federal agencies liable in cases arising from radon, it added. The report said that while <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s radon mandate is clear, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has said nothing to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>, the VA or FmHA. In addition, it said, the agencies are further confused by the lack of an <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> standard for how much radon is too much. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> secretary and <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator should meet to `` define their respective responsibilities and planned actions.'' <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, could consider specifying how it wants other agencies to deal with radon. it said. The report's poorest grades went to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>, which administers the home mortgage insurance program and subsidies for public and Indian housing. It said `` <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> has reacted to radon hazards in a limited, piecemeal manner.'' Department spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Glavin </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> has no overall radon policy, but has reacted to specific cases of suspected pollution. The VA, which administers a guaranteed and insured loan program for veterans buying homes, has `` no radon policy and essentially is not involved with the issue,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. VA spokesman <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> said the agency, in backing mortgage loans, generally defers to state law on housing construction and safety standards. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>'s highest grades went to the FmHA, which lends mortgage money in rural areas. According to the report, <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION> has trained its field workers in radon measurement and mitigation, and is at work on an overall policy. <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Ence </PERSON> said, `` We've been on top of this for several years.'' Only the Park Serice, which operates housing for visitors and staff, has pursued comprehensive radon testing at those dwellings and its administrative buildings, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> found.
