<HEAD>Simon Suspends Campaign But Holds Delegates</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Moves up grafs 15-18 pvs to grafs 9-12 to raise Simon comment
on delegates</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> suspended his stalled presidential campaign Thursday but held onto his 170 delegates in hopes of influencing the choice of a nominee at the Democratic national convention in July. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> immediately blasted <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> for keeping the delegates, saying many of them were rightfully his. `` In a year that has already seen many surprises, no one knows what twists and turns may develop between now and then,'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> told a news conference. `` There will be many encounters with fate before the contest is ultimately decided in a wide-open convention.'' In a quasi-withdrawal, <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said he would no longer actively campaign for the nomination but said he technically would remain a candidate even though he conceded he has `` no illusions that the nomination will come my way.'' `` I want to have an impact on who the party nominates,'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said. `` I want to have an impact on the whole process there -LRB- at the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> convention -RRB-, and on where we go.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, however, said <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>'s move was a less-than-honorable one, and that he ought to release his delegates. `` If one is not in the race one ought to indicate a form of honorable withdrawal at which time whoever got second place in that state will get those delegates. That's what Mr. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> did. It was the honorable and the fair thing to do,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> dropped out of the Democratic race last month. `` I would hope that in time Mr. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> likewise _ now that he has made the decision to leave the race _ will leave so honorably, and hide behind no technicalities to block those as my delegates which in fact belong to me,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>'s decision to nominally remain a candidate and retain his delegates means he holds onto 47 at-large delegates won in the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> primary. Had he formally withdrawn from the race, those delegates would have gone automatically to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who finished second in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. Asked whether his move could be seen as an effort to deprive <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> of support, <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said, `` I am sure it is not perceived by <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> as a stop-Jackson effort.'' He said he had spoken to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and the other two remaining Democratic candidates _ <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> _ about his plans. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said he would keep a lock on the 170 delegates he has won and an aide said he hoped to perhaps attract a few more by the time the party's last primaries end on June 7. At that point, <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said, he will meet with the delegates and decide what to do next. `` I owe something to those delegates,'' he said. A total of 2,082 delegates is needed to nominate a candidate. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> showed early strength in the Democratic campaign, finishing a close second in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>'s first-in-the-nation caucuses. But he dropped to third in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> and failed to rebound as the primary season wore on, except for a lone win in his home state. His bid bottomed out Tuesday in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, where he finished last with just 5 percent of the vote. He blamed his campaign's precipitous decline on a failure to effectively communicate his message of traditional Democratic party values, and on a lack of money, but said he did not see his failure as a rejection of those values. `` I do belive we have to have a government that cares, and the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people believe that, too _ that I know,'' he said to the cheers of supporters who packed a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearing room where he made his announcement. `` I really believe the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people are ready for a candidate who says let's put unemployed people to work, let's have quality schools for this nation,'' he said. But <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said he still is concerned, as he said at the outset of his campaign a year ago, that the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> could `` become a clone'' of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> by forgetting its past. `` We ca n't build the kind of nation we want if we simply pander to the wishes of the rich and powerful,'' he said. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, 59, stayed true to his liberal background during the campaign. With his trademark bow-tie and claim to the plain-spoken legacy of <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>, he said often that voters were `` ready for something other than the slick, packaged product.'' He proposed long-term health care for the elderly, a public works program for the unemployed and new education initiatives, and promised that as president he would balance the budget in three years. But critics questioned how he could reconcile promises to set up expensive new programs while also claiming to be a fiscal conservative who would balance the budget.
