<HEAD>Moslem Factions Battle, 39 Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDMOND SHEDID</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABATIYEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fighting raged for the third day in a showdown for dominance in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> between Shiite Moslem militias allied with <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Police said 39 people were killed and 96 wounded. Casualties for the three days stood at 51 dead and 130 wounded, according to police figures The battle is between Justice Minister <PERSON> Nabih </PERSON> <PERSON> Berri </PERSON>'s mainstream militia Amal, supported by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, which is loyal to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. It continued despite repeated cease-fire appeals from the highest Shiite clerics. That may indicate <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> wants to crus <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s challenge to its role as the main power broker in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, where the Syrians have 25,000 troops. A police spokesman said Amal units with armored personnel carriers advanced about noon into the coastal town of <LOCATION> Ghaziyeh </LOCATION>, a key <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> stronghold. By nightfall, <PERSON> Amal </PERSON> recaptured the village after `` ferocious house-to-house fighting,'' police reported. They said most of the day's casualties occurred in <LOCATION> Ghaziyeh </LOCATION>, five miles south of <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION>, the provincial capital of south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> said its fighters had captured and disarmed several <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> militiamen. `` With the recapture of <LOCATION> Ghaziyeh </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> has established undisputed control over the whole of south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> as well as the main coastal highway,'' which links the predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> south to the rest of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, the communique said. Trouble between Amal and <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGAN