comes from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has been favorable to the Panamanians,'' he said. `` The people of the world know that the recipes formulated in the imperial capitals, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, never are favorable to the interests of the people.'' He added: `` It is absolutely necessary for Gen. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to abandon his post. For us, this is fundamental.'' Leaders of the two parties have joined demonstrations, strikes and other protests of the Civic Crusade, while differing with some of its policies and generally favoring a harder line. Popular Action, for example, refused to join the Crusade, Authentic Panamanians and three other parties in agreeing to a proposal for dialogue with the government mediated by the Roman Catholic church. Political parties linked most closely with the Civic Crusade are the Democratic Christians and the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, known as <PERSON> Molirena </PERSON>. Those two parties, the Crusade and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> all recognize deposed President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> as the constitutional head of state. Popular Action and the Authentic Panamanian Party do not. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> orchestrated the ouster of <LOCATION> Delvalle </LOCATION> on Feb. 26, the day after <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> tried to fire the general. <PERSON> Zuniga </PERSON>, brother of a former Popular Action presidential candidate, said the movement `` will center its fight on the original principles of the Civic Crusade.'' He and <PERSON> Arosemena </PERSON> denied its creation amounted to a split with the Civic Crusade, but rejected a proposal for dialogue with the government mediated by <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON>, the Roman Catholic archbishop. They also demanded an end to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic sanctions, which some Civic Crusade leaders have said should be strengthened, and opposed the idea of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intervention. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should not continue economic and military action against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Arosemena </PERSON> said. `` The Panamanian people are capable of solving their own problems.'' The last of 1,300 additional <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers arrived Thursday at <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> outside <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, completing a buildup meant to provide greater security for the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>, American installations and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens. Late Wednesday, the government said it had issued arrest warrants for three leading opponents, including <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, who has been in hiding in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. It also asked <ORGANIZATION> Interpol </ORGANIZATION>, the international police organization, to arrest <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Galindo </PERSON>, a former ambassador to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON>, who was <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>'s envoy in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and remains there. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` would regard any efforts by the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> regime to attempt arrests or pro