<HEAD>Aliens Urged To Apply for Amnesty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Reagan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday urged illegal aliens eligible for amnesty to take advantage of a citizenship offer that expires May 4. Presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said in a statement that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` urges those who may be eligible to attain this privilege and benefit to do so promptly.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>'s statement noted that more than 1.25 million illegal aliens have come forward to seek legal status under the `` general amnesty'' clause of sweeping immigration legislation <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed a little more than a year ago. Among the law's amnesty provisions are requirements that the applicant be free of a criminal record and have lived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continously since before 1982. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>'s statement took no notice of a bill approved March 31 by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that would extend the May 4 amnesty application deadline to Nov. 30. The spokesman said that among the more than 1 million aliens who have applied so far for citizenship are people comprising nearly every nationality. `` By their actions in this country over the past six years, they have demonstrated that they deserve the privilege of remaining here in a fully legal status, without having to live in an underground society and fearing discovery of their unlawful existence,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` But the time to apply for citizenship under this ` amnesty' provision will end on May 4, 1988,'' it said `` There may still be those who for one reason or another have not taken advantage of this onetime opportunity.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` calls on all Americans to do whatever is in their power to remind their neighbors, friends, co-workers and others, who may be living outside our immigration laws ... that the time is growing short for them to come forward and join us as recognized members of our nation and society.'' Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> figures show that besides the more than 1.25 million general amnesty applications, there have been roughly 300,000 applications for citizenship under a separate program for farmers and farm workers. Of the applications that have reached the decision stage, only 12,700 have been rejected and 782,000 have been approved. The remaining applications are in the clearance pipeline at INS.
