<FIRST>r a AM-CDC--Flu     04-07 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC--Flu,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Separate Flu Variations Floating Around U.S.</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release 6:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four variations of the winter's most prevalent flu type have been circulating in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and that could pose a tricky question for researchers trying to concoct next winter's flu vaccine, health officials said Thursday. The 1987-88 vaccine did not protect patients against the various viruses as well as it could have against the single virus expected to predominate, said <PERSON> Suzanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaventa </PERSON>, a researcher with the national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. `` There have been people coming down with influenza who did receive the vaccine,'' Ms. <PERSON> Gaventa </PERSON> said. Although the current flu season is winding down, some activity continues, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> reported `` widespread'' flu outbreaks last week _ covering areas including more than half the population. Eight other states, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, reported less severe `` regional'' outbreaks. Late last year, as the 1987-88 influenza season began, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> saw evidence of an apparent `` drift'' in the predominant flu type, which this past winter was the one researchers call Type A-H3N2, one of three major types of flu. The predominant A-H3N2 virus, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said at the time, was `` drifting'' away from the <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> flu, the A-H3N2 strain the 1987-88 flu vaccine was designed to stop, and toward a somewhat different form. On Thursday the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said it had now identified four different variants of A-H3N2 flu virus circulating in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in recent months; they are known as the <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> flu, the <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION> flu, the <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> flu and the <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> flu. `` Co-circulation of two or more closely related ... variants in a single season is not uncommon,'' the Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said in its weekly report. But the four different viruses present something for <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> immunization experts to think about, Ms. <PERSON> Gaventa </PERSON> said. Each year, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Immunization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Practices </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> recommends which flu types the next winter's vaccine should protect against and which specific strains of those types should be targeted. The reports of the four different A-H3N2 strains circulating this past winter `` will be used in deciding which H3N2 antigen to use'' in next winter's vaccine, Ms. <PERSON> Gaventa </PERSON> said. `` They'll take this information, along with information provided from other areas, and put that together and try to determine which strain is most likely to circulate next season,'' she said. A single flu vaccine can not protect optimally against four different flu viruses belonging to the same type, she said. Instead, vaccine experts will try to determine which virus to target and how much protection that vaccine might offer against closely related viruses. <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> recommends flu vaccine particularly for older people and those who might be prone to severe complications from the flu. Type A-H3N2 flu has long been associated with `` excess mortality,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said, and many states have reported outbreaks of flu-like illness this winter in nursing homes, where patients might be particularly vulnerable.
</TEXT>
