<HEAD>Accord Appears to Meet U.S. Terms, Officials Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS lede, grafs 6-8 pvs, bgng: State Department, and 14-18,
bgng: The Shultz, to CLARIFY U.S. proposal; ADDS 5 new grafs with
Byrd, Humphrey comments; single name Najib correct in 4th graf</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet-Afghan agreement under which the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> may start pulling out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by May 15 appears to meet <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> conditions on continuing aid to the warring parties, administration sources said Thursday. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was described by his chief of staff, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, as `` cautiously optimistic.'' But <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> still `` wants to see the fine print,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told reporters in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is vacationing. `` We think an agreement now is clearly within reach,'' said one administration source in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> who closely monitors Afghan developments. Administration officials interpreted a statement issued by <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his Afghan ally <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> as `` an indication that they have agreed to our conditions, but we want to know that authoritatively,'' said the source, who spoke on condition of annoymity. The administration is waiting to hear from the Soviets on a proposal advanced by Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> on March 31. He said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ under what is being called a `` gentlemen's agreement'' _ would continue its estimated $ 600 million a year in covert aid to the Afghan guerrillas as long as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> was aiding the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> regime. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said Thursday that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has not budged from the <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> formula, which embodies what diplomats call `` positive symmetry.'' She said the Soviets had rejected a proposal involving `` negative symmetry,'' in which the two sides would end aid shortly after an agreement was signed. `` Our position is clear,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said. `` Such an agreement must be a comprehensive settlement that provides for the prompt withdrawal of all Soviet troops, an independent non-aligned <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, self-determination for the Afghan people and the return of the refugees in safety and honor.'' Two other administration sources involved with <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, also speaking on condition of anonymity, said the next step would be to seek agreement at the United Nations-brokered talks in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on formation of an interim Afghan government during the Soviet withdrawal. `` The parties are going to work very hard on the interim government,'' said one official. `` It is the next item on the agenda. But it is not clear whether it will be part of the agreement.'' The Gorbachev-Najib communique, issued after a surprise meeting between the two in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Tashkent </LOCATION>, said `` the last obstacles to concluding the agreements have now been removed thanks to constructive cooperation of all who are involved in the settlement and favor their immediate signing.'' The declaration said the road was now clear for formation of a coalition government including all political forces in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, `` including those who are currently opposed to one another.'' Many of the guerrillas balked at <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s previous political overtures, which he has billed as `` national reconciliation.'' The administration has seesawed on the question of ending aid to resistance. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had been pushing for cessation of aid to the guerrillas within 60 days of an agreement. But last December, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he would continue sending aid to the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas until the last of the 115,000 Soviet soldiers left <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, acting on a resolution introduced by Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, urged <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in a 77-0 vote to stick to his guns, and at the beginning of March, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> made the tougher line a formal <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> position at the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> The Soviets rejected that, and <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> proposed `` negative symmetry,'' or simultaneous cessation of aid, a softer line than advanced by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in December. But the Soviets rejected that too, and <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> proposed `` positive symmetry,'' which was closer to the positions taken by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> last December and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in February. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> applauded the latest turn of events. `` Secretary <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> has kept me informed of the developments during the last three weeks of negotiations. From our conversations, I believe that my concerns have been met. I want to give this agreement a chance,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said in a statement issued by his office. Another lawmaker who has vocally supported the guerrillas, Sen. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>, was pessimistic about the chances of the proposed agreement. `` If the option to resupply is not in writing, then the government of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> -LRB- which channels aid to the guerrillas -RRB- is going to find itself in under tremendous domestic and international pressure to pinch or sever the arms pipeline,'' <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. At the same time, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> greatly increased its covert arms shipments to the guerrillas, but curtailed shipments of hand-held Stinger anti-aircraft missiles, according to congressional sources who closely track the issue.
