<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 180 tons of material, presumed to be components for cluster bombs, were shipped from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> since June, police said Thursday. Italian law forbids sale or supply of arms to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> or to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which have been at war in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> since September 1980. Officials here said two men were arrested and a third was sought. The shipments were halted with the March 24 seizure at <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Leonardo </PERSON> da Vinci airport of nearly 27 tons of bomb parts about to be loaded on an Iraqi Airways jet bound for <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, said officials of the carabinieri, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s paramilitary police force An added 33 tons of parts, waiting to be transported to the airport and eventually to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, also were seized recently in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, the police said. Customs declarations were falsified to describe the components as parts for furniture or spare parts for home appliances or plumbing repair, the police said, speaking on condition of anonymity. They said documents examined by police showed the <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> ordered the shipments and the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> government provided, for export agents in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, a letter of credit for $ 8 million to cover dealings with Italian factories manufacturing the parts. Cluster bombs, designed to spread shrapnel over a wide area, are an effective anti-personnel weapon. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has used such bombs to break up mass Iranian ground assaults. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> says <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> dropped cluster bombs in <LOCATION> Kurdistan </LOCATION> against villages which it says were also hit by chemical bombs March 16-17. Police reported finding <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> government documents outlining which components were needed for the cluster bombs. A police official said other bomb components, 16 tons in all, were seized at 27 small factories that received the Iraqi orders. A few factories are in the <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> area; others are in <LOCATION> Tuscany </LOCATION>. No one answered at the <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> when called for comment. Police said Thursday the two men arrested were charged with construction, export and illegal holding of war arms. Both worked for an import-export firm in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> that police said arranged the bomb parts delivery. Officers identified them as Iraqi-born <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Kodasi </PERSON>, 30, an Italian citizen, and <PERSON> Hamoudi </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaffar </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasim </PERSON>, 21, of <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>. Police said they a third man sought is an <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION>. They said no charges have been brought against factory officials. The parts ranged from metal tubes and cones, which the factories described as plumbing pieces, to plastic connecting parts listed on the inventory as table legs, police said. Several investigations are being carried out in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> into the alleged supply of weapons to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> by Italian arms manufacturers.
