<HEAD>Up to $9.2 Billion Needed To Upgrade Existing Public Housing,
Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> estimates it will cost up to $ 9.2 billion to make the nation's existing public housing `` decent, safe and sanitary.'' The estimate, in a report issued for publication Friday, is based on inspection of 2,196 units and 3,120 buildings at public housing projects across the country at the end of 1985. It took more than two years and $ 5 million to compile and review the final report which was ordered by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials said. Since then, said <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> deputy assistant secretary <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> <PERSON> MacRae </PERSON>, $ 3.9 billion has been spent. He said another study to be completed this summer will show how much needs to be spent each year to keep public housing at mandatory <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> standards. The study released by <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said repair and renovation of existing units among the 1.3 million dwellings nationwide will cost between $ 7.5 billion and $ 9.2 billion. `` <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> is committed to restoring the public housing stock to decent, safe and sanitary conditions in every instance where that housing is viable,'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said. The report indicates that only 5 percent to 10 percent of public housing is not viable and not worth modernizing. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> mandatory modernization standards include repairs and changes to `` preserve public health and safety, ensure bulding integrity, meet local code requirements and meet federal standards for accessibliity for the handicapped as well as reduction of hazards associated with lead-based paint,'' said a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> statement accompanying the study. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said half the nation's public housing has been in service for between 20 and 40 years. He said that after the backlog is met, additional funds will be needed from federal, state and local governments. The 283-page report, `` Study of the Modernization Needs of the Public and <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION>,'' was based on data gathered by <ORGANIZATION> Abt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. Its estimates cover 11,000 public housing projects, where low-income families live, paying about 30 percent of their incomes as rent. Individual housing authorities own the units, aided by federal assistance and financing. Officials say 3 million Americans live in public housing.
</TEXT>
