<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Church Mediation Collapses; Opposition Splits</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with church suspending mediation effort,
banks said not opening Friday; no pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>LaserPhoto PAN2
^By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it was suspending its effort to mediate <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s political crisis as the first major split appeared in the opposition to Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> archbishop of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, said in a statement he was withdrawing his mediation offer for three reasons: _ Opposition groups refused to talk to the government until it showed it was willing to discuss the departure of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> _ The archbishop had not received <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s `` explicit and personal backing of the initiative'' in writing _ There were no assurances that the four international leaders who proposed the talks could be present The breakdown came a day after <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> ordered the arrests of several leading opponents. The general has defied <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts to force his resignation. In another development, banking and diplomatic sources said <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s banks would not reopen Friday, and possibly not next week. The government said last week it hoped to have banks functioning again Friday. A major rift appeared Thursday in the anti-Noriega opposition, as two parties split from the opposition alliance to form their own anti-government movement. Their leaders argued that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic sanctions are hurting <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s people more than they are damaging <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and the civilian government he controls. <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Arosemena </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuniga </PERSON>, leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, announced formation of the <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> in a break with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crusade </ORGANIZATION>, an alliance of about 200 organizations that has led the 10-month-old effort to oust <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. They told a news conference their movement also is backed by the <ORGANIZATION> Authentic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Panamanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the largest opposition political party. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has supported the Civic Crusade in its effort to remove <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> as chief of the 15,000-member <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>, which include the military and police. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is under indictment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges, which he denies. <PERSON> Zuniga </PERSON> said the new movement rejects any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> influence. `` For us, no recipe that comes from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has been favorable to the Panamanians,'' he said. `` The people of the world know that the recipes formulated in the imperial capitals, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, never are favorable to the interests of the people.'' He added: `` It is absolutely necessary for Gen. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to abandon his post. For us, this is fundamental.'' Leaders of the two parties have joined demonstrations, strikes and other protests of the Civic Crusade, while differing with some of its policies and generally favoring a harder line. Popular Action, for example, refused to join the Crusade, Authentic Panamanians and three other parties in agreeing to the proposal for dialogue with the government mediated by the Catholic church. The dialogue was proposed by Presidents <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, Prime Minister <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and ex-presidents <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Oduber </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>. Political parties linked most closely with the Civic Crusade are the Democratic Christians and the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, known as <PERSON> Molirena </PERSON>. Those two parties, the Crusade and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> all recognize deposed President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> as the constitutional head of state. Popular Action and the Authentic Panamanian Party do not. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> orchestrated the ouster of <LOCATION> Delvalle </LOCATION> on Feb. 26, the day after <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> tried to fire the general. <PERSON> Zuniga </PERSON>, brother of a former Popular Action presidential candidate, said the movement `` will center its fight on the original principles of the Civic Crusade.'' `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should not continue economic and military action against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Arosemena </PERSON> said. `` The Panamanian people are capable of solving their own problems.'' Banking and diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said bank would not open Friday even on a limited basis. They said bankers feared the government would use their deposits if they reopened. The government, whose deposits in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks have been frozen, has not met public payrolls since the crisis began. The last of 1,300 additional <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers arrived Thursday at <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> outside <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, completing a buildup meant to provide greater security for the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>, American installations and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens. Late Wednesday, the government said it had issued arrest warrants for three leading opponents, including <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, who has been in hiding in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. It also asked <ORGANIZATION> Interpol </ORGANIZATION>, the international police organization, to arrest <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Galindo </PERSON>, a former ambassador to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON>, who was <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>'s envoy in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and remains there. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` would regard any efforts by the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> regime to attempt arrests or prosecutions of President <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> and the others for their activities in urging and supporting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sanctions as the unlawful acts of an illegitimate regime.''
