<HEAD>Student Posters Criticize Educational Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Students at <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s leading university put up posters this week criticizing government education policy, but unlike student protesters in 1986, they made no sweeping calls for democracy. The official response so far also has been more restrained. The posters have been allowed to stay up for days on <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s main bulletin board. In 1986, tens of thousands of students at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and schools in other cities put up posters and took to the streets demanding more democracy. Authorities were lenient at first, but cracked down when they thought the students became too bold. Posters were torn down and students were ordered back to campus. The authorities' decision to leave the latest posters alone appeared to be an example of a new government openness which is being promted during the present session of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s legislature <PERSON> Lu </PERSON> <PERSON> Hao </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s student association, noted that most of the opinions advanced in the posters have been expressed by congress delegates or printed in the official press. He said it was normal that students should raise such complaints. He and other students said the posters contained no radical ideas and should not be interpreted as signs of widespread student discontent. A lengthy `` open letter'' directed to <ORGANIZATION> congress </ORGANIZATION> delegates was posted Wednesday at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, and on Thursday other posters were put up which picked apart official educational policy and proposed reforms. Students said an `` open letter'' would be presented to the congress demanding that more money be spent on education and charging that leaders were neglecting education in their attempts to modernize <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Some of the posters opposed a proposal from the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> which would require students and faculty to earn money for their universities by running their own factories or hiring themselves out to other businesses. Students regard the idea as further evidence that the leadership is unwilling to invest in education and instead wants students and teachers to fend for themselves. One poster called on students to express their displeasure with the idea by going to <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to earn money by shining shoes. About 80 students were gathered at about noon Thursday, reading and discussing the posters. Most seemed to agree with the criticisms. Presidents of four of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s major universities, including <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, told the English-language <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> last week that state funding falls far short of their operating needs.
</TEXT>
