<HEAD>U.S.-South Korea Field Exercise Ends</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To CORRECT spelling of assistant secretary of state to Sigur,
sted Segur, sub 6th graf: U.S. Assistant ....; picks up 7th graf
pvs: Washington has ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> on Thursday ended their annual military field training exercise involving <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops from the American continent and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> areas, a military announcement said. The 10-day field exercise, which was held at various parts of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, was the highlight of Team Spirit 88 which involved about 200,000 troops from the two countries. The announcement from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.-South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Korea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Combined </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> said that all deployed forces will return to their home bases by early May. The command said Team Spirit, which was first held in 1976, was designed to improve defensive readiness of South Korean and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces through joint operations. <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> has attached a special meaning to the joint exercise because <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> threatens to disrupt the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Olympic Games. <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> has refused to take part in the Games unless its demand to be made a cohost is met. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON> <PERSON> Sigur </PERSON> said Tuesday while on a visit here that the exercise was `` a valuable demonstraton of our commitment to preserving peace ... and timely in this year of the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Olympics.'' <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has pledged to provide necessary security support to prevent <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> from disrupting the Games. Also on Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said it plans to introduce at least 24 more F-16 fighters this year to improve combat capability of its tactical fighter wing in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said its 51st Tactical Fighter Wing here would replace F-4E Phantom II fighters now in service with F-16 fighters this fall. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said the introduction of F-16 <ORGANIZATION> Fighting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Falcons </ORGANIZATION> would help meet military threat from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and the modernization of the Soviet military in the region. Currently, 12 F-4E Phamtom fighters are assigned to two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> air bases in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> each: the 36th <ORGANIZATION> Tactical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fighter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Squadron </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Osan </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> 497th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tactical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fighter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Squadron </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Taegu </LOCATION>, they said. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> statement said the 36th TFS will receive 24 F-16C and D models in October 1989 to improve and modernize its combat capability and readiness. The 497th TFS in <LOCATION> Taegu </LOCATION> will be deactivated early next year in line with budget cuts, with its 12 F-4E Phantom fighters to be released for foreign sales, the statement said.
