<HEAD>`Borderlines,' Two One-Act Plays by John Bishop, Open Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The men in `` Borderlines,'' the umbrella title for two new one-act plays by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON>, sure have their problems. `` Right now I'm having trouble connecting to things,'' admits <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, the protagonist in the evening's pretentious curtain-raiser. It's called `` Borderline'' without the `` s,'' presumably to mark its anti-hero's precarious state of mind. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> is a yuppyish marketing specialist who sells things like shampoo and toothpaste, but his mind is not on his work. He worries about his stale marriage, frets about the big basketball game he blew in high school, commiserates and drinks with a crude co-worker, sleeps with a young secretary and finally kills the woman's jealous boyfriend. In between these episodes, a lecturer appears on stage to outline <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>' violent family tree which she traces back several centuries to the border wars between <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. His ancestors made their way to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> where they were involved in one disastrous episode after another _ from <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> wars in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> to battles between cowboys and sheepmen in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and fights over land in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> suggests that <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>' homicidal nature was preordained. It's in man's genes and no amount of moping about and worrying is going to change things. Much of the same anxiety pervades `` Keepin' An Eye On <PERSON> Louie </PERSON>,'' the second and much more successful half of the evening. This time, the man at sea with himself is <PERSON> Dave </PERSON>, a policeman who keeps a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> mobster named <PERSON> Louie </PERSON> under surveillance. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> is just as miserable as <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> but in this play, the dialogue crackles with blue-collar banter. There are a lot of jokes about members of the mob with first names like Bananas or Tomatoes or <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. Also enlivening the proceedings is the appearance _ in drag _ of <PERSON> Louie </PERSON>'s recalcitrant son-in-law, who has decided to help the police and identify members of the mob. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> also ca n't communicate with his wife. The reason is never made clear, although the playwright paints a picture of a man closer to his job and his fellow police officers than the woman he married. It's an unsatisfactory portrait. The cast is first-rate, particularly <PERSON> Cotter </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> as the distraught executive in the first play and <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarty </PERSON> as the unnerved policeman in the second. They bring a conviction to their roles that is not supported by the writing. Despite those performances and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>'s fluid direction, `` Borderlines,'' which arrived Thursday at off-Broadway's <ORGANIZATION> Circle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Repertory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, never becomes much more than two morose, murky tales of male menopause.
</TEXT>
