<DATELINE>YORK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police ended a three-hour siege Wednesday by fatally shooting a suicidal 20-year-old man who had held his young girlfriend hostage apparently with a fake gun, authorities said. Israel <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> died Wednesday afternoon of a single gunshot wound at <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, where he had been taken for surgery, a hospital spokeswoman said. The hostage, a 14-year-old runaway whose name was withheld by authorities, was not injured. <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> had held what appeared to be an automatic gun to the girl's head, which was covered by a pillowcase. Authorities originally said that a police sharpshooter fired at <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> after the hostage taker said, `` I am now going to kill her.'' But film shot by WGAL-TV in <LOCATION> Lancaster </LOCATION> showed <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> was hit by a bullet moments after he swore at police and said `` I'm coming out.'' Both <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON>' hands were on a window ledge, no gun was apparent and the girl was out of view. As soon as <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> was shot in the abdomen, the teen came to the window shouting for an ambulance. Police Chief <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hose </PERSON>, who was not present at the shooting, said the initial accounts may have been wrong and that the incident was being investigated. State police were called in to assist. The chief said a handgun and an Uzi-type rifle found in <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON>' apartment appeared to be fakes The sharpshooter's name was not released. During the siege, <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> tossed radios, a stereo, pizza boxes and shoes from the window as he swore at police and asked whether he should beat his hostage. He refused to surrender despite pleas from his psychiatric counselor, who had been treating <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> for suicidal tendencies, said police Lt. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> McMaster </PERSON>.
