<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> suspended his stalled presidential campaign Thursday but held onto his 170 delegates in hopes of influencing the choice of a nominee at the Democratic national convention in July. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> immediately blasted <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> for keeping the delegates, saying most of them were rightfully his. `` In a year that has already seen many surprises, no one knows what twists and turns may develop between now and then,'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> told a news conference. `` There will be many encounters with fate before the contest is ultimately decided in a wide-open convention.'' In a quasi-withdrawal, <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said he would no longer actively campaign for the nomination but said he technically would remain a candidate even though he conceded he has `` no illusions that the nomination will come my way.''
