 Day after day, a small, dapper man in a gray derby has trudged up the federal courthouse steps weighed down with a document-filled suitcase and the threat of a 10-year prison sentence. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Merrill </PERSON> <PERSON> Mount </PERSON>, an art historian and portrait painter, is charged with selling documents that belong to the Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION>. The government has portrayed him as a thief, a <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> native with an affected British accent who has had previous scrapes with the law. But Mount's friends say he is genuine, a self-taught scholar and <ORGANIZATION> Guggenheim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> fellow who wrote well-received artist biographies and collected an impressive catalog of letters of the famous, much of which he has donated to one institution he is accused of looting.
