<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv08   04-07 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 08 ,0660</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday April 8</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Did You Pay The Cleaning Woman's Social Security?
^By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If you employ a cleaning person on a regular basis you must deduct Social Security taxes of 7.51 percent from the paycheck and, in addition, contribute a like amount as the employee's portion of the tax. This is one of the touchiest areas of American tax policy. Many employers of household help are ignorant of their obligations. Many domestics are equally unaware. And in many instances, either side elects to ignore the obligations. But those obligations, and others, are very real. They could lead to fines. They could lead to more costly problems if an ex-employee sues to reclaim benefits that should have been paid, but were not, over a period of years. It is a growing challenge to families, since many are able to exist only by having two breadwinners, each working at a fulltime job and therefore unable to handle household chores without the help of a domestic. Since there is already enough confusion about the obligations of those who employ domestics, a concerned household should describe its specific situation and accept guidance from an accountant or tax authority. The key word is `` employee.'' A young person who rakes your lawn once a year is n't an employee. But a domestic who cleans your house once a week is almost certainly an employee for whom you must pay taxes. Specialists at <ORGANIZATION> Spicer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Oppenheim </PERSON>, an accounting and tax firm, define a domestic as someone who performs service in or about a private home, including housekeepers, maids, cooks and babysitters. Payments made for the performance of such services are generally subject to the Federal Insurance Contribution Act, or Social Security. An exclusion exists, says the accounting firm, for all payments under $ 50 made to an individual for occasional domestic help during a calendar quarter. Also excluded are payments in the form of lodging or meals. Otherwise, you might be liable _ and, again, it is wise to check with an accountant or tax adviser about your specific case _ for deducting your employee's portion of FICA and adding in the employer's identical FICA payment. Your tax responsibilities might not end there either. You might also be responsible for collecting both federal and state unemployment taxes. Wages paid for domestic service are subject to federal unemployment tax, says the firm, if cash paid to a performer of domestic service totals $ 1,000 or more in any quarter of a taxable year, or in a preceding taxable year. The maximum tax rate is 6.2 percent of the first $ 7,000 in wages. For state unemployment tax purposes, each state establishes its own quarterly requirements. But, whatever is paid to the state may earn a credit deductable from the federal tax. Almost needless to say, one reason many households ignore these tax laws is that they have more paperwork than time in which to do it, and more legal and financial complications than they feel competent to contend with. There is a way out of this one if you hire domestic help through an agency in the business of furnishing the actual services. Then, the agency is viewed as the employer responsible for all taxes. For the agency to qualify, and for you to be relieved of taxes, the agency must claim to be in the business of providing domestic services. It must fix compensation levels. Its income must be derived from its employee's income. By that definition, a company listed with the state as an agency that merely furnishes domestic workers to prospective employers for a fee _ that is, an employment agency _ does n't meet the requirements. Final advisory: Check with a tax authority or an accountant about your specific situation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday April 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880407-0250 </DOCNO>
