<HEAD>Theater Group Gives Former Prisoners Chance to Make Clean Break</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Rena </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> remembers the 2,022 bricks in her tiny cell. Sue <PERSON> Rossiter </PERSON> can still hear the clink of locks and keys. The sights and sounds of prison are vivid years later. <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rossiter </PERSON>, both jailed on drug charges, do n't forget. Through an unusual theater group called Clean Break, they and other female ex-offenders are leaving their experiences behind by putting them on the stage. Begun nine years ago in a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> prison, Clean Break has grown into a theater group which has toured in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, performed on the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shakespeare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> stage and produced more than a dozen plays. For the women, it's a chance to perform, to produce plays about the traumas of lives that led to jail sentences and, most of all, an opportunity to speak out about an experience many others try to hide. `` One of the most important things women ca n't do when they come out of prison is articulate their experience,'' says <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Tchaikovsky </PERSON>, who helps run a reform group called Women in Prison and wrote one Clean Break play. Prison `` floats around in the back of your head,'' she says. `` If people can articulate crime it puts it behind you, and Clean Break makes a unique contribution. `` Apart from that, it's great fun,'' adds <PERSON> Tchaikovsky </PERSON>, who served three years for check fraud. `` It's not everyone sitting around thinking, ` God, I'm a victim.''' Still, prison life is not the stuff of comedy. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has only 1,755 women in jail, out of a total prison population of nearly 49,000 cramped into an overcrowded prison network. But women prisoners are disciplined twice as often as men, are punished more often for violence and injure themselves more often than men, studies by the private <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Care and Resettlement of Offenders -LRB- NACRO -RRB- show. `` Women's prisons have never really been considered; they're run like men's prisons but with women in them,'' says <ORGANIZATION> NACRO </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON>. `` The main question is why are they there,'' she says. `` It's terribly expensive, it's so destructive, it's such a waste This is true for men but more true for women.'' <PERSON> Jenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>, who co-founded Clean Break in 1979 with a fellow inmate, <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Holborough </PERSON>, at a low-security prison, says leaving jail does n't mean the problems end. <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> and <PERSON> Holborough </PERSON>, with the support of a liberal warden at Askhams Grange prison, expanded the annual Christmas show into a theater workshop, then a troupe. With a 21-strong group, they became the first British prisoners to perform outside jail, presenting a play in <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION>. Of the group, only <PERSON> Holborough </PERSON> had had any prior experience in the theater. `` It was an absolutely freeing activity from the bordom and general uselessness of prison,'' <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> said. Now, <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> works mainly with Creative and Supportive Trust -LRB- CAST -RRB-, a group for ex-offenders that shares Clean Break's drafty basement rooms in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and is closely allied with the theater group. Most productions have small casts and a barren set, and Clean Break can afford only one annual tour of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> fringe theaters. However, the actresses have union cards and salaries, and the group, which numbers about 30 permanent members, has expanded its activities. With its first public grant in 1986, Clean Break took <PERSON> Holborough </PERSON>'s play `` The Sin Eaters'' on an American tour including stops in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, an <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> prison and a <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> women's festival. It has also toured in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>. The group has performed at psychiatric hospitals, drug and alcohol rehabiliation centers and detention centers, opened its ranks to former inmates and sought the help of several professional actresses. <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shakespeare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> actress who worked on `` The Sin Eaters,'' has for more than a year led writing workshops with therapist <PERSON> Kate </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>. Last year, she combined a cast of RSC and Clean Break actresses in performing a collection of writings from both former and current prisoners called `` Voices From Prison'' at the Barbican, the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> stage of the RSC. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> also recently directed the latest production affiliated with Clean Break, 27-year-old <PERSON> Rena </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>'s passionate account of how the therapy she demanded in prison helped her accept her heritage as a Maori, the indigenous minority of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>. As Clean Break enters its ninth year, those involved question whether its main role is theatrical or therapeutic. Still, for many, Clean Break remains a dramatic help. `` It's a refuge,'' says <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Rossiter </PERSON>. `` It was real therapy.''
</TEXT>
