<HEAD>Message from the Woods: The Story of Park Naturalist Glen Kaye</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Forget about the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> auditor who may be doublechecking your tax return. Forget the unreceptive receptionists who pass your call around when you phone some federal office with a simple question. Forget the fact that everyone loves to kick bureaucrats, especially at tax time. Read on. You may end up glad you're paying <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON>'s salary.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKY MOUNTAIN NATIONAL PARK, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> gets paid federal tax dollars to serve the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people as chief naturalist for Rocky Mountain National Park. He helps the 2.7 million citizen bosses who visit each year to understand the 414 square miles of national patrimony located 75 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. It's <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON>'s job to tell us what it all means: What are those funny looking birds? Will this mushroom kill me if I eat it? What time do the rangers turn off the waterfalls? His is a five-page, single-spaced job description. He supervises two visitor centers, two museums, four amphitheaters, two information booths, a 2,000-volume library and an outpouring of new books and pamphlets; oversees six park employees, more than 30 seasonal workers and 50 volunteers, and administers an annual budget of $ 400,000. He is park spokesman for good news, such as international wilderness conferences, and bad news, such as people falling off mountains. A 25-year veteran of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, he earns $ 43,891 annually and lives with his wife, <PERSON> Harriet </PERSON>, a pianist and caterer, and their two teen-age children, in a government-owned house five minutes' walk from his office. His burning ambition is to return to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, ideally as a park superintendent. Assigned for five years to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> Volcanoes National Park, <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> says: `` I left my heart there. It's the first place on Earth that really sang to me.'' But the return will have to wait. In mid-May, <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> begins work as chief of interpretation for the park service's <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> region. He'll be based in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, a beautiful place, even if not his paradise. If <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> did n't exist, <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> would invent him. At 46, he reports for work dressed like the Boy Scout he once was, yet often spends his days immersed in cosmic dilemmas such as the future of the ozone layer. He is an acrophobic who tries, and fails, to overcome his fear of heights by climbing mountains. A painter of tropical scenes, a wearer of Hawaiian shirts, <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> lives in a landlocked alpine valley where winter lasts seven months. He describes himself as a diffident man, yet he boldly creates five-year plans for his department. Tall and gangly, with a monk's fringe of hair, he is a solitary outdoorsman but seizes every opportunity to attend grand opera with crowds Growing up in <LOCATION> Medford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> decided he wanted to spend his adulthood in the outdoors. So, straight out of <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1963, he joined the park service as a naturalist at Crater Lake National Park. There were n't many interpreters back then. `` Rangers were hugging trees or working with three spine sticklebacks -LRB- an ugly little fish -RRB-. They were n't big on people or communications skills.'' Today hundreds of workers on the federal payroll do nothing but explain the nation's parks to its people. `` What I try to do is get people to realize a park is not protected by boundaries on paper and a handful of rangers,'' <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> said. `` But we ca n't go out and say, ` YOU MUST SAVE THIS NATIONAL PARK!' `` We must lay out information and let people make up their own minds. In the long run, parks are protected by the peer attitudes of society.'' <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> believes one of the best ways to educate Americans about their natural treasures is through art. That notion, and an old log cabin, inspired him to create Rocky Mountain National Park's artist-in-residence program in 1984 The cabin, once owned by the late <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> newspaper editor <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, has a breathtaking view of 14,255-foot Long's Peak Every summer <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> selects `` creators and communicators'' to spend from one to three weeks in the cabin, doing their own thing. The park provides housing and firewood, guests provide groceries. `` <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> broke through the inertia of ` This is the way we've always done it' and came up with a great idea,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Sontag </PERSON>, chief of the park service's <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> region interpretation office in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> <PERSON> Sontag </PERSON> attributed the program's success to <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON>'s enthusiasm _ he raised money for the restoration and contributed his own elbow grease _ but added, `` There are quite a lot of those folks in government.'' Participating last summer were four journalists, three artists, two composers, a photographer, a writer and an actor. `` Artists need time to goof around, and <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> understands that,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> pianist and composer who stayed in the cabin after he was commissioned to create a score for a park service film. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> taped wildlife, water and wind sounds to help him write a piano composition. He also practiced daily on the piano <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> moved into the house for his tenure. `` The cabin was offered with no strings attached. The guy was genuinely offering an experience to us to see what we would do with it,'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. `` At first it seemed too good to be true, but I learned that <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> is a truly gentle man who has a very sincere respect for artists.'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> plans to return to the park later this year to premier his musical work. `` This is the best thing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has ever done for me personally,'' the pianist said, speaking of the opportunity <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON>'s program presented `` I feel I've been given a great gift.'' Art, <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> says, has helped change Americans' perception of their land _ `` from fear and loathing of wilderness to embracing and positively administering it.'' <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> writes magazine articles and a column in the local newspaper. In one recent piece, he gently warned readers about world overpopulation and dwindling natural resources, and cautioned of a growing scarcity for future generations. He wished them freedom from the regimentation of overcrowding, access to beauty in nature, clean air and water, and the opportunity to achieve their potential. `` Above all,'' he concluded, `` I want them to know of their history and their responsibility, for in their action is the future of their lives.''
