<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 10 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Rural Bus Effort Being Cranked Up by Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sometimes its hard to get from <LOCATION> Frogfuzz </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Junction </LOCATION> over to <ORGANIZATION> Blitz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> where the courthouse is. Or up to <LOCATION> Wrathgrape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> where <PERSON> Aunt </PERSON> <PERSON> Sophie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> has the family in for Sunday dinner now and then. Most often rural people who are too poor or infirm to drive a car have to find a friend or relative to take them around. You do n't trot or teeter down to the corner to catch a bus or train because there are n't any. And sometimes people who live in the countryside, in the thousands of small towns and hamlets that make up rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, simply stay home when they're lonely or really should see a doctor. Railroad whistle-stop passenger service, the `` local'' or milk train of yesteryear, has long passed into history. Stagecoaches mostly gave way to buses by World War I, and even the buses are now becoming hard to find. `` Increasingly, if one lives in a rural community, efficient bus service may be only a distant memory, nor may rail or air service be available,'' says the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. That's why <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> are joining with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Owners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> to discuss a solution to rural transportation problems. Two regional meetings will be held this spring, in <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, April 20-22, and in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, May 18-20. A national conference will be held in August in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Stommes </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> said the government's major financial aid involves the `` Section 18'' funds provided states by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- DOT -RRB- under the Urban Mass Transportation Act. The money has totaled around $ 75 million annually and is apportioned to states under a formula to help improve passenger transportation systems available to rural people. No increase in federal money is being talked about at this point, Ms. <PERSON> Stommes </PERSON> said in an interview. Instead, she said, the conferences will be focusing on `` coordinating the resources that are out there and trying to bring together the private and public sectors.'' It's sort of a hodge-podge of programs right now. States are contributing to rural transportation programs, along with the federal government. Local transportation providers, mostly non-profit groups, often have authority to operated within a single county or a certain multi-county region. To some extent, these contract with human services agencies to provide specialized transportation, to health facilities, for example. But in order to qualify for Section 18 funds, general public transportation must also be provided. `` One of the things that we're trying to encourage ... is the coordination of schedules between these providers and the intercity carriers,'' Ms. <PERSON> Stommes </PERSON> said. `` That is not happening in a great many places.'' But there are exceptions, she said. For example, `` Greyound is establishing what they call their rural connector program, in which local or non-profit providers are feeding their passengers into the intercity network,'' Ms. <PERSON> Stommes </PERSON> said. Improving rural transportation is not a new or novel idea. It has been the goal of countless community efforts since Americans started heading West. Any small-town <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> worth its salt has had a plan, prospectus or lobbying effort on behalf of gaining or keeping its railroad service, bus station or airport. Much work already has been done at the federal level. In the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration, a White House Rural Development Initiatives project included `` ways to overcome isolation by improving transportation in rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> in 1979 took the lead with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> for the Transportation Disadvantaged in turning out a handbook, Rural Rides, for starting and operating a rural public transportation system. A point made by the 1979 handbook is the relatively scant amount of federal money available for rural transportation: although nearly 30 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> population lives in rural areas, only about 1 percent of the federal money spent on public transportation goes to rural needs. The handbook, although dated in many ways, sounded a call for coordinating the fragmented transportation services that did exist _ exactly what Ms. <PERSON> Stommes </PERSON> said is one of the priorities of the 1988 effort. `` Coordination is good for the taxpayers and contributors who foot the ultimate bill because waste, inefficiency and duplication of effort should be eliminated,'' the handbook said. `` And it's good for everybody in the participating town, county or area because the savings can be passed on to the public in the form of increased transportation services. For further information on the upcoming meetings about bus service in rural areas, contact: <PERSON> Eileen </PERSON> <PERSON> Stommes </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>, P.O. Box 96575, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> 20090-6575. Phone 202?653-6305.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 10</NOTE>
