<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Families of Crew Mark 25th Anniversary of Thresher Sinking</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, `It was ...' to RESTORE dropped `he said';
SUBS 19th graf pvs, `Although the ...' to fix noun-verb agreement.</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BETSY HENDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Edna </PERSON> <PERSON> DiNola </PERSON> has trouble recreating the jumbled events of April 10, 1963, the night she was told the USS Thresher, a nuclear submarine carrying her husband and 128 other men, had not resurfaced from a dive 220 miles off the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> coast. She is n't quite sure who came to her home or what they said. She thinks friends helped put her five children to bed and turned away reporters clamoring for reaction. She thinks a <ORGANIZATION> Portsmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipyard </ORGANIZATION> chaplain told her he would be there if she needed him. There is one thing, however, <PERSON> DiNola </PERSON> did remember as she reflected last week on Sunday's 25th anniversary of the nation's worst submarine disaster: `` I just did n't think that they would n't come up again But the submarine, powerless with a crippled nuclear reactor, never had a chance, sinking deeper and deeper in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> until fierce water pressure crushed its hull and killed all aboard. Rear Adm. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Axene </PERSON>, Thresher's commanding officer until three months earlier, was returning to <LOCATION> Portsmouth </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> when he heard on the radio a submarine was missing. He drove immediately to the shipyard, which <PERSON> Thresher </PERSON> had left two days earlier. After midnight, <PERSON> Axene </PERSON> began calling family members, many of whom were close friends and had faith in the 278-foot submarine that the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said could `` dive deeper, move faster and carry more weapons than any other submarine in the fleet.'' `` It was a great ship and it had a great crew,'' he said. `` When I was reassigned, I fought to stay on it.'' <PERSON> Thresher </PERSON> had three years of success when it left for tests the morning of April 8. Accompanied by the submarine tender <PERSON> Skylark </PERSON>, Thresher's 112 military personnel and 17 civilian technicians were looking for minor glitches in the machinery after a routine overhaul. But the problems were more severe than anyone suspected. At 9:02 a.m. on April 10, the Skylark received a message from Thresher, 1,000 feet below the surface: `` Experiencing minor difficulties.'' Garbled radio messages followed saying <PERSON> Thresher </PERSON> was `` exceeding test depth,'' then `` attempting to blow,'' a naval term for resurfacing. At 9:17, Lt. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>, listening to <PERSON> Skylark </PERSON>'s radio, `` heard the sounds of a ship breaking up _ a dull, muted roar.'' Then silence. <PERSON> Skylark </PERSON> radioed that <PERSON> Thresher </PERSON> was missing. `` It was a terrible experience, a terrible thing,'' Axene, now retired and living in <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, said of calling crew families. He plans to attend Sunday's memorial services for the first time in 24 years, but the memories are still too painful for his wife. Some crewmen's wives, like <PERSON> DiNola </PERSON>, did n't believe <PERSON> Thresher </PERSON> was lost and told reporters to print the good news when their husbands returned. <PERSON> DiNola </PERSON> finally went to bed that night. `` I had three babies -LRB- and two other children -RRB- and they had to be taken care of, so you just go on,'' she said. Although the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> told her the sub was lost, she told shipyard officials to leave her husband's car waiting at the pier. `` You would think that you would react immediately to something like this, but you do n't,'' she said. <PERSON> DiNola </PERSON> was n't alone. Some speculated that crewmen might be alive, sustained by air bubbles trapped in the wreckage. Another sub detected what some believed were hull noises, prompting the secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> to declare the night after the tragedy that `` there is absolutely no possibility that there might be survivors.'' But the truth did n't register with <PERSON> DiNola </PERSON> until days later when friends told her ships had spotted an oil slick _ the telltale sign of wreckage. `` I finally realized what was happening, and I went into orbit,'' she said. A <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> board of inquiry pieced together what went wrong. The board considered 120 witnesses, 225 exhibits and 1,700 pages of testimony before concluding problems probably started with a leak in the saltwater piping. The board said water had shorted out electrical circuits and shut down the nuclear reactor, leaving Thresher powerless. `` The Thresher presumably blew main ballast, started to rise, then slowed and began to sink,'' Vice Adm. E.W. <PERSON> Grenfell </PERSON> wrote in a 1964 analysis of the disaster. When the sub sank below its `` collapse depth,'' water pressure crushed the hull. In August 1964, a research submarine found and photographed the wreckage, about 1 -LCB- miles down. A witness described the ocean floor as resembling `` a huge automobile junkyard with big pieces of heavy metal all over the place.'' <PERSON> Thresher </PERSON>'s sole surviving crew member, who took leave just before the sub left because his wife had had an accident, said he still believes the submarine could have been saved. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> McCoole </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thresher </PERSON>'s reactor officer, said he might have been able to use the sub's momentum to prevent its plunge. He would have sacrificed the reactor to save the submarine, he said. After Thresher, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> developed a submarine safety program based on the board's findings. The program includes strict construction methods and testing for saltwater piping, more initial shallow-water sea trials and design improvements. `` My feeling is that progress is expensive and the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has certainly learned from Thresher,'' <PERSON> McCoole </PERSON> said last week. `` It's a hard way to learn, however.'' <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Collier </PERSON>, who was 4 when his father, <PERSON> Merrill </PERSON>, perished, agreed. `` A lot of good came out of that sad day,'' said <PERSON> Collier </PERSON>, who spent three years on a submarine himself and now is an instructor at a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> training center in <LOCATION> Saratoga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> has read names of the dead at several Thresher services and helped plan this year's service, expected to be the largest since the tragedy. Despite the pain of growing up without his father, <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> said mourning is n't the main purpose of the service. `` I take the memorial service very seriously and it's a big deal to me every year,'' he said. `` But from my point of view, the Thresher incident and what impact it had on national defense is really why it's important. `` It made subs a lot safer. Many, many lives have been saved because those guys gave their lives.'' <PERSON> DiNola </PERSON> will be at Sunday's service. After working years in a school lunch program and as a nurse, <PERSON> DiNola </PERSON> decided in 1986 to honor her husband with a plaque in Arlington National Cemetery. `` I finally decided it was time to have our own service'' for <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, she said. `` I felt that by then everyone would understand the situation.'' Aided by veterans benefits and Social Security, <PERSON> DiNola </PERSON> has raised her family. This spring, her last child will graduate from college. `` You do what you have to, and the good Lord guides you,'' she said.
