<HEAD>Stocks Rally, Testing Trading Limits, As Dollar Strengthens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A stronger dollar and weaker interest rates sparked Wall Street's second best day of 1988, with stock prices rising so strongly they triggered the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s self-imposed limits on one type of trading. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 64.16 points to 2,061.67 on Wednesday, its biggest gain since the widely-watched market barometer rose 76.42 points on Jan. 4, the year's first trading day. In Wednesday's only major economic report, <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s Big Three automakers reported that dealer sales incentives paid off with strong late-March and first-quarter sales increases. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, nearly three stocks rose in price for every one that declined as <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> volume rose to 189.76 million shares, from Tuesday's 135.29 million. By swinging more than 50 points, the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> industrials triggered an <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> restriction on computerized program trading for the first time since the so-called `` collar'' was announced on Feb. 4. Program trading, a technique used to profit on price differences between stocks traded in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and corresponding stock-index futures traded in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> futures markets, has been blamed for injecting volatility into the market and frightening investors. Analysts said Wednesday's gain was due to a strengthening of the dollar in foreign exchange, which in turn prompted a decline in long-term interest rates in the credit markets. The dollar moved higher, analysts said, on speculation the major industrial nations may be moving toward a fresh agreement to support the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency. A meeting of the industrial powers is planned for next week. The dollar rose to 126.03 Japanese yen late in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> from 125.28 yen late Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s bellwether 30-year bond ended the session up nearly $ 10 per $ 1,000 face amount. Its yield, which moves inversely to its price, slipped to 8.75 percent from 8.84 percent. In <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported more than 18 percent jumps in daily sales rates for the quarter. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the top seller, reported a nearly 10 percent rise.
