<HEAD>Crude Prices Slightly Higher; Products Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hopes continue waning in the oil markets that an upcoming <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> committee meeting will result in actions to stabilize crude prices. In quiet trading Wednesday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, crude oil futures prices finished marginally higher while refined oil products were mixed. Contracts for May delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, edged up 2 cents per barrel to $ 16.81. Other contract months gained between 1 cent and 3 cents. Among refined products, wholesale heating oil for May delivery rose 0.14 cent a gallon to 45.34 cents, while most longer-term months declined. Wholesale unleaded gasoline for May fell 0.22 cent a gallon to 48.42 cents, but longer-term contracts advanced. Crude prices failed to reach the $ 17-a-barrel level, which they had tumbled below Tuesday following reports that the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>' pricing committee would not recommend a full ministerial conference of the cartel at its April 9 meeting. The upcoming meeting in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, earlier had incited hope that the 13-nation cartel would act aggressively to stabilize prices and enforce production limits to curb excessive supplies. `` The market is no longer expecting great shakes'' from the April 9 meeting, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, an oil analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said prices were supported by the latest weekly statistics on the nation's oil supply and demand, which showed a jump in oil imports and a substantial drawdown of oil stocks from the previous week. The data, released late Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, an industry group based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, were construed as indicating continued robust demand for oil.
</TEXT>
