<FIRST>r f PM-NewspageStocks     04-07 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspage Stocks,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Post Broad Advance, Trigger Trading Limit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices have jumped sharply in response to optimism over the outlook for inflation and interest rates, propelling the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average to its second biggest gain of the year. The Wednesday rise in the Dow was sharp enough to trigger a <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> restriction on computerized program trading for the first time since the limit was announced Feb. 4. But stocks kept rising even after the restriction _ effective once the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> industrials moves more than 50 points up or down from the previous day's close _ kicked in late in the session. The Dow industrials finished 64.16 points higher at 2,061.67. It was the average's ninth-biggest gain ever and the largest since it rose 76.42 on Jan. 4. Nearly three issues rose for every one that fell among NYSE-listed issues. <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> trading volume grew to 189.76 million shares from 135.29 million shares on Tuesday. Analysts said the market's rise was triggered by a news report from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> that officials of the seven major industrial countries likely would agree on a plan to support the dollar in foreign exchange. A strong dollar would diminish inflationary pressure, which in turn could ease upward pressure on interest rates, analysts said. Recent expectations that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> would tighten credit and push interest rates higher had depressing stock market psychology, said <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zinder </PERSON>, a market analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. But some analysts were skeptical about how long the strong gains would last, given the market's recent volatility. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> program trading restrictions took effect after the Dow industrials passed the 50-point gain mark at about 3:19 p.m. EDT, a spokeswoman for the exchange said. Program trading is a technique used by big investors to profit on price differences between stocks and the corresponding stock-index futures. It has been blamed for injecting volatility into the market, frightening investors away and harming the securities industry.
</TEXT>
