<FIRST>r f PM-NYSECapacity     04-07 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYSE Capacity,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>NYSE Gears For 1 Billion-Share Day By Late Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crushing trading volume during last year's stock market crash has prompted the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> to broaden the planned expansion of its trading systems, with a daily capability of 1 billion shares targeted by the end of 1989. `` At a time when many firms are cutting costs, we believe the securities industry needs to take action to insure the ability to handle high volume,'' <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Birnbaum </PERSON> said Wednesday. The exchange now can efficiently process the buying and selling of 200 million shares a day. It initially planned to broaden its capacity to 400 million shares a day this year, but increaesd that target following the October stock market crash. Volume exceeded 600 million shares on both Oct. 19 and 20, representing 200 million shares more than the system's current theoretical capacity. The exchange now expects to be able comfortably to handle daily volume of 600 million shares by June, according to its operations advisory committee, which is coordinating the upgrading of the securities industry's trading and communications systems. Last year trading volume averaged 197 million shares a day. Among additional measures the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> has taken to upgrade its systems capacity since the October market crash are: _ Increasing and restructuring the Designated Order Turnaround -LRB- DOT -RRB- System's memory for more efficient order processing _ Program changes to the limit order systems to reduce bottlenecks during peak volume periods A 50 percent capacity increase is targed for this month. _ Adding 20 printers to the trading floor, thereby increasing capacity by 20 percent, and increasing the number of electronic display books on the floor by 25 percent _ Replacing the automated pricing and reporting system Since 1982 the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> has spent more than $ 250 million upgrading its systems and technology. The exchange has budgeted another $ 200 million to be spent on improvements over the next five years.
</TEXT>
