<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   04-07 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Domestic Automakers Post First Quarter Sales Surge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Growing confidence in the economy and plentiful buyer incentive offerings boosted domestic car and light truck sales in late March and the first quarter of 1988, according to manufacturers and industry analysts. Sales of domestically-manufactured cars in the 10 selling days of March 21-31 totaled 332,721, up from 282,358 in the nine selling days during the late-March period last year. Domestic sales for the quarter totaled 1,914,022, up from 1,666,748 a year earlier, according to manufacturers sales reports released Wednesday. Import car sales, reported monthly, totaled 255,867 for March, up from 237,677 in March 1987, and 700,572 for the quarter, up from 639,403 in first quarter 1987. <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Certo </PERSON>, an automotive industry analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said the sales figures indicated that buyer incentives offered during the month were very effective at drawing customers. `` Sales are robust for the month, continuing what was going on in January and February,'' <PERSON> Certo </PERSON> said. Buyers appear confident in a strong election-year economy and unworried about last October's stock slump, she said. `` Cash-allowance buyer incentive programs are in effect a temporary price cut and the buyers are reacting to the bargain prices,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rewey </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> vice president. <PERSON> Rewey </PERSON> also said: `` The solid economic conditions of high employment and strong consumer confidence are a major part of their total purchase process.'' First-quarter sales of imported light trucks slid to 168,908 from 204,424 in the 1987 first-quarter, while domestic light truck sales jumped to 1,044,984 for the quarter, compared with 840,073 in the year-earlier quarter. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> both reported more than 18 percent jumps in daily sales rates for the quarter. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the top seller, reported a 9.5 percent rise in its daily rate. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> sold 159,728 domestically produced autos in the March 21-31 period, up from 136,082 in the 1987 late-March period. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> quarterly sales rose to 942,830 autos from 849,470 in first quarter 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> sold 93,590 domestic cars in the 10 days, up from 79,249, and 553,545 for the three months, up from 462,629. The automaker posted an 18.1 percent increase in its daily sales rate for the quarter over last year. Chrysler domestic car sales totaled 48,125 for the 10 days, up from 41,652, and 283,491 for the quarter, up from 236,280. The company's daily sales rate jumped 18.4 percent for the quarter.
</TEXT>
