<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales-Table     04-07 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales-Table,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Auto Sales Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are sales results for the eight major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers for March 21-31. Percentage changes in sales are based on average daily sales during each period rather than comparisons of straight totals. There were 10 selling days in the period this year and nine selling days in the period last year. Cars and trucks made in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> are counted as domestic and appear in this table. Cars and trucks imported for sales under the <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> names are counted as foreign. Sales of imported cars and trucks are reported at the end of each month.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>DOMESTIC CAR TOTAL</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 March 21-31: 332,721 vs. 282,358, up 6.1 percent. Month: 733,738 vs. 682,117, up 3.6 percent. Year: 1,914,022 vs. 1,666,748, up 13.3 percent.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>FOREIGN CAR TOTAL</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Month: 255,867 vs. 237,677, up 3.7 percent. Year: 700,572 vs. 639,403, up 8.1 percent.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>DOMESTIC TRUCK TOTAL</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 March 21-31: 186,875 vs. 139,909, up 20.2 percent. Month: 416,803 vs. 352,889, up 13.7 percent. Year: 1,044,984 vs. 840,073, up 22.8 percent.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>FOREIGN TRUCK TOTAL</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Month: 63,120 vs. 82,073, down 25.9 percent. Year: 168,908 vs. 204,424, down 18.4 percent.
</TEXT>
