<HEAD>Mexico Will Press Ahead With Efforts to Erase Foreign Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> will continue pursuing efforts to pare its $ 100 billion foreign debt despite the limited success of its novel program to swap some loans for U.S.-backed bonds, according to the nation's chief debt negotiator. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Gurria </PERSON>, director of public credit for the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, told foreign reporters that the nation's debt outlook had improved dramatically since the beginning of the crisis in 1982. But, he said, `` the matter of the foreign debt continues being a matter of fundamental importance -LRB- and -RRB- great worry for Mexican authorities.'' `` It's obvious that today we have a situation drastically different -LRB- from 1982 -RRB-, and obviously from a positive point of view,'' he said. `` The situation is much better, it is more comfortable,'' he said. But foreign debt remains a problem because of the hefty amount of interest <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> must pay its creditors. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> paid $ 8 billion to $ 9 billion in interest on its debt last year, second-highest in the developing world after <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gurria </PERSON> talked to foreign reporters late Tuesday on the condition that his remarks not be released as a matter of `` courtesy'' before he spoke to a panel of the Mexican legislature on Wednesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> official said <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> officials were pleased with the concept of the program to erase some of its foreign debt by exchanging old loans for special U.S.-backed bonds. But he acknowledged February's auction of the bonds had not lived up to expectations. The operation was `` smaller than what we had expected, certainly smaller than what we had wanted,'' <PERSON> Gurria </PERSON> said. The program involves exchanging some of the debt <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> owes foreign commercial bankers for new, 20-year-old bonds issued by the Mexican government. The bonds are backed by special <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities and carry a higher interest rate than <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is paying on the old debt. During the Feb. 26 auction, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> received bids from 139 banks in 18 countries but rejected 45 percent of the bids. The bids that were accepted will result in retiring $ 3.66 billion in debt at an average discount of 69.77 cents on the dollar, offering $ 2.56 billion worth of bonds in exchange. That sale will reduce the Mexican debt by $ 1.1 billion, a small amount in comparison with the total oustanding credit. But the cancellation of debt will mean savings of $ 1.5 billion in interest charges over the next 20 years, the government said. <PERSON> Gurria </PERSON> said officials were pleased with the discount on the loans. Mexican debt has been selling for about 50 cents on the dollar in the secondary market. In his remarks to foreign reporters and the legislature, he emphasized <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s desire to erase some of its foreign debt, while capturing more new money to use in developing the economy. `` The balance is difficult to achieve and the final objective even more so: to reduce the burden of the debt without closing off to the country doors to possible support that will be required in the future,'' he said in remarks released by the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
