<HEAD>Dollar Higher Following Wednesday's Rally, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar was higher in early European trading today, still boosted by a report that finance ministers of the seven major industrialized nations will set a floor for the American currency at a meeting next week. Gold prices were lower but steady following Wednesday's falls. Dealers said foreign exchange markets had calmed down considerably following the dollar's frantic rally Wednesday after the Japanese report that the so-called <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> would set a bottom rate for the dollar of 125 yen. Although traders said they doubted the group has set a specific minimum for the dollar, the market appeared to be reluctant to sell dollars before the meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> next Wednesday. `` Until the Group of Seven meeting, it probably wo n't go any lower,'' one dealer at a European bank in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> said. While the group may not have specific targets, one trader in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> said, `` it is clearly the intention of the central banks, especially of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, to maintain the dollar stable in order to avoid a negative impact on the stock market.'' In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar rose 0.67 yen to a closing 125.70 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted fractionally higher at 125.85 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's rates, included: 1.6787 West German marks, up from 1.6700; 1.3890 Swiss francs, up from 1.3775; 5.6975 French francs, up from 5.6570; 1.88325 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8720; 1,244.50 Italian lire, up from 1,236.50; and 1.2445 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2401 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar also gained against the British pound. It cost $ 1.8685 to buy one pound, cheaper than $ 1.8790 late Wednesday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 446.60 a troy ounce and at midmorning the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 446.25, both down from Wednesday's late bid of $ 449.50. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 446.40, down from $ 449.50 late Wednesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 5.56 to close at a bid $ 447.65. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 6.45 a troy ounce, down from late Wednesday's $ 6.57.
