<HEAD>Nikkei Index Hits All-Time High, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices surpassed their pre-crash best levels and reached an all-time high today in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, while the dollar gained ground against the Japanese yen. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, which gained 195.82 points Wednesday, gained another 258.05 points, or 0.97 percent, closing the day at 26,769.22. The overnight surge in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> helped release bullish sentiment pent up for several days because of concern over how Wall Street would fare if the dollar fell further or <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates rose, traders said. The Nikkei average close today was more than 100 points above the previous high recorded just before the worldwide stock market crash last Oct. 14, when it closed at 26,646.43. `` Share prices rose almost across the board,'' said <PERSON> Yoshio </PERSON> <PERSON> Shimoyama </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. The key market barometers regaining their pre-crash levels indicated the strong fundamentals of the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> market, he said. Prominent among gainers were electricals and automobiles. Financials were also firm. Volume of the first section trade was a heavy 1.6 billion shares. Meanwhile, the dollar closed the day at 125.70, the day's high, up 0.67 yen from its close of 125.03 yen Wednesday. It had opened the day at 125.60 yen and ranged between 125.40 and 125.70 yen. `` Trading was mixed in dollar-buying and selling, but the market was generally quiet,'' said an exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, who spoke on condition of anonymity. He attributed the quietness to participants sidestepping the market in advance of the meeting of seven major monetary nations in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> next week.
