<HEAD>Convicted Tycoon Launches Program to Aid Homeless</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH1</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf, `While the ...,' with 2 grafs to add
background on Kellner's motion. Picks up in 5th graf pvs, `At a ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Millionaire industrialist <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>, sentenced for tax fraud to create a $ 3 million project to aid the homeless, insists he wants to go ahead with the plan despite the objections of a federal prosecutor. <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>, 69, faced what could have been up to a 40-year prison term after pleading no contest to inflating that value of land donated to a college in order to deduct it from his tax return. Instead, the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> financier was ordered to set up the $ 3 million project to aid the homeless and pay $ 4 million in back taxes, interest, fines and court costs. While the $ 4 million part of <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>'s sentence wo n't be changed, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON>, who did not prosecute <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>, has argued the sentence gives the appearance that the wealthy can buy their liberty. <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON> said in his motion he was `` duty-bound to call to this court's attention the fact that this court does not have the power to order a criminal defendant to make charitable contributions as a condition of probation.'' At a hearing Wednesday, Judge <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Spellman </PERSON> required the 69-year-old <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> to state under oath that he did not wish the sentence set aside and that he was going ahead with the plan `` freely and voluntarily.'' <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> and a 10-member blue ribbon committee met Wednesday in <PERSON> Spellman </PERSON>'s courtroom to discuss the first stage of the program, a study of the homeless in south <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. `` Since February, I have been studying and learning about the problems of the homeless both nationally and in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> said in a brief statement. `` All the studies in the world will not help one homeless person. I will come to you with what will solve the problem.'' <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, must formally reply within 30 days to <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON>'s motion, which was filed Monday, <PERSON> Spellman </PERSON> said. The initial study will include a six-part census of south <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s homeless; an examination of subpopulations such as alcoholics, the mentally ill and families with children; and a review of how government policy affected the problem and what services are available to the homeless in each community. <PERSON> Spellman </PERSON> said he did n't plan to take an active role in the committee's deliberations but suggested that the initial study not use more than $ 500,000 of <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>'s donation. Findings are scheduled to be available by May 16, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Fike </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Barry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, which was chosen by <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> to administer the study because of its social work program. Sister <PERSON> Jeanne </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Loughlin </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Barry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, praised the tycoon's ideas and said she hoped that <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>'s donation would be the nucleus of a program that might grow to $ 300 million. `` He has a very fast mind,'' she said. `` He's creating solutions even before we give him all the data.''
