<HEAD>Taiwan's March Trade Surplus Lowest Since January 1983</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> registered a trade surplus of $ 163 million in March, the lowest monthly surplus in six years, the government reported Thursday. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the island's largest trading partner, totaled $ 298 million in March, down sharply from $ 1.27 billion a year earlier, the government said. The monthly surplus was down sharply from $ 994 million in February, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Directorate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, Accounting and Statistics. Exports totaled $ 4.51 billion, up 10.9 percent from March last year, while imports amounted to $ 4.35 billion, up 67.6 percent, the report said. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s monthly surplus has not been that low since April 1982, when it was $ 60 million. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in January replaced <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> as the country sending the most goods to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports reaching $ 1.3 billion in March, up 152 percent from a year earlier. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> equaled $ 1.6 billion, down 10.5 percent, the report said Trade officials attributed the surplus decline to tariff reductions on 3,500 items and the 39 percent appreciation of the <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> dollar against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar since January 1986, which has made American products less expensive here. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> has been under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pressure to reduce its massive bilateral trade surplus, which totaled a record $ 16 billion last year, the third largest surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> after those of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s trade deficit with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, its second largest trading partner, totaled $ 601 million in March, up 27 percent from the same month last year.
