<HEAD>Mercantile Exchange Votes To Implement An S&amp;P Opening Limit of
Five Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Board of Governors of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> voted Wednesday to implement an opening limit of five points in the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P 500 futures contract, officials said. The opening limit was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> last week and will be effective April 19. It isdesigned to coordinate any imbalance which may occur at the opening of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The opening limit was one of a series of proposals the exchange made to the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> in early February designed to address concerns raised by the <ORGANIZATION> Brady </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that investigated the stock market crash. The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> is the first exchange to implement daily price limits on its stock index contract. Traders and market users will be briefed on the opening limit before its implementation. The new rule specifies that there will be no trading at a price more than five index points above or below the previous day's settlement price If triggered on the opening, the five-point limit will remain in effect for the first 10 minutes of scheduled trading or until the contract trades off the five-point limit, whichever happens first. After 10 minutes or if the contract trades off the limit, the regular daily limit of 15 index points becomes effective.
