<HEAD>UAW Members Still Wrangling Over Chrysler Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> members moved closer to wrapping up demands for mid-April <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> contract talks, but continued wrangling internally over whether to extend the contract's protections to some former <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> workers. About 140 delegates from 49 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> local unions approved contract proposals Wednesday that closely mirror economic and job-protecting provisions in contracts signed last fall with <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The union's main strategy in talks set to open April 18 is to return to uniform bargaining with the Big Three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers by imposing the Ford-GM pattern contract on <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> and by limiting the contract to two years so that all three contracts expire together in 1990. `` We've had a pattern settlement before us now for almost a year. ... It should not take a long time for us to put this together,'' <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> said of the coming negotiations after addressing the delegates. The strategy prevents the union from seeking to win <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s 59,500 active and 8,000 laid-off workers any significant improvement on the GM-Ford pattern in this year's talks But it will strengthen the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s bargaining power in 1990, when its members' jobs will be further threatened by as many as eight Japanese-owned <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories capable of building up to 2.5 million vehicles a year. The decision against asking for pay raises breaking the <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> pattern angered some <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> bargainers. `` We're stuck with something that was negotiated with <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> <PERSON> Betts </PERSON>, unit chairman of Local 573 of the Office and Clerical Workers, told The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. `` We're not getting any raises, and the membership does n't want it.'' Like the <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> contracts, the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> proposals would give workers yearly bonuses equal to 3 percent of their annual wages, forbid plant closings and prevent layoffs for any reason except a drop in sales. But unlike the two earlier pacts, the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> proposal also would forbid sale of plants or operations during the life of the contract, an attempt to force <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> to back further away from plans to sell its 28,000-worker <ORGANIZATION> Acustar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> parts subsidiary. The council was scheduled to finish approving demands today and to vote on whether to include nearly 1,000 former <ORGANIZATION> AMC </ORGANIZATION> workers at an engine and stamping plant in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, under the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> contract or to leave them to bargain for themselves, as they did before <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> bought <ORGANIZATION> AMC </ORGANIZATION> last August.
