<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> officially ended a year under bankruptcy court protection today, completing its epic legal fight with <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> but facing continued pressure from dissident shareholders and takeover strategists. Under a reorganization plan approved March 23 by a federal bankruptcy court judge, the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, N.Y.-based oil giant transferred $ 3 billion to a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> bank account in <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>'s name today. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> also will begin making another $ 2.6 billion in payments to its other creditors. The four wire transfers to <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> began at 10:03 a.m. CST today and took 10 minutes to complete, officials at the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> said. In exchange for the $ 3 billion, <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> will drop its claim to a $ 10.3 billion judgment against <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> that Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> was holding when <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> filed for Chapter 11 protection from its creditors on last April 12. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> said it took that action to avoid having to post a potentially ruinous multibillion-dollar security bond while appealing the judgment awarded <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> by a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> jury in November 1985. The jury found <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> had improperly interfered with a January 1984 <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> acquisition of part of <ORGANIZATION> Getty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, then bought all of <PERSON> Getty </PERSON> itself. Following <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Court Judge <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartzberg </PERSON>'s approval of the plan _ worked out in December by the two companies and committees representing <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> creditors and shareholders _ <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> borrowed $ 2.7 billion from a consortium of banks The loan was to be repaid today once the $ 3 billion is deposited in <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>'s account at <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Wednesday. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>, another <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said today that no company celebration was planned to mark the occasion, but he added he was glad to see the case finally end. `` It's obviously been a very protracted affair,'' <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> said. `` I think it is important that all the parties concerned move into the mainstream of what we really do best, and that's run our companies.'' The money <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> borrowed has been invested in short-term securities such as government securities and high-grade corporate bonds, <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> borrowed the money before actually getting the cash so the company could invest it `` in an orderly manner.'' <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> said he does not expect any immediate major investments by <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>. `` Our board really wants to take a look at all the options out there,'' he said. `` We've been looking at various opportunities. Our board will meet in early June to assess various possibilities.'' Officials of both companies have said they chose to settle the matter so they could get back to their businesses without the prospect of endless litigation. Takeover strategist <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, who holds 14.8 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s stock and is its largest shareholder, last week filed an appeal of the reorganization plan objecting to certain financial conditions and provisions giving legal releases to <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> officials. But <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> stressed he never opposed the plan as a whole. `` I'm glad they came out of bankruptcy, and did not want to stand in the way of that event,'' he said in an interview Wednesday. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> added that he thought it was `` wrong that shareholders were forced to give releases to those involved -LRB- in the Getty Oil acquisition -RRB- without having to vote on the releases separately.'' His objection _ joined by other shareholders _ has been that <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> was throwing away a chance to recoup some of its losses by suing the people who were responsible. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> also opposed a default provision of a loan <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> will use to help fund the reorganization. Under a provision of <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s agreement with a consortium of about 25 banks providing up to $ 3 billion in credit, the loans would be callable, on a vote by two-thirds of the banks, if control of the company changed hands. Attorneys representing <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> and some shareholders criticized the indemnity and change-of-control provisions as devices for entrenching <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s management. But <PERSON> Schwartzberg </PERSON>, in approving the plan, cited contentions by <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> that the indemnities were necessary to end the litigation. He also cited testimony that the banks insisted on the change-of-control provision as a requirement for granting <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> the $ 3 billion loan.
