<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has imposed fishing sanctions against <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in reprisal for alleged violations of an international whale conservation accord. In a letter to <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> found that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has been granting permits allowing the killing of its minke whales in the Antarctic for research purposes. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, an official from the <ORGANIZATION> Japanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said his government would seek to lift the sanctions through discussions with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities. He said that the issue of fishing rights in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> waters had nothing to do with the whaling accord. `` The feeling is that we've been hit through some irrelevant issue,'' he said. Invoking the Magnuson Fishery Conservation and Management Act and the Fishermen's Protective Act of 1967, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> ordered the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to withhold 100 percent of the fishing privileges that would otherwise be available to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in an exclusive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fishing zone. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> affiliate of the World Wildlife Fund, said Wednesday the announced fishing sanctions would hurt the Japanese to a degree. But he said the punitive measures come too late to save any of the 300 minke whales that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> plans to take in this year's research program. In his letter to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> had been granting the whale-killing permits despite a 1987 <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Whaling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> resolution against this practice. That resolution recommended that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> refrain from issuing further permits `` until uncertainties in their scientific research proposals were resolved.'' The president's letter said the commission adopted a second resolution since the finding of non-compliance by <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Verity </PERSON>, in which the panel again recommended that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> discontinue the practice. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he had no evidence that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> `` is bringing its whaling activities into conformance'' with the whaling commission recommendations. He said that because of this, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government would deny <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s request to fish for 3,000 metric tons of sea snails and 5,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> whiting. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also told <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> will be `` barred from any future allocations of fishing privileges for any other species, including <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> cod, until the secretary of commerce determines that the situation has been corrected.'' He called the sanctions `` the strongest possible'' under existing law. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, however, stopped short of moving against Japanese fish products imported into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, saying the steps he took represented the `` most effective means of encouraging <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to embrace the <ORGANIZATION> IWC </ORGANIZATION> conservation program.''
