<HEAD>Group Plans to Breed Alligators in Spain for Meat and Skin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Danish investment group plans to set up <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s first alligator farm in southern <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> to produce skins and meat for export, the project's organizer said Thursday. `` The baby alligators would come from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and be bred at the farm in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, but it would take three to four years before production and export of the reptiles' skin and meat could begin,'' said <PERSON> Leif </PERSON> <PERSON> Skovgaard </PERSON> in a telephone interview with the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Skovgaard </PERSON>, a chartered accountant who is organizing the project for a group of seven Danish investors, said 10,000 to 12,000 alligators would be bred yearly at a farm near the town of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Roque </LOCATION>. European Alligator Institue, as the project is called, is seeking financial support from local and state governments in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> as well as the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. The farm, which the group hopes to open by the beginning of 1989, would employ about 100 people, <PERSON> Skovgaard </PERSON> said. `` As alligators are dangerous at any age, our personnel will be specially trained to cope with them so they do n't lose fingers,'' he added. The investors hope to develop a nature park where visitors can observe the animals, which can grow to 15 feet in length, in an outdoor environment. Alligator meat, according to Skovgaard, tastes like something between veal and chicken, and is popular in American, British and French fish restaurants. The skins are used for shoes, handbags and other leather assessories. <PERSON> Skovgaard </PERSON> said he did not anticipate protests from animal protection or environmental groups. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> banned hunting alligators because the species was disappearing. but the ban was lifted recently after the alligators made a strong comeback.
