<HEAD>Former Reuters, Times of London Chairman Dead at 69</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sir <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, a former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> news agency and a leading figure in the British newspaper industry, died Thursday at the age of 69. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, onetime editor-in-chief of <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, which includes the Times of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, died at his home in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> after a long illness. The cause of death was not given. He introduced the color magazine supplement, now a feature of all the big national weekly newpapers, into British journalism. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, also a onetime chairman of the British Museum and recipient of a knighthood in 1976, began his career as a cub reporter on the <ORGANIZATION> Middlesbrough </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION> in northern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> in 1936. An influential figure in British newspapers for more than four decades, <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> was also the first president from 1978 until 1983 of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, an organization of more than 200 editors and publishers. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> was chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> from 1979 to 1985 during the British-based agency's expansion of its financial news services. After a meteoric career in newspapers in northern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and a distinguished military record during World War II, <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> at 28 became personal assistant to newspaper proprietor <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemsley </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> became editor of the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Sunday Times, weekly companion of the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION>, when Canadian Lord <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> bought the newspapers in 1959, as well as editorial director of the group. As chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> battled production unions over computer technology and staff cutbacks. It culminated in a year-long strike which closed the newspapers in 1978. In 1981, they were bought by publisher <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON>. He is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Olive </PERSON>, and four sons.
