<HEAD>Unions Battle Back Against Lorenzo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Buoyed by favorable court decisions and growing political support, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' labor leaders say they believe they've got the momentum in the battle to save the financially troubled carrier. `` There's a new sense that the right people are finally listening to what we're saying,'' said <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of mammoth <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` It's very heartening to a lot of employees,'' <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said. `` Up until not long ago, everyone thought -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> chairman -RRB- <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> was unbeatable.'' `` I have felt a lot of confidence all along that we were gaining momentum, that we were going to get justice,'' added <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, veteran leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, which represents 12,000 maintenance and ground workers in a company with 33,000 employees. `` <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> was just arrogant ... thumbing his nose at justice. We've been able to hold the resistance movement together very effectively.'' Speaking in his union office less than five miles from the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> offices of the Contra rebels _ the <LOCATION> Nicaraguan </LOCATION> resistance _ <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> smiled as he realized his description of the unions as `` the resistance movement.'' `` We're an occupied country right now,'' said <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, 54, a 32-year veteran of Eastern. `` It's our airline, we built it up. But we've been invaded.'' Eastern management officials declined to be interviewed about the recent developments. Spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said the situation was too uncertain to speculate. But he said the unions have exaggerated the significance of court rulings and added that management still considers reducing labor costs crucial to salvaging the carrier, which has lost $ 900 million in the past 10 years. `` It still comes down to this: ` Do you pay baggage handlers $ 47,000 a year?''' <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> declared March 10 that Eastern was in contempt of court for trying to sell its profitable <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> shuttle to another unit of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>. Earlier this week, <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> said he has accepted a report from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> officials that the airline no longer planned to sell off the shuttle and would not find them in contempt if they follow through with that pledge. On March 28, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Barrington </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, also in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, granted a preliminary injunction sought by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilots which would prevent Eastern from using its planes to train pilots from <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>. Eastern management hoped to use the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> cargo line to fly Eastern routes in case of a strike. The rulings were crucial to halting what the unions believe are two major pushes by <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, who began taking over Eastern two years ago following his successful takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and has since swallowed up <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> and other small carriers. Stymied by <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> unions in 1983, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> shut the airline down, took it into federal bankruptcy reorganization, got union contracts voided, and emerged with a low-cost carrier. The <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> injunction halted the `` spin-off'' of the shuttle, which the labor leaders see as part of a strategy by <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> to cannibalize <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s assets. The Eastern reservations system was bought by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> last year, and planes and gates have also been sold off. The Parker injunction against training <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> pilots sets back <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s strike contingency program. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> warned machinists last December, when labor talks deadlocked, to be ready for a management-provoked strike that he said was aimed at crushing the union. But the federal mediator sent in for the talks has so far declined to classify the talks `` at an impasse.'' If he makes that declaration, a 30-day cooling off period must follow. The unions, in a national election year, have rallied political support. Democratic presidential candidates <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> criticized <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> management during February campaign appearances here. Congressional hearings have been held into Eastern safety practices and some congressmen are calling for a federal probe into the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> takeover. A report by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> should correct `` deeply rooted and pervasive problems'' before gaining <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> permission to fly Eastern planes. Other unions have joined <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> employees in `` Jobs for Justice'' rallies on the Capitol steps and other locations. `` The attitude in other unions is if <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s model for destroying unions is successful, it may well spill over. It threatens most unions,'' <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> said. The unions have numerous court cases, including lawsuits from fired employees and hundreds of pending grievances. The Machinists filed a new federal suit March 31 in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> charging <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and other defendants with systematically violating federal securities and labor laws. More than a year ago, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> management called for a 30 percent reduction, or $ 490 million, in labor costs. Union leaders responded that <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> employees have made concessions for years and are tired of paying for bad management. The employees say they want to buy <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and run the airline themselves. `` Eastern has everything it needs to be a success: an established name; dedicated professional employees, good routes, major airports. We could make it the airline it should be,'' said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Currier </PERSON>, a vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> flight attendants local. Takeover strategist <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </