<HEAD>Denver Chosen As Test Market For Fast Food, Gasoline Venture</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Suanne is cq in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For the next 18 months, those in a hurry here can fuel up their cars and themselves in one stop in what's believed to be the nation's first combination fast food, gasoline outlet. The city was chosen as the test market for an 18-month joint venture, which began Thursday, by Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Burger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` Basically, we're both in the energy industry,'' said <PERSON> Suanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Map </PERSON>, a Burger King spokeswoman in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. `` <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> provides food for the car and we provide the food for the body.'' <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> Knake </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> marketing specialist, said both companies' clientele are similar `` Our typical customer is between 18 and 49. So that means our customers will match up pretty well with <PERSON> Burger </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s customers,'' he said. `` And the typical <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> and Burger King customer wants speed. They want to save time.'' <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION>'s end of the operation consists of four pump islands, a security booth and a cashier. The Burger King restaurant sits at the rear of a 150-foot lot and consists of a drive-through and walkup window but no sit-down service. Burger King customers can use their <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> credit card to pay for food. <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> first approached Burger King in early 1986 with the idea, <PERSON> Knake </PERSON> said. He said the operation will be evaluated during the next 18 months. `` There are no plans to roll it out, because we do n't know how it's going to work,'' he said. `` We're going to have to evaluate it.''
