<HEAD>Japanese Investment In U.S. Real Estate To Remain Strong, Bank
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Japanese appetite for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> real estate is expected to remain strong this year but may not exceed the $ 6 billion they invested last year, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. `` At minimum, we expect Japanese investment to be equal to or slightly below 1987 levels,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, managing director of the bank's <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Real </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. The Japanese remain concerned about volatility in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stock market as well as the nation's huge trade and budget deficits. But <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said in a statement that if there is improvement in `` the global economic and political issues that are causing'' those concerns, the amount invested in this country could be substantially higher than last year. Investment will continued to be focused on the west and east coasts, but the Japanese increasingly are looking beyond the major cities for opportunities. Among the new spots to draw attention are: _ <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> More than 150 Japanese companies have established subisidiaries in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, and that will serve as a magnet for more Japanese investment. _ <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Tenn </PERSON> The bank cites <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> officials as saying about 10,000 workers are employed by Japanese firms within the state. As in the case of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, that is likely to lead to additional real estate investment there. _ <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, Ore The city is becoming `` an increasingly well-known market in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'' largely because of its own promotion efforts, the bank noted. _ <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> noted that this city is particularly convenient because of simple airline connections to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Investors are likely to be attracted by its port and diverse economy. _ <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> Physical limitation of the city's growth, because of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, the Mexican border and the desert, increase the potential for strong real estate appreciation, the bank said. _ <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> Japanese recognize the city's growing demand for offices, housing and shopping centers, the bank said _ <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. Japanese investors are likely to turn to this city as an alternative to the higher-priced <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> markets, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> _ <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> Continued population growth of this city has maintained a need for apartments and shopping centers.
