<FIRST>r f AM-TWA-Hughes     04-07 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-TWA-Hughes,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delaware Supreme Court Upholds TWA Against Howard Hughes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has upheld damages and interest awarded to <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> in a 25-year legal battle with the late <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> and his <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tool </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. In a ruling dated April 4, the state's highest court upheld an award of more than $ 48.3 million in damages plus interest against the <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tool </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, also known as <PERSON> Toolco </PERSON>. A Chancery Court in January last year awarded <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> more than $ 17.2 million plus pre-judgment interest of about $ 31.1 million. Post judgment interest was allowed only on the damage award. <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> filed the lawsuit in 1962, claiming the defendants had breached their fiduciary duty of loyalty by deliberately interfering with <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s commercial success to benefit themselves. At that time, <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> owned 78 percent of <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> stock. According to the ruling, <ORGANIZATION> Toolco </ORGANIZATION> used its control position to <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s detriment. It said that because of <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>' evasive nature, <PERSON> Toolco </PERSON> was slow to order jets <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> needed to remain competitive. <PERSON> Toolco </PERSON> appealed to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> filed a cross appeal. <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> sought to have post-judgment interest calculated on both the damage award and pre-judgment interest. The state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said the claim was without merit because <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> courts `` have traditionally disfavored the practice of compounding interest, and we see no reason to depart from that rule here.'' <PERSON> Toolco </PERSON> appealed on four issues, including a clain it did not breach its fiduciary duty to <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> through its failure to place an earlier order for <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> jets. <PERSON> Toolco </PERSON> claimed <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> did not need that type of jet. <PERSON> Toolco </PERSON> contended it should not be held accountable for <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s lost profits due to <PERSON> Toolco </PERSON>'s failure to order such aircraft. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> held that <PERSON> Toolco </PERSON>'s argument `` ignores the fact that the intrinsic fairness test placed the burden upon <PERSON> Toolco </PERSON> to prove that it was not the cause of <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s lost profits,'' and <PERSON> Toolco </PERSON> failed to meet that burden. <PERSON> Toolco </PERSON> also disputed the inclusion of accounting changes made by <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> in late 1963 in calculating damages. The ruling said, however, that `` there was no error or abuse of discretion'' by including the accounting changes in calculating the damages through 1963. In its final argument, <PERSON> Toolco </PERSON> claimed it was erroneous to use an interest rate in excess of the legal rate in calculating the pre-judgment interest. But the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> noted that <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is a court of equity and `` has broad discretion, subject to principles of fairness, in fixing the rate to be applied.'' In <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, the `` legal rate is a mere guide, not an inflexible rule,'' the ruling said. `` In selecting the interest rate the trial court considered the nature of the plaintiff, the nature of the wrong remedied, and the peculiar facts of the case. Each of those factors was appropriate, and there was no abuse of discretion in the court's choice of rate,'' the ruling said.
</TEXT>
