<HEAD>Stockbroker Charged in Guinness Affair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police charged <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayhew </PERSON>, a partner with British investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Cazenove </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, with three offenses related to <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>'s 1986 takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Distillers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mayhew </PERSON> was arrested Thursday and taken to a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> police station to answer questions about the Guinness affair and was later charged The first charge accuses him of inducing <ORGANIZATION> Distillers </ORGANIZATION> shareholders to dispose of their shares `` by dishonest concealment of a material fact,'' the police said. The second charge alleges unlawful financial assistance, and the third accuses him of involvement with an undisclosed party, which purchased <ORGANIZATION> Distillers </ORGANIZATION> shares in April 1986. <PERSON> Mayhew </PERSON>, who was released, is scheduled to appear in a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> magistrate's court on Friday to hear the charges. He is the seventh person to be charged by <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> police in connection with the Guinness affair. The other accused are former <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON>; <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Seelig </PERSON>, a former corporate finance director for <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grenfell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>; financier Sir <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON>; <ORGANIZATION> Heron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ronson </PERSON>; <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Spens </PERSON>, a former director of <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ansbacher </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>; and stockbroker <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> British police have also issued a warrant for the arrest of former <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer. <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> has admitted that its former management arranged for company outsiders to purchase the brewer's shares to boost their price in order to make <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION>' cash and stock offer for <ORGANIZATION> Distillers </ORGANIZATION> more attractive than a rival bid. Cazenove, which acted as <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION>' broker during the Distillers bid, reaffirmed on Thursday a 1987 statement in which Cazenove denied that any of its representatives broke the law or offered `` improper indemnities or inducements'' to purchase Distillers shares. Cazenove insisted on <PERSON> Mayhew </PERSON>'s innocence, saying he would remain a partner and would continue to have the firm's complete support.
