<FIRST>u f AM-Texaco-Pennzoil-Scene Bjt   04-07 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texaco-Pennzoil-Scene, Bjt,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>$3 Billion In 10 Minutes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Texaco-Pennzoil, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four years and two months after the start of an epic legal battle between two oil industry rivals, it took just 10 minutes Thursday for <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to deliver a $ 3 billion settlement into the bank account of <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. A half-dozen tight-lipped executives from <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank-Houston </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> huddled around a computer terminal in a sterile bank office, waiting like expectant parents for the green computer screen to signal the beginning of the largest cash settlement in the nation's judicial history `` I'll be glad when it's over,'' a tense <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Alderson </PERSON>, assistant treasurer of <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>, said. `` It'll be a relief.'' Bank officials warned about a dozen reporters and photographers before escorting them into Room 1760 of the bank's <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division-Funds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transfer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Section </ORGANIZATION> that the place was a high-security area and they would not be allowed to wander. Ironically, the bank is two blocks south of <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> headquarters and two blocks north of the downtown Texaco Building. <PERSON> Margo </PERSON> <PERSON> Somers </PERSON>, an operations officer at <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, repeatedly punched in the Pennzoil account number on her terminal to see if the Texaco money electronically appeared on the bank ledger. `` This is the largest one I've ever handled,'' she said. To get an idea of how much $ 3 billion really is, consider this: If you spent $ 1 every second, it would take 92 years to go through $ 3 billion. If comprised of $ 1 bills only, the stack would reach 203 miles high and weigh 3,061 tons, according to <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Polikoff </PERSON>, a spokesman at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s Bureau of Engraving and Printing. At <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which handled <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s end of the transaction from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Witkins </PERSON>, a senior vice president, gathered the cash from 26 or 27 banks using a task force of four people. `` It's not really the raw money itself, it's the sensitivity and the technicality,'' he said. `` You want the thing to shut out in one day. Three billion dollars works out to about a half a million dollars a day in interest. Money like that does n't sit around idle.'' At 10:03 a.m CDT, the first payment _ $ 600 million _ came in to <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. `` So far, so good,'' someone said. <PERSON> Alderson </PERSON> smiled faintly. <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> officials notified Manufacturers Hanover the payment had been received. Then they waited, eyes still glued to the computer screen. There was little small talk. The minutes dragged. A bank spokesman explained that the next wire transfer probably was hung up in the computer queue behind other business. Mrs. <PERSON> Somers </PERSON> typed in the Pennzoil account number again. Payment No. 2 arrived at 10:10 a.m. <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> had another $ 800 million. <PERSON> Alderson </PERSON> smiled a bit more. He and <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Condit </PERSON>, director of treasury operations for <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>, scribbled notes on legal pads. At 10:12 a.m., another $ 700 million appeared in the <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> account. <PERSON> Alderson </PERSON>'s smile grew. Just a minute later, at 10:13 a.m., the fourth and largest single payment _ $ 900 million _ arrived. `` There it is,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Somers </PERSON> said. `` It's all in.'' <PERSON> Alderson </PERSON> flashed a $ 3 billion grin. A few people began applauding. `` We're all very glad it's all over,'' <PERSON> Alderson </PERSON> said, accepting congratulations, but hurrying out of the room. `` Going to call the boss?'' a reporter asked. `` Exactly right,'' the assistant treasurer said. A few blocks away, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jamail </PERSON>, the colorful <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> attorney who headed the <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> legal team and stands to make millions from the case, was in court, trying another case. `` I do n't have any gloating feeling,'' he said. `` I'm just glad that the system of justice prevailed and we won. Now I hope they -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- quit crying about it.''
</TEXT>
