Report are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the
week ended Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Assets of the nation's 420 money market mutual funds fell $ 1.43 billion in the latest week, the <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. The decline, to $ 276.8 billion in the seven-day period ended Wednesday, followed a revised $ 548.3 million drop in the funds' assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund trade group The funds' assets hit a record high $ 280.02 billion in the week ended Feb. 24. The <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said that in the latest week, assets of 210 general purpose funds rose $ 781.7 million to $ 83.64 billion, assets of 98 broker-dealer funds increased $ 356.5 million to $ 117.4 billion, and assets of 112 institutional funds declined $ 2.57 billion to $ 75.76 billion. The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in the week ended Tuesday to 6.05 percent from 6.04 percent the previous week, according to <PERSON> Donoghue </PERSON>'s Money Fund Report, a trade journal based in <LOCATION> Holliston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. The 30-day average yield was unchanged at 6.05 percent, <PERSON> Donoghue </PERSON>'s said. The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 42 days, down from 43 days, <PERSON> Donoghue </PERSON>'s said. Separately, the newsletter <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monitor </ORGANIZATION> said its survey of 100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield available on money market accounts fell to 5.68 percent as of Wednesday from 5.70 percent a week earlier. The <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW accounts, fell to 5.14 percent from 5.15 percent. Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 6.81 percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 6.78 the previous week. Yields were 7.14 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 7.12 percent; 7.56 percent on 2 -LCB- - year CDs, up from 7.53 percent; and 8.01 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 7.99 percent
