<SECOND>BC-Surfwear Bankruptcy,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surfwear Firm a Victim of Shifting Tides in Fashion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION> and Sons, the fast-growing maker of beachgoer garb, has found itself the victim of shifting tides of fashion. The Orange County-based surfwear company sought protection from creditors by filing for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in federal court on Tuesday, listing liabilities of $ 7.1 million and assets of $ 2.5 million. The company listed more than 200 creditors in court documents. `` We just needed the Chapter 11 to get over the cash-flow glitch that was created from the fall line not doing well,'' said the company's attorney, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lobel </PERSON>. `` Fortunately for us, the demand for <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION> and Sons clothing right now is extraordinary. The company's problem is ... finding the cash to buy the merchandise to fill the orders,'' <PERSON> Lobel </PERSON> said. Under Chapter 11 of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Code, a company is protected from creditors and permitted to continue operating and restructure itself under court supervision. The surfwear industry is fast-growing but highly volatile, made up mostly of tiny entrepreneurial companies. Sales industrywide this year are expected to be between $ 1 billion and $ 3 billion. <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION> and Sons is considered a leader in the industry even though its annual sales are only $ 12 million.
</TEXT>
