<FIRST>r f AM-Farmland-Foreign     04-07 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farmland-Foreign,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreigners Own Nearly 1 Percent of U.S. Agricultural Land</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreigners continue to own just under 1 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural land, slightly more than the level of a year ago, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. The department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said its 1987 year-end review of reports under the Agricultural Foreign Investment Disclosure Act found 12.5 million acres of agricultural land in foreign hands, 202,000 acres more than reported in 1986. Of the land owned by foreign interests, 50 percent was forest land, 17 percent cropland, 28 percent pasture and other agricultural land, and 5 percent used for non-agricultural purposes or unreported. Corporations held 80 percent of the foreign-owned land, with the balance held by individuals, partnerships, institutions and other entities. As in the past, much of the ownership is concentrated in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antilles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. Those countries combined to account for 69 percent of the foreign-held acreage, the agency said. <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> continued to have the heaviest concentration of foreign ownership, with holdings of almost 1.79 million acres, mostly timberland, or more than 14 percent of the total. `` Ninety-three percent of the foreign-owned acreage will remain in agricultural production, according to foreign owners,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
