<HEAD>Oil Futures Top $17 a Barrel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices put on a late rally and broke past $ 17 a barrel Thursday, with traders at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> looking ahead to a weekend <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> committee meeting on prices. On other markets, grain and soybean futures were mostly higher, livestock were mostly weaker, and precious metals were mixed. Most of the action in the energy markets was buying to offset earlier sales to square away accounts before the price committee meeting, said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> E.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Man </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` There's the general expectation that the price committee is n't going to do anything substantial,'' he said `` In fact, they have no power to do much of anything. `` But there's still some fear that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> could throw a curve ball'' and take meaningful steps to stabilize international oil prices, he said. Gasoline and heating oil futures also advanced, responding to firm demand and to the rally in crude oil, said <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON>. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 23 cents to 26 cents higher with the contract for delivery in May at $ 17.06 a barrel; heating oil was .39 cent to .71 cent higher with May at 45.73 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was .35 cent to .40 cent higher with May at 48.82 cents a gallon. Livestock futures were mostly lower, while pork bellies advanced at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. `` The cattle market is basically on the fence,'' said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. A recent bull market appears to have stalled because the profit margins of processors and retailers are very thin and they see larger supplies later in the spring, he said `` So they're not willing to commit themselves in a big way to feature or push beef.'' This means processors are resisting paying top dollar for live cattle, but at the same time there is no surplus of market-ready animals, so the producers are n't willing to drastically cut their prices. Pork futures are stymied by their high price compared with the cash market, <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> said. `` The premium -LRB- about $ 7 a hundredweight -RRB- is about as wide as it's been any time in the 1980s,'' he said. `` So before they can move ahead, futures need cash prices to catch up,'' said <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON>. Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .15 cent higher with the April contract at 73.82 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .20 cent lower with April at 79.57 cents a pound; live hogs were .45 cent lower to .27 cent higher with April at 45.35 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .08 cent to .40 cent higher with May at 53.32 cents a pound. Soybean futures prices put on a late rally and pulled corn a little higher at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. A large speculator who had driven prices up earlier in the week came into the market as a buyer again, said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. This forced traders, who had sold earlier in the hope of prices would decline, to start buying to limit their losses. Trading in the grains was relatively quiet. Corn was helped by the rally in beans while wheat has some underlying support from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> bidding on a half million tons of the grain and the expectation that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> may be interested in buying some. Wheat settled 2 -RCB- cents to 4 -LCB- cents higher with the May contract at $ 3.13 a bushel; corn was unchanged to 2 \ cents higher with May at $ 2.07 -LCB- a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1 -RCB- cents higher with May at $ 1.65 a bushel; and soybeans were 5 -RCB- cents to 7 \ cents higher with May at $ 6.73 a Gold futures moved higher while silver was a little lower at the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Gold settled $ 1.40 to $ 1.80 higher with the June contract at $ 452.70 a troy ounce; and silver was 3 cents lower with May at $ 6.435 a troy ounce. Stock index futures advanced on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the contract for June delivery of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 index contract settled .20 point higher at 267.60. The underlying spot index closed .67 point higher at 266.16.
</TEXT>
