<TEXT>
 Stock prices worked their way higher in an erratic session Thursday, getting a bit more mileage out of Wednesday's strong rally. As has been the case for much of the time this year, smaller stocks turned in a better showing than the big-name blue chips. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had gained 64.16 points Wednesday, edged up another 0.50 to 2,062.17. Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 9 to 5 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with 988 up, 541 down and 473 unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> volume came to 177.84 million shares, against 181.76 million in the previous session. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index rose .52 to 150.28. Over the past three days the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average has gained 81.47 points. Analysts said new signs of stability in the dollar had touched off rallies in stock markets around the world. The <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> stock market climbed Thursday to new highs, having recovered all the ground it lost in last year's crash. But the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bond market showed less life. Prices of long-term government bonds declined slightly, putting their yields in the 8.75-8 .8 percent range And brokers said many traders were reluctant to chase after stocks while talk persists that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> might be leaning toward a tighter credit policy, and that leading banks might soon raise their prime lending rates. Among Japanese stocks traded in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets, <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> gained 3 to 141; <ORGANIZATION> Matsushita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrical </ORGANIZATION> 3 -RCB- to 223 -RCB-; <ORGANIZATION