<HEAD>Lucky Stores Rejects Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Lucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has rejected a takeover bid by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> that could have created the nation's largest supermarket chain, officials announced Thursday Lucky's board said in a statement it had unanimously rejected <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>' unsolicited tender offer of $ 1.74 billion, or $ 45 a share, as `` inadequate'' and not in the best interests of the company or its stockholders. The board also rejected a proposal by the <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City-based </LOCATION> company to increase its bid to $ 50 a share in a negotiated acquisition. The rejection of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>' surprise tender offer three weeks ago for Lucky's 38.6 million shares outstanding occurred 17 months after the Dublin-based company derailed a hostile takeover attempt by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Asher </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Holt </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> vice president for investor public relations, said his company had no comment on the announcement. Lucky's stock closed at $ 52.50 per share on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Thursday, up $ 3.75 from Wednesday's $ 48.75 per-share close. Lucky's board also authorized company management and advisers to consider other alternatives to boost its value, including possible reorganization to focus on <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> operations, a leveraged recapitalization with possible distributions to stockholders by a dividend or share repurchase, and a negotiated sale of the company to a third party. `` We are confident that pursuit of one of these alternatives will provide our best opportunity to achieve greater value for our stockholders,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lillie </PERSON>, Lucky's chairman and chief executive officer. Lucky also announced its board adopted a warrant dividend plan and has declared a dividend under the plan of one common stock purchase right for each share of outstanding common stock, payable to stockholders of record on April 8. In its statement, <PERSON> Lucky </PERSON> said that its financial adviser, <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, advised the board the $ 45 tender offer and the $ 50 alternative were inadequate. <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, financial adviser to the non-management directors, also advised the board the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> proposal was financially inadequate, the company said. Lucky, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s No. 2 supermarket chain, has 480 outlets, 340 within the state. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, a grocery and drugstore chain, had indicated it would convert its struggling 240 Alpha Beta outlets in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to Lucky stores. If successful, the move would have transformed Lucky into <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s No. 1 grocery chain. A successful merger of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, with 1,700 outlets in 40 states, and Lucky would have make Lucky the nation's largest supermarket chain, surpassing No. 1 <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> last year posted $ 14.3 billion in annual sales; Lucky had $ 6.9 billion In 1984, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> acquired <ORGANIZATION> Jewel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, paving the way for an extensive consolidation aimed at creating the nation's first coast-to-coast drugstore chain.
